r]]\n! scope=\"col\" | [[Over (cricket)|Overs]]\n! scope=\"col\" | [[Over (cricket)|Maidens]]\n! scope=\"col\" | [[Run (cricket)|Runs]]\n! scope=\"col\" | [[Wicket]]s\n! scope=\"col\" | [[Economy rate (cricket)|Economy]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal; text-align: left;\" | [[Sophie Devine]] \n| 9 || 0 || 30 || 0 || 3.33\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal; text-align: left;\" | [[Kate Pulford]] \n| 3 || 0 || 17 || 0 || 5.66\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal; text-align: left;\" | [[Nicola Browne]] \n| 7 || 1 || 24 || 0 || 3.42\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal; text-align: left;\" | [[Suzie Bates]] \n| 4.1 || 0 || 21 || 0 || 5.04\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal; text-align: left;\" | [[Lucy Doolan]] \n| 10 || 4 || 23 || 3 || 2.30\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal; text-align: left;\" | [[Sarah Tsukigawa]] \n| 4 || 1 || 23 || 0 || 5.75\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal; text-align: left;\" | [[Aimee Watkins|Aimee Mason]] \n| 9 || 0 || 28 || 2 || 3.11\n|}\n\n'''Match officials'''\n* On-field [[umpire (cricket)|umpires]]: [[Steve Davis (umpire)|Steve Davis]] and [[Brian Jerling]]\n* [[Third umpire]]: [[Tyron Wijewardene]]\n* [[Match referee]]: [[Brian Aldridge (cricketer)|Brian Aldridge]]\n* [[Fourth umpire|Reserve umpire]]: [[Jeff Brookes]]\n\n'''Key'''\n* {{asterisk}} \u2013 [[Captain (cricket)|Captain]]\n* {{dagger}} \u2013 [[Wicket-keeper]]\n* c ''Fielder'' \u2013 Indicates that the batter was dismissed by a catch by the named [[Fielding (cricket)|fielder]]\n* b ''Bowler'' \u2013 Indicates which [[Bowling (cricket)|bowler]] gains credit for the dismissal\n* lbw \u2013 Indicates the batter was dismissed [[leg before wicket]]\n* st \u2013 Indicates the batter was [[stumped]]\n\n==Aftermath==\nThe ICC awarded England US$45,000 for their cup win, while New Zealand received $25,000.<ref name=\"tears\"/> Shaw, who had not expected to play, said after the match; \"I started the day crying, I finished it crying, but we won a World Cup in between\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2009/mar/23/women-england-cricket-world-cup |title=England win the World Cup |last=Booth |first=Lawrence |author-link=Lawrence Booth (cricket writer) |work=The Guardian |date=23 March 2009 |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> New Zealand's captain, Tiffen, reflected after the match, \"Maybe there were some nerves in amongst the camp. We didn't hype it up to be anything more than another day at the office, unfortunately it was a bad day at the office.\"<ref name=\"tears\"/> The team of the tournament included seven finalists: England's Edwards was selected as captain, and was joined by teammates Brunt, Marsh, Claire Taylor and Sarah Taylor. Bates and Pulford represented New Zealand in the team, while Devine was named as the team's twelfth woman. Claire Taylor, who finished the tournament as the leading run-scorer, was named as the player of the tournament.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wwc2009/content/story/396488.html |title=Five England players in World Cup XI |website=ESPNcricinfo |date=23 March 2009 |accessdate=9 April 2012}}</ref> The month after the final, Taylor became the first woman to be selected as one of [[Wisden Cricketers of the Year|''Wisden's'' Cricketers of the Year]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/cricket/international/england/5096209/Claire-Taylor-the-first-woman-to-be-named-among-the-Wisden-Cricketers-of-the-Year.html |title=Claire Taylor the first woman to be named among the Wisden Cricketers of the Year |last=Berry |first=Scyld |authorlink=Scyld Berry |work=The Daily Telegraph |publisher=Telegraph Media Group |location=London |date=3 April 2009 |accessdate=9 February 2015}}</ref> Both Taylor and Edwards were awarded [[Order of the British Empire|MBEs]] for their services to cricket; Edwards received hers in the [[2009 Birthday Honours]], while Taylor's came in the [[2010 New Year Honours]].<ref>{{cite book |title=Skirting the Boundary: A History of Women's Cricket |last=Duncan |first=Isabelle |year=2013 |publisher=[[The Robson Press]] |location=London |isbn=978-1-84954-546-4 |pages=151\u2013153}}</ref>\n\nThe England team flew back to the United Kingdom in [[economy class]]; Mitchell highlighted the contrast with the [[England cricket team|England men's team]], who \"fly business as standard\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/tms/2009/03/world_champions.shtml |title=World champions return home |last=Mitchell |first=Alison |author-link=Alison Mitchell |work=BBC Sport |date=24 March 2009 |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> They held a reception at Lord's in London upon their return, but the former [[Minister for Sport and Civil Society|sports minister]], [[Richard Caborn]], lamented the low-key celebrations, saying that \"I would have a Number 10 reception, a reception at the House of Commons, and, at the appropriate time, in the Lords.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2009/mar/25/england-womens-world-cup-winners |title=England women's cricket team bring back the cup \u2013 and the pride |last=Gibson |first=Owen |work=The Guardian |date=25 March 2009 |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> In her history of women's cricket, Rafaelle Nicholson was critical of some of the reporting on the final, saying that \"coverage increasingly appears to compare women's cricket with the men's game, and to treat the male version as 'real cricket'\".<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MkXOxAEACAAJ |title=Ladies and Lords: A History of Women's Cricket in Britain |last=Nicholson |first=Rafaelle |year=2019 |publisher=[[Peter Lang (publisher)|Peter Lang]] |isbn=978-1-78874-294-8 |page=loc. 7916 |nopp=true}}</ref> The English journalists Simon Wilde and [[Lawrence Booth (cricket writer)|Lawrence Booth]] credited the contracts introduced in 2008 as being critical to England's success.<ref name=\"wilde\"/><ref name=\"feet\">{{cite news |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/englands-women-have-the-world-at-their-feet-kwsx05xkrkc |title=England\u2019s women have the world at their feet: Team can complete a historic treble by winning the World Twenty20 final against New Zealand at Lord\u2019s today |last=Booth |first=Lawrence |authorlink=Lawrence Booth (cricket writer) |work=[[The Sunday Times]] |date=21 June 2009 |accessdate=21 April 2020 |url-access=subscription}}</ref> Booth highlighted the contrast with New Zealand's captain, Tiffin, who had retired after the World Cup, claiming: \"If I was paid properly, I'd still be playing.\"<ref name=\"feet\"/>\n\nThe two sides met again three months later to contest the final of the [[2009 ICC Women's World Twenty20|2009 Women's World Twenty20]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wwt202009/engine/match/355990.html |title=Final: England Women v New Zealand Women at Lord's, Jun 21, 2009 |website=ESPNcricinfo |date=9 April 2012}}</ref> England once again won the contest, and in doing so became the first team of either gender to be champions in all three cricketing formats: [[Women's Test cricket|Test]], [[Women's One Day International|One Day International]] and [[Women's Twenty20 International|Twenty20]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wwt202009/content/story/409994.html |title=All-conquering England take title |last=Narayanan |first=Nishi |website=ESPNcricinfo |date=21 June 2009 |accessdate=9 April 2012}}</ref> Each of the top four in the 2009 tournament automatically qualified for the [[2013 Women's Cricket World Cup]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.rediff.com/cricket/report/kiwi-bates-does-a-sehwag-world-cup/20090319.htm |title=Kiwi Bates does a Sehwag in World Cup |work=[[Rediff.com]] |date=19 March 2009 |accessdate=9 February 2015}}</ref> Neither England nor New Zealand reached the final of that tournament, but instead met in the third-place playoff, which England won by four wickets.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://sports.ndtv.com/icc-womens-world-cup/news/203626-charlotte-edwards-guides-england-to-third-spot-in-womens-world-cup |title=Charlotte Edwards guides England to third spot in Women's World Cup |agency=Press Trust of India |publisher=[[NDTV]] |date=15 February 2013 |accessdate=9 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Women's Cricket World Cup}}\n{{2009 Women's Cricket World Cup}}\n{{England women's cricket team}}\n{{New Zealand women's national cricket team}}\n{{Good article}}\n\n[[Category:2008\u201309 Australian women's cricket season|World Cup]]\n[[Category:2009 in English women's cricket|World Cup]]\n[[Category:2009 in New Zealand cricket|World Cup]]\n[[Category:2009 in New Zealand women's sport|cricket]]\n[[Category:2009 Women's Cricket World Cup|!]]\n[[Category:England women's national cricket team matches|World Cup 2009]]\n[[Category:New Zealand women's national cricket team matches|World Cup 2009]]\n[[Category:Women's Cricket World Cup finals]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox limited overs final\n| title                   = 2009 Women's Cricket World Cup Final\n| image                   = File:ENGLAND CRICKET TEAM (3385718581).jpg\n| caption                 = The England team celebrating a win earlier in the tournament.\n| event                   = {{nobr|[[2009 Women's Cricket World Cup]]}}\n| team1                   = [[New Zealand women's national cricket team|New Zealand]]\n| team1flag               = {{flagicon|New Zealand|size=30px}}\n| team1score              = 166\n| team1overs              = 47.2 overs\n| team2                   = [[England women's cricket team|England]]\n| team2flag               = {{flagicon|England|size=30px}}\n| team2score              = 167/6\n| team2overs              = 46.1 overs\n| details                 = England won by four wickets\n| date                    = 22 March 2009\n| stadium                 = [[North Sydney Oval]]\n| attendance              = 2,300\n| city                    = [[Sydney]]\n| man_of_the_match        = [[Nicky Shaw]] (England)\n| umpires                 = [[Steve Davis (umpire)|Steve Davis]] and [[Brian Jerling]]\n| previous                = [[2005 Women's Cricket World Cup Final|2005]]\n| next                    = [[2013 Women's Cricket World Cup Final|2013]]\n}}\nThe '''2009 Women's Cricket World Cup Final''' was a [[Women's One Day International]] cricket match between the [[England women's cricket team]] and the [[New Zealand women's national cricket team]], played on 22 March 2009 at the [[North Sydney Oval]] in Australia. It was the culmination of the [[2009 Women's Cricket World Cup]], the ninth edition of [[Women's Cricket World Cup|the tournament]]. England won the final by four [[Wicket#Winning by number of wickets|wickets]], clinching their third World Cup title and their first outside England. It was the second time that the two teams had met at this stage of a World Cup \u2013 England won their previous final contest in 1993.\n\nBoth teams were unbeaten in the first group stage. In the second, known as the Super Sixes, New Zealand and England finished first and second to qualify directly for the final; New Zealand had only lost to England, while England had already guaranteed their place in the final when they lost their last match to Australia. England were considered the favourites for the final. The New Zealand [[Captain (cricket)|captain]], [[Haidee Tiffen]], won the [[Toss (cricket)|toss]], and opted to [[Batting (cricket)|bat]] first. Her side were [[bowled out]] for 166 [[Run (cricket)|runs]]. The [[all-rounder]] [[Lucy Doolan]], batting at [[Batting order (cricket)|number nine]], was the highest scorer for New Zealand with 48. [[Nicky Shaw]], one of England's bowlers, took a career-best four wickets for 34 runs. In their response, England built an opening [[Partnership (cricket)|partnership]] of 74 runs and continued to score steadily. Despite regularly losing wickets, they reached the winning total with 23 [[Delivery (cricket)|balls]] to spare, earning England their first World Cup title for 16 years. Shaw, who had initially not been included in the England team, was named [[Player of the Match awards (cricket)|player of the match]] having replaced the injured [[Jenny Gunn]] just minutes before the game started.\n\n==Background==\nThe [[2009 Women's Cricket World Cup]] was the ninth edition of [[Women's Cricket World Cup|the tournament]], and the first to be organised by the [[International Cricket Council]] (ICC).<ref>{{cite web |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090802230336/http://icc-cricket.yahoo.net/the-icc/pepsi_icc_development_programme/woman_cricket.php |title=Women's Cricket |publisher=[[International Cricket Council]] (ICC) |url=http://icc-cricket.yahoo.net/the-icc/pepsi_icc_development_programme/woman_cricket.php |url-status=dead |archivedate=2 August 2009 |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref>{{efn|The ICC took over administration of the women's game in 2005, when it merged with the [[International Women's Cricket Council]] (IWCC).<ref>{{cite book |title=Routledge Handbook of Global Sport |editor1-last=Nauright |editor1-first=John |editor2-last=Zipp |editor2-first=Sarah |year=2020 |publisher=[[Routledge]] |location=[[Abingdon-on-Thames|Abingdon]] |p=202 |isbn=978-1-138-88723-7}}</ref>}} The first had been [[1973 Women's Cricket World Cup|held in 1973]], pre-dating the first [[Cricket World Cup|men's Cricket World Cup]] by two years.<ref>{{cite book |title=Skirting the Boundary: A History of Women's Cricket |last=Duncan |first=Isabelle |year=2013 |publisher=[[The Robson Press]] |location=London |isbn=978-1-84954-546-4 |page=139}}</ref> The 2009 tournament included eight teams; six of which ([[Australia women's national cricket team|Australia]], [[England women's cricket team|England]], [[India women's national cricket team|India]], [[New Zealand women's national cricket team|New Zealand]], [[Sri Lanka women's national cricket team|Sri Lanka]] and the [[West Indies women's cricket team|West Indies]]) qualified automatically due to finishing as the top six teams at the [[2005 Women's Cricket World Cup]], while the other two ([[Pakistan women's national cricket team|Pakistan]] and [[South Africa women's national cricket team|South Africa]]) qualified through the [[2008 Women's Cricket World Cup Qualifier]].<ref>{{cite book |title=Women's Cricket and Global Processes: The Emergence and Development of Women's Cricket as a Global Game |last=Velija |first=Philippa |year=2015 |publisher=[[Palgrave Macmillan]] |location=[[Basingstoke]] |p=102 |isbn=978-1-137-32351-4}}</ref> Matches took place at various cricket grounds in Australia between 7 and 22 March, featuring 25 matches over 16 days.<ref name=\"matches\">{{cite web |url=https://www.espncricinfo.com/scores/series/8584/season/2009/icc-womens-world-cup |title=ICC Women's World Cup 2009 \u2013 Fixtures and Results |website=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nAlthough the ICC had successfully developed and expanded the women's game, from 15 member countries in 2005 to 42 in 2007, there was still a growing gap between the top four teams\u2014Australia, England, India and New Zealand\u2014and the rest.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=TIAnBwAAQBAJ |title=Cricket and Globalization |editor1-last=Rumford |editor1-first=Chris |editor2-last=Wagg |editor2-first=Stephen |year=2010 |publisher=[[Cambridge Scholars Publishing]] |location=[[Newcastle upon Tyne]] |isbn=978-1-4438-2370-8 |chapter=Women at the Wicket: The Development of Women's Cricket in England and Overseas |last1=Velija |first1=Philippa |last2=Ratna |first2=Aarti |last3=Flintoff |first3=Anne |pages=115\u2013116}}</ref> In 2008, England, and then Australia, became the first teams to introduce contracts for some of their women's players;<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/22864609/australia-women-handed-contracts |title=Australia women handed contracts |last=Roesler |first=Jenny |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=30 June 2008 |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref> [[Charlotte Edwards]], England's [[Captain (cricket)|captain]], said that this allowed the players to \"commit to training without worrying about our jobs outside cricket.\"<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=BcOkAwAAQBAJ |title=Young Wisden: A New Fan's Guide to Cricket |last1=de Lisle |first1=Tim |author1-link=Tim de Lisle |last2=Booth |first2=Lawrence |author2-link=Lawrence Booth (cricket writer) |publisher=John Wisden & Co |location=London |year=2011 |orig-year=2007 |page=40 |isbn=978-1-4081-2463-5}}</ref> Before the competition, Jenny Roesler of ''[[ESPNcricinfo|Cricinfo]]'' suggested England and New Zealand, along with Australia, as the favourites to win the competition.<ref name=\"three-way\">{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wwc2009/content/story/393395.html |title=A three-way battle to stand on top of the world |last=Roesler |first=Jenny |website=ESPNcricinfo |date=6 March 2009 |accessdate=8 April 2012}}</ref> [[Haidee Tiffen]], the captain of New Zealand, said that she thought \"Australia, New Zealand, England and India are of equal strength and any team can beat the other on its day. It is an open tournament with no clear-cut favourites.\"<ref name=\"bbc-team-guide\">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/womens_cricket/7907264.stm |title=Women's World Cup teams guide |work=[[BBC Sport]] |date=1 March 2009 |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> England's [[Claire Taylor]] said that she thought that Australia might struggle after losing key members of their 2005 World Cup-winning squad.<ref name=\"bbc-team-guide\"/>\n\n==Route to the final==\n{{main|2009 Women's Cricket World Cup}}\n\n===Group stage===\nNew Zealand were drawn in Group A of the competition, along with Australia, South Africa and the West Indies.<ref name=\"groups\">{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/women/content/story/361490.html |title=New South Wales to host Women's World Cup fixtures |website=ESPNcricinfo |date=17 July 2008 |accessdate=8 April 2012}}</ref> They started their campaign against Australia. Tiffen scored a cautious [[Glossary of cricket terms#H|half-century]] for New Zealand, but her dismissal triggered a collapse in which the team lost seven wickets for the addition of 34 runs. In their reply, Australia regularly lost wickets, and a six over [[Glossary of cricket terms#S|bowling spell]] by medium pacer [[Kate Pulford]], in which she took three wickets for 30 runs, slowed the run chase. After an initial rain delay held up the game, a second downpour finished the match, with Australia 13 runs short by the [[Duckworth\u2013Lewis\u2013Stern method|Duckworth\u2013Lewis method]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wwc2009/content/story/394145.html |title=New Zealand show strength in opening success |website=ESPNcricinfo |last=English |first=Peter |date=8 March 2009 |accessdate=8 April 2012}}</ref> Tiffen missed New Zealand's second match, against the West Indies, with an injury, and [[Aimee Watkins|Aimee Mason]] deputised as captain. For the second time in as many matches, New Zealand suffered a collapse, losing their first six wickets for 104 runs. A seventh-wicket partnership of 57 between Mason and [[Sarah Tsukigawa]] helped New Zealand to remain competitive in the match, and they completed their 50 overs with 192 runs. According to ''Cricinfo'', the West Indian reply \"was devoid of momentum\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wwc2009/content/story/394561.html |title=Mason and Doolan set up New Zealand win |website=ESPNcricinfo |date=10 March 2009 |accessdate=8 April 2012}}</ref> [[Spin bowling|Spin bowlers]] Mason and [[Lucy Doolan]] took three wickets apiece to limit the West Indies to 136 runs for the loss of eight wickets from their overs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wwc2009/engine/current/match/357963.html |title=8th Match, Group A: New Zealand Women v West Indies Women at Sydney, Mar 10, 2009 |website=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=8 April 2012}}</ref> In their final group stage match, a win over South Africa ensured that New Zealand won the group. [[Amy Satterthwaite]], [[Sara McGlashan]] and [[Nicola Browne]] all scored half-centuries as their team reached a total of 250 for five. South Africa struggled in their chase: only [[Cri-Zelda Brits]] reached double figures in an innings dominated by the bowling of Mason and [[Suzie Bates]], who collected four wickets each.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wwc2009/content/story/394912.html |title=New Zealand batter South Africa by 199 runs |website=ESPNcricinfo |date=12 March 2009 |accessdate=8 April 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Clairetaylor.jpg|thumb|England's [[Claire Taylor]] finished the tournament as the leading run-scorer.|alt=Claire Taylor batting]]England were placed in Group B, alongside India, Pakistan and Sri Lanka.<ref name=\"groups\"/> In their first contest, against Sri Lanka, they scored 277 runs, aided by a 95-ball century from Claire Taylor, and a half-century by [[Caroline Atkins]]. Sri Lanka batted their full allocation of overs, but lost by 100 runs. [[Laura Marsh]] took three wickets, and three of the Sri Lankan batters were [[run out]] in their chase.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wwc2009/engine/match/357957.html |title=2nd Match, Group B: England Women v Sri Lanka Women at Canberra, Mar 7, 2009 |website=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=8 April 2012}}</ref> Following the match, [[Jenny Gunn]]'s bowling action was reported to the ICC as being potentially illegal,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wwc2009/content/story/394398.html |title=Gunn and Fernando reported for suspect actions |website=ESPNcricinfo |date=9 March 2009 |accessdate=8 April 2012}}</ref> but she was cleared a few days later.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/women/content/story/395124.html |title=Gunn's action deemed legal |website=ESPNcricinfo |date=13 March 2009 |accessdate=8 April 2012}}</ref> England faced India in their second match, in a contest billed as the battle for top spot in the group.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/story/394453.html |title=India and England aim for top spot in Group B |website=ESPNcricinfo |date=9 March 2009 |accessdate=8 April 2012}}</ref> England won the match easily, bowling India out for 169; with Gunn and [[Holly Colvin]] each taking three wickets, and [[Not out|unbeaten]] half-centuries from both Atkins and Claire Taylor.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wwc2009/content/story/394538.html |title=Atkins and Taylor lead England to massive victory |website=ESPNcricinfo |date=10 March 2009 |accessdate=8 April 2012}}</ref> Another large win, over Pakistan, guaranteed that England finished as group winners. Marsh took a career-best [[List of five-wicket hauls in women's One Day International cricket|five wickets]] to help bowl Pakistan out for just 78 runs, a total which her side reached in less than half of their allowed overs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wwc2009/content/story/394899.html |title=Marsh takes five as England surge into Super Sixes |website=ESPNcricinfo |date=12 March 2009 |accessdate=8 April 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Super Sixes===\nAfter the initial league stage, the bottom team from each group was eliminated, and the remaining teams progressed into the Super Sixes. During this stage, results and points from matches between the teams that had qualified were carried over, and each team played a further three matches, against those teams that had advanced from the other group.<ref name=\"three-way\"/> England and New Zealand met each other in the first match of the Super Sixes. England batted first, and despite being 96 for four at one stage, 57 runs from Edwards, and a rapid 22 runs from Gunn, helped their side recover to post a total of 201 for five. In response, New Zealand began positively, and were boosted by a half-century from their captain, Tiffen, but the spin bowling of Edwards, Marsh and Colvin controlled the [[run rate]], and New Zealand were eventually bowled out for 170, Edwards taking four wickets.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wwc2009/content/story/395172.html |title=All-round Edwards helps England go top |website=ESPNcricinfo |last=Roesler |first=Jenny |date=14 March 2009 |accessdate=8 April 2012}}</ref> England's following match was against the West Indies, and they once again surpassed 200 runs after batting first. [[Sarah Taylor (cricketer)|Sarah Taylor]], Claire Taylor and Atkins all scored half-centuries to propel England to their total of 236 for eight. The English bowlers then dismissed the West Indies for 90 runs, with Marsh collecting three wickets. The win secured England a place in the final, irrespective of the result of their final Super Sixes match against Australia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wwc2009/content/story/395473.html |title=Unstoppable England march into World Cup final |website=ESPNcricinfo |date=17 March 2009 |accessdate=8 April 2012}}</ref>\n\nAfter losing their first Super Sixes match to England, New Zealand faced an Indian side which had beaten Australia in their first Super Six contest. India batted first and scored 207, during an innings in which they lost four batters to run outs. New Zealand began their response well, putting on a partnership of 78 runs for the first wicket between Pulford and Tiffen. After Tiffen's dismissal, Bates supported Pulford, who eventually fell for 71 runs, and New Zealand reached their target with 14 balls to spare.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wwc2009/content/story/395474.html |title=India's final hopes fade as New Zealand win |website=ESPNcricinfo |date=17 March 2009 |accessdate=8 April 2012}}</ref> New Zealand set a record partnership for the second wicket in women's ODIs in their final match:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/records/283599.html |title=Records / Women's One-Day Internationals / Partnership records / Highest partnership for the second wicket |website=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=13 June 2012}}</ref> Bates scored 168 and Tiffen 100 as the pair put on 262 runs together. Bates played an aggressive innings, scoring her runs from 105 balls, including 6 [[Boundary (cricket)|sixes]] and 19 [[Boundary (cricket)|fours]].  New Zealand reached 373 from their overs, and bowled Pakistan out for 150, granting themselves a 223 run victory, and qualifying for the final.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/sport/news/article.cfm?c_id=4&objectid=10562613 |title=Cricket: England next up as Bates blasts Ferns into final |work=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |publisher=[[New Zealand Media and Entertainment]] |location=[[Auckland]] |last=Geenty |first=Mark |date=20 March 2009 |accessdate=9 February 2015}}</ref> England were outplayed by Australia in their final Super Six match: [[Shelley Nitschke]] slowed the run rate during her bowling, taking two wickets and restricting England to just fourteen runs from her ten overs. England were bowled out for 161, a total Australia chased down within 34 overs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wwc2009/content/story/395771.html |title=Australia upset England but miss the final |website=ESPNcricinfo |date=19 March 2009 |accessdate=8 April 2012}}</ref> England's loss to Australia ended a 17-match unbeaten run.<ref name=\"roused\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2009/mar/21/england-women-cricket-world-cup-final-new-zealand |title=Edwards leads roused England into final against New Zealand |last=Bull |first=Andy |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=21 March 2009 |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Build up==\nThe final was a repeat of the [[1993 Women's Cricket World Cup|1993 tournament]], when England won at [[Lord's]]. Both sides had won the World Cup previously, but only when hosting the tournament. New Zealand achieved the feat [[2000 Women's Cricket World Cup|in 2000]], while England were winners in both 1973 and 1993.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wwc2009/content/story/396185.html |title=Little separates England and New Zealand |website=ESPNcricinfo |last=Roesler |first=Jenny |date=21 March 2009 |accessdate=7 April 2012}}</ref> In addition to losing the 1993 final to England, New Zealand were also finalists in 1997, losing to Australia in India. England had contested five previous finals; losing to Australia in subsequent tournaments in 1978, 1982 and 1988.<ref name=\"point\">{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wwc2009/content/story/396339.html |title=Shaw proves a point |website=ESPNcricinfo |last=Roesler |first=Jenny |date=22 March 2009 |accessdate=7 April 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"bbc\"/> Huw Richards, writing for the ''[[International New York Times|International Herald Tribune]]'', described both England and New Zealand as worthy finalists, and noted that he was disappointed with the performance of Australia, who finished fourth.<ref name=\"tribune\">{{cite news |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-162140852.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150329170206/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-162140852.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=29 March 2015 |title=English women win 3rd World Cup Cricket |last=Richards |first=Huw |work=[[International New York Times|International Herald Tribune]] |publisher=[[The New York Times Company]] |location=[[La D\u00e9fense]], France |date=23 March 2009 |accessdate=9 February 2015 |via=[[Highbeam Research]] |url-access=subscription}}</ref> Simon Wilde of ''[[The Times]]'' cited England as favourites: \"In Edwards they have the ICC player of the year, in Claire Taylor the No 1-ranked batsman and in Isa Guha the No 1 bowler.\"<ref name=\"wilde\">{{cite news |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/bat-women-one-england-side-keeps-winning-tdpf2jf3cq7 |title=Bat women: one England side keeps winning |last=Wilde |first=Simon |work=[[The Times]] |date=22 March 2009 |accessdate=21 April 2020 |url-access=subscription}}</ref> ''[[The New Zealand Herald]]''{{'}}s Mark Geenty concurred that England were favourites, describing them as \"the form side of recent years\".<ref name=\"hit hard\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/sport/news/article.cfm?c_id=4&objectid=10562747 |title=Cricket: We'll hit England hard, says White Ferns coach |last=Geenty |first=Mark |work=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |date=20 March 2009 |accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref> England had beaten New Zealand in their most recent four matches, including their victory over them during the Super Sixes stage of the competition.<ref name=\"roused\"/>\nNew Zealand's coach, [[Gary Stead]], said that his team would aim to play their normal \"aggressive style of play and although that may be a bit more high risk, I think it's the style that we play best.\"<ref name=\"hit hard\"/> \n\nAfter the Australian team was knocked out, local press coverage for the match diminished; only three journalists attended the pre-game press conference for the final. A reporter for the [[BBC]], [[Alison Mitchell]], said that in the Australian newspapers, \"the nationals and even most of the locals I flicked through on Saturday carried nothing except one slim column\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/tms/2009/03/england_just_want_to_play.shtml |title=England just want to play |last=Mitchell |first=Alison |authorlink=Alison Mitchell |work=BBC Sport |date=21 March 2009 |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> England [[all-rounder]] Gunn aggravated a calf-strain during the warm-up, and 10 minutes before the start was replaced by the team's vice-captain [[Nicky Shaw]].<ref name=\"point\"/>\n\n==Match==\n===Summary===\n[[File:Lucy Doolan.jpg|thumb|right|[[Lucy Doolan]] was New Zealand's best performer with both bat and ball.|alt=Lucy Doolan leaving a cricket field]]\nThe final was played on \"a gloriously sunny day\" at the [[North Sydney Oval]], a [[multi-purpose stadium]] in [[North Sydney, New South Wales|North Sydney]], New South Wales.<ref name=\"bbc\">{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/womens_cricket/7957519.stm |title=World Cup joy for England women |work=BBC Sport |last=Lewis |first=Aimee |date=22 March 2009 |accessdate=8 April 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"card\">{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wwc2009/engine/match/357980.html |title=Final: England Women v New Zealand Women at Sydney, Mar 22, 2009 |website=[[ESPNcricinfo]] |accessdate=7 April 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.austadiums.com/stadiums/stadiums.php?id=80 |title=North Sydney Oval |publisher=Austadiums |accessdate=26 March 2015}}</ref> The ground had hosted a number of matches earlier in the tournament, and during the [[1988 Women's Cricket World Cup]],<ref>{{cite web  |url-access=subscription |url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Grounds/2/198_wo.html |title=Women's One-day International matches played on North Sydney Oval, Sydney (15) |website=CricketArchive |accessdate=26 March 2015}}</ref> but, as of 2020, has not hosted men's international cricket.<ref>{{cite web |url-access=subscription |url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Grounds/2/198.html |title=North Sydney Oval, Sydney |website=CricketArchive |accessdate=26 March 2015}}</ref> Played in front of a crowd of 2,300, the match began at 10:00 [[Daylight saving time in Australia|AEDT]] (23:00 [[Greenwich Mean Time|GMT]]), with a scheduled lunch interval from 13:10 to 13:55.<ref name=\"card\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=http://tvnz.co.nz/cricket-news/white-ferns-rue-final-got-away-2576899 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402191322/http://tvnz.co.nz/cricket-news/white-ferns-rue-final-got-away-2576899 |archive-date=2 April 2015 |url-status=dead |title=White Ferns rue final that got away |publisher=[[Television New Zealand]] |date=23 March 2009 |accessdate=26 March 2015}}</ref> [[Steve Davis (umpire)|Steve Davis]], of Australia, and the South African [[Brian Jerling]] were appointed as the on-field umpires for the match. Davis was a member of the [[Elite Panel of ICC Umpires]], the highest designation for an umpire, while Jerling was on the [[International Panel of Umpires and Referees]], the next most senior designation. [[Tyron Wijewardene]] and [[Jeff Brookes]] fulfilled the off-field roles of third and fourth umpires respectively, and [[Brian Aldridge (cricketer)|Brian Aldridge]] served as [[match referee]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.icc-europe.org/newsdetails.php?newsId=5544_1237507200 |title=ICC announces umpire appointments for play-offs and final of ICC Women's World Cup 2009 |publisher=ICC Europe |date=20 March 2009 |accessdate=26 March 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402120818/http://www.icc-europe.org/newsdetails.php?newsId=5544_1237507200 |archive-date=2 April 2015 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Aldridge had previously umpired the [[1992 Cricket World Cup Final]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/65156.html |title=Benson & Hedges World Cup, Final: England v Pakistan at Melbourne, Mar 25, 1992 |website=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=26 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nDespite conditions conducive to [[swing bowling]], New Zealand's captain, Tiffen, chose to bat first after winning the toss.<ref name=\"wisden\">{{cite book |last=Roesler |first=Jenny |chapter=The Women's World Cup, 2008\u201309 |pages=1012\u20131013 |editor-first=Scyld |editor-last=Berry |editor-link=Scyld Berry |title=[[Wisden Cricketers' Almanack]] 2010 |edition=147 |year=2010 |publisher=John Wisden & Co. Ltd |location=[[Alton, Hampshire|Alton]], Hampshire |isbn=978-1-4081-2466-6}}</ref> England opened the bowling with [[Seam bowling|seam]] from one end, provided by [[Katherine Brunt]], and spin at the other, from [[Isa Guha]]. Brunt's bowling spell was described by the BBC's Aimee Lewis as \"superb\",<ref name=\"bbc\"/> and teammate Shaw credited her with putting the New Zealand batters under pressure.<ref name=\"point\"/> The New Zealand opening batters, Pulford and Tiffen, put on 26 runs together before Pulford was caught by Claire Taylor off the bowling of Guha,<ref name=\"bbc\"/> having scored 8 runs.<ref name=\"card\"/> According to Roesler, players on both teams showed some early nerves: Tiffen played some uncertain shots, while Guha bowled some [[Wide (cricket)|wide]] deliveries.<ref name=\"ci\">{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wwc2009/content/story/396271.html |title=England lift World Cup after late drama |website=ESPNcricinfo |last=Roesler |first=Jenny |date=22 March 2009 |accessdate=7 April 2012}}</ref> New Zealand progressed to 46 for one before England made their first bowling change. The England vice-captain, Shaw, was brought on, and made an immediate impact. In her first over,<ref name=\"guard-report\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2009/mar/22/england-womens-world-cup-final-cricket |title=Shaw leads England to World Cup glory |last=Pandaram |first=Jamie |work=The Guardian |date=22 March 2009 |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> Bates attempted a loft over [[Fielding (cricket)|mid-on]], and was caught by Atkins. The following ball, Satterthwaite fell for a [[Duck (cricket)|duck]], edging a delivery to the [[wicket-keeper]], Sarah Taylor, leaving New Zealand 49 for three.<ref name=\"card\"/> Four overs later, Tiffen was also dismissed by Shaw, caught behind by Sarah Taylor. McGlashan was described by Lewis as looking \"in fine touch\", but after scoring 21 runs from 20 deliveries, she was caught at mid-wicket by Greenway off the bowling of Colvin.<ref name=\"bbc\"/> After 20 overs, New Zealand were 74 for five, with their most prolific batters of the tournament all dismissed.<ref name=\"tears\">{{cite news |url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/sport/news/article.cfm?c_id=4&objectid=10562996 |title=Cricket: Tears after White Ferns' 'bad day at the office' |last=Geenty |first=Mark |work=The New Zealand Herald |publisher=New Zealand Media and Entertainment |location=Auckland |date=23 March 2009 |accessdate=9 February 2015}}</ref> Marsh subsequently [[bowled]] Mason for 13, while Tsukigawa edged a delivery from Brunt for 2:<ref name=\"bbc\"/> New Zealand's innings collapsed to 101 for seven.<ref name=\"card\"/> Doolan joined Browne at the crease, and the pair provided their side with some degree of a recovery: Doolan scored 48 runs in a partnership of 63 to help New Zealand to their total of 166.<ref name=\"guard-report\"/> After the dismissal of Doolan, who was [[stumped]] off a wide delivery,<ref name=\"NZinns\">{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wwc2009/engine/match/357980.html?innings=1;view=commentary |title=Final: England Women v New Zealand Women at Sydney, Mar 22, 2009: New Zealand Women innings |website=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=7 April 2012}}</ref> New Zealand subsided rapidly, losing their final two wickets for just two more runs.<ref name=\"card\"/> ''The New Zealand Herald'' criticised the batting as being \"indifferent\",<ref name=\"tears\"/> but Richards credited England for their \"tight bowling and fielding\" to restrict New Zealand.<ref name=\"tribune\"/>\n\nSimon Briggs of ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' described the start of England's chase as being \"smooth and confident\":<ref name=\"tele\">{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/cricket/international/england/5031389/England-victorious-in-World-Cup-final.html |title=England victorious in World Cup final |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |publisher=Telegraph Media Group |location=London |last=Briggs |first=Simon |date=22 March 2009 |accessdate=7 April 2012}}</ref> opening batters Atkins and Sarah Taylor built a partnership larger than any managed by New Zealand, scoring 74 runs. Taylor was the first batter out,<ref name=\"ci\"/> caught by Tiffen at mid-wicket from the off-spin bowling of Doolan for 39 runs.<ref name=\"stars\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2009/mar/22/womens-cricket-england-win-world-cup |title=Shaw stars with bat and ball as England win World Cup |work=The Guardian |date=22 March 2009 |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> Claire Taylor came to the crease upon Sarah Taylor's dismissal and played with a similar attacking intent, striking four boundaries during her 21 runs before she was bowled by Mason, with England 109 for two.<ref name=\"ci\"/> Atkins played a patient innings, and scored the most runs for her side, accruing 40 from 85 balls, eventually being caught by [[Sophie Devine]] from the bowling of Dooley.<ref name=\"card\"/> England's middle order suffered their own collapse against the opposition spin bowlers Doolan and Mason,<ref name=\"wisden\"/> their scoring rate slowing significantly from 4.78 runs per over at the end of the fourteenth over to 3.58 twenty overs later.<ref name=\"tele\"/><ref name=\"ENGinns\">{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wwc2009/engine/match/357980.html?innings=2;view=commentary |title=Final: England Women v New Zealand Women at Sydney, Mar 22, 2009: England Women innings |website=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=7 April 2012}}</ref> Edwards became Dooley's third wicket when she was given out after being caught by wicket-keeper [[Rachel Priest]] for 10 runs, though she did not actually hit the ball.<ref name=\"ci\"/> Despite their struggles through the middle overs, Richards opined that \"England never looked like losing.\"<ref name=\"tribune\"/> Greenway and Morgan were both dismissed for single-figure totals: Greenway had survived an early appeal when she was caught after the ball had hit her [[pads]], but was later caught by Satterthwaite off the bowling of Mason for eight runs, to leave England on 139 for five;<ref name=\"stars\"/> Morgan was the victim of a what Lewis described as a \"sloppy run out\" shortly thereafter, moving the score to 149 for six.<ref name=\"bbc\"/> It was Shaw who once again galvanised England, batting with a more attacking style than those that had struggled before her.<ref name=\"tele\"/> Her score of 17 [[not out]] pushed England towards the winning target, and a single from Colvin secured victory for England with 23 balls remaining in the innings.<ref name=\"ENGinns\"/> Shaw's contribution earned her the player of the match accolade.<ref name=\"bbc\"/>\n\n===Scorecard===\n{| style=\"text-align:center; width: 60%;\" class=wikitable\n|+ [[New Zealand women's national cricket team|New Zealand]] batting innings<ref name=\"card\"/>\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | [[Batting (cricket)|Batter]]\n! scope=\"col\" | [[Dismissal (cricket)|Method of dismissal]]\n! scope=\"col\" | [[Run (cricket)|Runs]]\n! scope=\"col\" | [[Delivery (cricket)|Balls]]\n! scope=\"col\" | [[Strike rate#Batting Strike Rate|Strike rate]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal; text-align: left;\" | [[Kate Pulford]] \n| style=\" text-align: left;\" | c [[Claire Taylor]] b [[Isa Guha]] || 8 || 23 || 34.78\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal; text-align: left;\" | [[Haidee Tiffen]] {{asterisk}} \n| style=\" text-align: left;\" | c [[Sarah Taylor (cricketer)|Sarah Taylor]] {{dagger}} b [[Nicky Shaw]] || 30 || 56 || 53.57\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal; text-align: left;\" | [[Suzie Bates]] \n| style=\" text-align: left;\" | c [[Caroline Atkins]] b [[Nicky Shaw]] || 2 || 7 || 28.57\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal; text-align: left;\" | [[Amy Satterthwaite]] \n| style=\" text-align: left;\" | c [[Sarah Taylor (cricketer)|Sarah Taylor]] {{dagger}} b [[Nicky Shaw]] || 0 || 1 || 0.00\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal; text-align: left;\" | [[Sara McGlashan]] \n| style=\" text-align: left;\" | c [[Lydia Greenway]] b [[Holly Colvin]] || 21 || 20 || 105.00\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal; text-align: left;\" | [[Aimee Watkins|Aimee Mason]] \n| style=\" text-align: left;\" | b [[Laura Marsh]] || 13 || 18 || 72.22\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal; text-align: left;\" | [[Nicola Browne]] \n| style=\" text-align: left;\" | lbw b [[Nicky Shaw]] || 25 || 78 || 32.05\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal; text-align: left;\" | [[Sarah Tsukigawa]] \n| style=\" text-align: left;\" | c [[Sarah Taylor (cricketer)|Sarah Taylor]] {{dagger}} b [[Katherine Brunt]] || 2 || 18 || 11.11\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal; text-align: left;\" | [[Lucy Doolan]] \n| style=\" text-align: left;\" | st [[Sarah Taylor (cricketer)|Sarah Taylor]] {{dagger}} b [[Laura Marsh]] || 48 || 57 || 84.21\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal; text-align: left;\" | [[Sophie Devine]] \n| style=\" text-align: left;\" | lbw b [[Charlotte Edwards]] || 0 || 5 || 0.00\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal; text-align: left;\" | [[Rachel Priest]] {{dagger}} \n| style=\" text-align: left;\" | [[not out]] || 0 || 1 || 0.00\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal; text-align: left;\" | Extras \n| style=\" text-align: left;\" | (2 [[leg bye]]s, 15 [[Wide (cricket)|wides]]) || 17 || colspan=\"2\" |\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal; text-align: left;\" | '''Totals''' \n| style=\" text-align: left;\" | (47.2 overs) || '''166''' || colspan=\"2\" | 3.50 runs per over\n|}\n{| style=\"text-align: center; width: 60%;\" class=wikitable\n|+ [[England women's cricket team|England]] bowling\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | [[Bowling (cricket)|Bowler]]\n! scope=\"col\" | [[Over (cricket)|Overs]]\n! scope=\"col\" | [[Over (cricket)|Maidens]]\n! scope=\"col\" | [[Run (cricket)|Runs]]\n! scope=\"col\" | [[Wicket]]s\n! scope=\"col\" | [[Economy rate (cricket)|Economy]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal; text-align: left;\" | [[Katherine Brunt]] \n| 10 || 3 || 33 || 1 || 3.30\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal; text-align: left;\" | [[Isa Guha]] \n| 5 || 0 || 24 || 1 || 4.80\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal; text-align: left;\" | [[Nicky Shaw]] \n| 8.2 || 0 || 34 || 4 || 4.08\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal; text-align: left;\" | [[Holly Colvin]] \n| 10 || 1 || 26 || 1 || 2.60\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal; text-align: left;\" | [[Laura Marsh]] \n| 10 || 3 || 34 || 2 || 3.40\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal; text-align: left;\" | [[Charlotte Edwards]] \n| 4 || 1 || 13 || 1 || 3.25\n|}\n{| style=\"text-align:center; width: 60%;\" class=wikitable\n|+ [[England women's cricket team|England]] batting innings\n|-\n! [[Batting (cricket)|Batter]]\n! [[Dismissal (cricket)|Method of dismissal]]\n! [[Run (cricket)|Runs]]\n! [[Delivery (cricket)|Balls]]\n! [[Strike rate#Batting Strike Rate|Strike rate]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal; text-align: left;\" | [[Sarah Taylor (cricketer)|Sarah Taylor]] {{dagger}} \n| style=\" text-align: left;\" | c [[Haidee Tiffen]] b [[Lucy Doolan]] || 39 || 45 || 86.66\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal; text-align: left;\" | [[Caroline Atkins]] \n| style=\" text-align: left;\" | c [[Sophie Devine]] b [[Lucy Doolan]] || 40 || 85 || 47.05\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal; text-align: left;\" | [[Claire Taylor]] \n| style=\" text-align: left;\" | b [[Aimee Watkins|Aimee Mason]] || 21 || 30 || 70.00\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal; text-align: left;\" | [[Charlotte Edwards]] {{asterisk}} \n| style=\" text-align: left;\" | c [[Rachel Priest]] {{dagger}} b [[Lucy Doolan]] || 10 || 19 || 52.63\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal; text-align: left;\" | [[Lydia Greenway]] \n| style=\" text-align: left;\" | c [[Amy Satterthwaite]] b [[Aimee Watkins]] || 8 || 34 || 23.52\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal; text-align: left;\" | [[Beth Morgan (cricketer)|Beth Morgan]] \n| style=\" text-align: left;\" | run out || 9 || 27 || 33.33\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal; text-align: left;\" | [[Nicky Shaw]] \n| style=\" text-align: left;\" | not out || 17 || 27 || 62.96\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal; text-align: left;\" | [[Holly Colvin]] \n| style=\" text-align: left;\" | not out || 5 || 10 || 50.00\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal; text-align: left;\" | Extras \n| style=\" text-align: left;\" | (1 [[leg bye]], 17 [[Wide (cricket)|wides]]) || 18 || colspan=\"2\" |\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal; text-align: left;\" | '''Totals''' \n| style=\" text-align: left;\" | (46.1 overs) || '''167/6''' || colspan=\"2\" | 3.61 runs per over\n|- style=\"text-align:left;\"\n| colspan=\"5\" | ''Did not bat'': [[Laura Marsh]], [[Katherine Brunt]], [[Isa Guha]]\n|}\n{| style=\"text-align: center; width: 60%;\" class=wikitable\n|+ [[New Zealand women's national cricket team|New Zealand]] bowling\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | [[Bowling (cricket)|Bowler]]\n! scope=\"col\" | [[Over (cricket)|Overs]]\n! scope=\"col\" | [[Over (cricket)|Maidens]]\n! scope=\"col\" | [[Run (cricket)|Runs]]\n! scope=\"col\" | [[Wicket]]s\n! scope=\"col\" | [[Economy rate (cricket)|Economy]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal; text-align: left;\" | [[Sophie Devine]] \n| 9 || 0 || 30 || 0 || 3.33\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal; text-align: left;\" | [[Kate Pulford]] \n| 3 || 0 || 17 || 0 || 5.66\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal; text-align: left;\" | [[Nicola Browne]] \n| 7 || 1 || 24 || 0 || 3.42\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal; text-align: left;\" | [[Suzie Bates]] \n| 4.1 || 0 || 21 || 0 || 5.04\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal; text-align: left;\" | [[Lucy Doolan]] \n| 10 || 4 || 23 || 3 || 2.30\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal; text-align: left;\" | [[Sarah Tsukigawa]] \n| 4 || 1 || 23 || 0 || 5.75\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal; text-align: left;\" | [[Aimee Watkins|Aimee Mason]] \n| 9 || 0 || 28 || 2 || 3.11\n|}\n\n'''Match officials'''\n* On-field [[umpire (cricket)|umpires]]: [[Steve Davis (umpire)|Steve Davis]] and [[Brian Jerling]]\n* [[Third umpire]]: [[Tyron Wijewardene]]\n* [[Match referee]]: [[Brian Aldridge (cricketer)|Brian Aldridge]]\n* [[Fourth umpire|Reserve umpire]]: [[Jeff Brookes]]\n\n'''Key'''\n* {{asterisk}} \u2013 [[Captain (cricket)|Captain]]\n* {{dagger}} \u2013 [[Wicket-keeper]]\n* c ''Fielder'' \u2013 Indicates that the batter was dismissed by a catch by the named [[Fielding (cricket)|fielder]]\n* b ''Bowler'' \u2013 Indicates which [[Bowling (cricket)|bowler]] gains credit for the dismissal\n* lbw \u2013 Indicates the batter was dismissed [[leg before wicket]]\n* st \u2013 Indicates the batter was [[stumped]]\n\n==Aftermath==\nThe ICC awarded England US$45,000 for their cup win, while New Zealand received $25,000.<ref name=\"tears\"/> Shaw, who had not expected to play, said after the match; \"I started the day crying, I finished it crying, but we won a World Cup in between\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2009/mar/23/women-england-cricket-world-cup |title=England win the World Cup |last=Booth |first=Lawrence |author-link=Lawrence Booth (cricket writer) |work=The Guardian |date=23 March 2009 |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> New Zealand's captain, Tiffen, reflected after the match, \"Maybe there were some nerves in amongst the camp. We didn't hype it up to be anything more than another day at the office, unfortunately it was a bad day at the office.\"<ref name=\"tears\"/> The team of the tournament included seven finalists: England's Edwards was selected as captain, and was joined by teammates Brunt, Marsh, Claire Taylor and Sarah Taylor. Bates and Pulford represented New Zealand in the team, while Devine was named as the team's twelfth woman. Claire Taylor, who finished the tournament as the leading run-scorer, was named as the player of the tournament.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wwc2009/content/story/396488.html |title=Five England players in World Cup XI |website=ESPNcricinfo |date=23 March 2009 |accessdate=9 April 2012}}</ref> The month after the final, Taylor became the first woman to be selected as one of [[Wisden Cricketers of the Year|''Wisden's'' Cricketers of the Year]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/cricket/international/england/5096209/Claire-Taylor-the-first-woman-to-be-named-among-the-Wisden-Cricketers-of-the-Year.html |title=Claire Taylor the first woman to be named among the Wisden Cricketers of the Year |last=Berry |first=Scyld |authorlink=Scyld Berry |work=The Daily Telegraph |publisher=Telegraph Media Group |location=London |date=3 April 2009 |accessdate=9 February 2015}}</ref> Both Taylor and Edwards were awarded [[Order of the British Empire|MBEs]] for their services to cricket; Edwards received hers in the [[2009 Birthday Honours]], while Taylor's came in the [[2010 New Year Honours]].<ref>{{cite book |title=Skirting the Boundary: A History of Women's Cricket |last=Duncan |first=Isabelle |year=2013 |publisher=[[The Robson Press]] |location=London |isbn=978-1-84954-546-4 |pages=151\u2013153}}</ref>\n\nThe England team flew back to the United Kingdom in [[economy class]]; Mitchell highlighted the contrast with the [[England cricket team|England men's team]], who \"fly business as standard\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/tms/2009/03/world_champions.shtml |title=World champions return home |last=Mitchell |first=Alison |author-link=Alison Mitchell |work=BBC Sport |date=24 March 2009 |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> They held a reception at Lord's in London upon their return, but the former [[Minister for Sport and Civil Society|sports minister]], [[Richard Caborn]], lamented the low-key celebrations, saying that \"I would have a Number 10 reception, a reception at the House of Commons, and, at the appropriate time, in the Lords.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2009/mar/25/england-womens-world-cup-winners |title=England women's cricket team bring back the cup \u2013 and the pride |last=Gibson |first=Owen |work=The Guardian |date=25 March 2009 |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> In her history of women's cricket, Rafaelle Nicholson was critical of some of the reporting on the final, saying that \"coverage increasingly appears to compare women's cricket with the men's game, and to treat the male version as 'real cricket'\".<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MkXOxAEACAAJ |title=Ladies and Lords: A History of Women's Cricket in Britain |last=Nicholson |first=Rafaelle |year=2019 |publisher=[[Peter Lang (publisher)|Peter Lang]] |isbn=978-1-78874-294-8 |page=loc. 7916 |nopp=true}}</ref> The English journalists Simon Wilde and [[Lawrence Booth (cricket writer)|Lawrence Booth]] credited the contracts introduced in 2008 as being critical to England's success.<ref name=\"wilde\"/><ref name=\"feet\">{{cite news |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/englands-women-have-the-world-at-their-feet-kwsx05xkrkc |title=England\u2019s women have the world at their feet: Team can complete a historic treble by winning the World Twenty20 final against New Zealand at Lord\u2019s today |last=Booth |first=Lawrence |authorlink=Lawrence Booth (cricket writer) |work=[[The Sunday Times]] |date=21 June 2009 |accessdate=21 April 2020 |url-access=subscription}}</ref> Booth highlighted the contrast with New Zealand's captain, Tiffin, who had retired after the World Cup, claiming: \"If I was paid properly, I'd still be playing.\"<ref name=\"feet\"/>\n\nThe two sides met again three months later to contest the final of the [[2009 ICC Women's World Twenty20|2009 Women's World Twenty20]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wwt202009/engine/match/355990.html |title=Final: England Women v New Zealand Women at Lord's, Jun 21, 2009 |website=ESPNcricinfo |date=9 April 2012}}</ref> England once again won the contest, and in doing so became the first team of either gender to be champions in all three cricketing formats: [[Women's Test cricket|Test]], [[Women's One Day International|One Day International]] and [[Women's Twenty20 International|Twenty20]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wwt202009/content/story/409994.html |title=All-conquering England take title |last=Narayanan |first=Nishi |website=ESPNcricinfo |date=21 June 2009 |accessdate=9 April 2012}}</ref> Each of the top four in the 2009 tournament automatically qualified for the [[2013 Women's Cricket World Cup]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.rediff.com/cricket/report/kiwi-bates-does-a-sehwag-world-cup/20090319.htm |title=Kiwi Bates does a Sehwag in World Cup |work=[[Rediff.com]] |date=19 March 2009 |accessdate=9 February 2015}}</ref> Neither England nor New Zealand reached the final of that tournament, but instead met in the third-place playoff, which England won by four wickets.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://sports.ndtv.com/icc-womens-world-cup/news/203626-charlotte-edwards-guides-england-to-third-spot-in-womens-world-cup |title=Charlotte Edwards guides England to third spot in Women's World Cup |agency=Press Trust of India |publisher=[[NDTV]] |date=15 February 2013 |accessdate=9 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Women's Cricket World Cup}}\n{{2009 Women's Cricket World Cup}}\n{{England women's cricket team}}\n{{New Zealand women's national cricket team}}\n{{Good article}}\n\n[[Category:2008\u201309 Australian women's cricket season|World Cup]]\n[[Category:2009 in English women's cricket|World Cup]]\n[[Category:2009 in New Zealand cricket|World Cup]]\n[[Category:2009 in New Zealand women's sport|cricket]]\n[[Category:2009 Women's Cricket World Cup|!]]\n[[Category:England women's national cricket team matches|World Cup 2009]]\n[[Category:New Zealand women's national cricket team matches|World Cup 2009]]\n[[Category:Women's Cricket World Cup finals]]\n", "name_user": "Harrias", "label": "safe", "comment": "link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2009_Women%27s_Cricket_World_Cup_Final"}
{"title_page": "Islamic calligraphy", "text_new": "\n\n{{short description|Artistic practice of calligraphy in Islamic contexts}}\n[[File:basmalah-1wm.svg|right|thumb|The [[Basmala]] in an 18th-century Islamic calligraphy from the [[Ottoman empire|Ottoman]] region, Thuluth script.]]\n{{Calligraphy}}\n\n'''Islamic calligraphy''' is the artistic practice of [[penmanship|handwriting]] and [[calligraphy]],<!-- and by extension, [[bookbinding|bookmaking]],--> based upon the [[Arabic alphabet|alphabet]] in the lands sharing a common Islamic cultural heritage. It includes [[Arabic calligraphy|Arabic Calligraphy]], [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]], and [[Persian calligraphy]].<ref name=\"Bloom\">{{cite book |last=Blair |first=Sheila S. |title=The art and architecture of Islam : 1250\u20131800 |year=1995 |publisher=Yale University Press |location=New Haven |isbn=0-300-06465-9 |edition=Reprinted with corrections |author2=Bloom, Jonathan M.}}</ref><!--{{rp|218}}--><ref name=\"ens\">Chapman, Caroline (2012). ''Encyclopedia of Islamic Art and Architecture'', {{ISBN|978-979-099-631-1}}</ref> It is known in [[Arabic language|Arabic]] as ''khatt Islami'' ({{rtl-lang|ar|\u062e\u0637 \u0625\u0633\u0644\u0627\u0645\u064a}}), meaning Islamic line, design, or construction.<ref name=\"typography\">{{cite web| title=Arabic calligraphy as a typographic exercise| url=http://ilovetypography.com/2008/07/10/arabic-calligraphy-as-a-typographic-exercise/ |author=Julia Kaestle |date=10 July 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe development of Islamic calligraphy is strongly tied to the [[Qur'an]]; chapters and excerpts from the Qur'an are a common and almost universal text upon which Islamic calligraphy is based. However, Islamic calligraphy is not limited to strictly religious subjects, objects, or spaces. Like all [[Islamic art]], it encompasses a diverse array of works created in a wide variety of contexts.<ref>Blair, Sheila S. (Spring 2003). \"The Mirage of Islamic Art: Reflections on the Study of an Unwieldy Field\". ''The Art Bulletin''. '''85''': 152\u2013184 \u2013 via JSTOR.</ref><!--{{rp|222}}--> The prevalence of calligraphy in Islamic art is not directly related to its non-figural tradition; rather, it reflects the centrality of the notion of writing and written text in Islam.<ref>Allen, Terry (1988). ''Five Essays on Islamic Art''. Sebastopol, CA: Solipsist Press. pp. 17\u201337. {{ISBN|0944940005}}.</ref> It is noteworthy, for instance, that the Prophet Muhammad is related to have said: \"The first thing God created was the pen.\"<ref name=\":1\">Roxburgh, David J. (2008). \"\"The Eye is Favored for Seeing the Writing's Form\": On the Sensual and the Sensuous in Islamic Calligraphy\". ''Muqarnas''. '''25''': 275\u2013298 \u2013 via JSTOR.</ref>\n\nIslamic calligraphy developed from two major styles: [[Kufic]] and [[Naskh (script)|Naskh]]. There are several variations of each, as well as regionally specific styles. Arabic or Persian calligraphy has also been incorporated into [[modern art]], beginning with the post-colonial period in the Middle East, as well as the more recent style of [[calligraffiti]].\n\n<!--[[Arabic language|Arabic]], [[Persian language|Persian]] and [[Ottoman Turkish language|Ottoman Turkish]] calligraphy is associated with abstract [[Arabesque (Islamic art)|arabesque]] motifs on the walls and ceilings of [[mosque]]s as well as on the page. Contemporary [[artists]] in the [[Islamic world]] draw on the heritage of calligraphy to use calligraphic inscriptions or abstractions in their work. They used it to represent God because they denied representing God with images.<ref name=\"Bernard Lewis\">Bernard Lewis and Butnzie Ellis Churchill, ''Islam : the Religion and the People'', {{ISBN|978-0-13-223085-8}}</rf>-->\n\n==Instruments and media==\nThe traditional instrument of the Islamic calligrapher is the [[qalam]], a [[pen]] normally made of dried [[Phragmites|reed]] or [[bamboo]]. The [[ink]] is often in [[Colour|color]] and chosen so that its intensity can vary greatly, creating dynamism and movement in the letter forms. Some styles are often written using a metallic-tip pen.\n[[File:Niebuhr Beschreibung von Arabien Tab XIII.png|thumbnail|Five principal Arabic calligraphic cursive styles:<br />\n{{ordered list|\n| Naskh\n| Nasta\u2018liq\n| Diwani\n| Thuluth\n| Reqa\n}}]]\nIslamic calligraphy can be applied to a wide range of decorative mediums other than paper, such as tiles, vessels, carpets, and stone.<ref name=ens/> Before the advent of paper, papyrus and parchment were used for writing. During the 9th century, an influx of paper from China revolutionized calligraphy. While monasteries in Europe treasured a few dozen volumes, libraries in the [[Muslim world]] regularly contained hundreds and even thousands of books.<ref name=Bloom>{{cite book |last=Blair |first=Sheila S. |title=The art and architecture of Islam : 1250\u20131800 |year=1995 |publisher=Yale University Press |location=New Haven |isbn=0-300-06465-9 |edition=Reprinted with corrections |author2=Bloom, Jonathan M.}}</ref>{{rp|218}}\n\nFor centuries, the art of writing has fulfilled a central iconographic function in Islamic art.<ref>Tabbaa, Yasser (1991). \"The Transformation of Arabic Writing: Part I, Qur'\u0101nic Calligraphy\". ''Ars Orientalis''. '''21''': 119\u2013148.</ref> Although the academic tradition of Islamic calligraphy began in Baghdad, the center of the Islamic empire during much of its early history, it eventually spread as far as India and Spain.\n\nCoins were another support for calligraphy. Beginning in 692, the Islamic caliphate reformed the coinage of the Near East by replacing Byzantine Christian imagery with Islamic phrases inscribed in Arabic. This was especially true for dinars, or gold coins of high value. Generally, the coins were inscribed with quotes from the Qur'an.\n\nBy the tenth century, the Persians, who had converted to Islam, began weaving inscriptions onto elaborately patterned silks. So precious were textiles featuring Arabic text that Crusaders brought them to Europe as prized possessions. A notable example is the [[Suaire de Saint-Josse]], used to wrap the bones of St. Josse in the Abbey of St. Josse-sur-Mer, near Caen in northwestern France.<ref name=Bloom />{{rp|223\u20135}}\n\nAs Islamic calligraphy is highly venerated, most works follow examples set by well-established calligraphers, with the exception of secular or contemporary works. In the Islamic tradition, calligraphers underwent extensive training in three stages, including the study of their teacher's models, in order to be granted certification.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Styles==\n===Kufic===\n[[File:A section of the Koran - Google Art Project.jpg|thumb|250px|left|9th century [[Qur'an]], an early kufic example from the [[Abbasid dynasty|Abbasid period]]]]\n[[File:Bowl with Kufic Calligraphy, 10th century.jpg|thumb|250px|left|''Bowl with [[Kufic]] [[Calligraphy]]'', 10th century. [[Brooklyn Museum]]]]\n\n[[Kufic]] is the oldest form of the Arabic script. The style emphasizes rigid and angular strokes, which appears as a modified form of the old [[Nabataean alphabet|Nabataean script]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=A Companion to Islamic Art and Architecture|last=Flood, Necipo\u011flu|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|year=2017|isbn=9781119068570|volume=Volume I|location=Hoboken|pages=109\u2013110|oclc=963439648}}</ref> The Archaic Kufi consisted of about 17 letters without diacritic dots or accents. Diacritical markings were added during the 7th century to help readers with pronunciation of the Qur'an and other important documents, increasing the number of Arabic letters to 28.<ref>Schimmel, Annemarie (1984). ''[http://universityoftexasbrownsville.worldcat.org/title/calligraphy-and-islamic-culture/oclc/20420019&referer=brief_results Calligraphy and Islamic Culture]''. New York: New York University Press. p. 4. {{ISBN|0814778305}}.</ref> Although some scholars dispute this, Kufic script was supposedly developed around the end of the 7th century in [[Kufa]], Iraq, from which it takes its name.<ref>Kvernen, Elizabeth (2009). \"An Introduction of Arabic, Ottoman, and Persian Calligraphy: Style\". [http://calligraphyqalam.com/index.html Calligraphy Qalam]., Schimmel, Annemarie (1984). ''Calligraphy and Islamic Culture''. New York: New York University Press. p. 3. {{ISBN|0814778305}}.</ref> The style later developed into several varieties, including floral, foliated, plaited or interlaced, bordered, and square kufic. Due to its straight and orderly style of lettering, Kufic was frequently used in ornamental stone carving as well as on coins.<ref>Ul Wahab, Zain; Yasmin Khan, Romana (June 30, 2016). \"The Element of Mural Art and Mediums in Potohar Region\". ''Journal of the Research Society of Pakistan''. Vol. 53; No. 1 \u2013 via Nexis Uni.</ref> It was the main script used to copy the Qur'an from the 8th to 10th century and went out of general use in the 12th century when the flowing naskh style become more practical. However, it continued to be used as a decorative element to contrast superseding styles.<ref>{{cite web|title=K\u016bfic script|url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/324418/Kufic-script|publisher=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica}}</ref>\n\nThere was no set rules of using the Kufic script; the only common feature is the angular, linear shapes of the characters. Due to the lack of standardization of early Kufic, the script differs widely between regions, ranging from very square and rigid forms to flowery and decorative ones.<ref name=qalam/>\n\nCommon varieties include<ref name=qalam/> square Kufic, a technique known as ''[[banna'i]]''.<ref name=\"BloomBlair2009\">{{cite book |author1=Jonathan M. Bloom |author2=Sheila Blair |title=The Grove encyclopedia of Islamic art and architecture |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=un4WcfEASZwC&pg=PA212 |accessdate=4 January 2012 |year=2009 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-530991-1 |pages=101, 131, 246}}</ref> Contemporary calligraphy using this style is also popular in modern decorations.\n\nDecorative Kufic inscriptions are often imitated into [[pseudo-kufic]]s in [[Middle Ages|Middle age]] and [[Renaissance]] Europe. Pseudo-kufics is especially common in [[Renaissance]] depictions of people from the [[Holy Land]]. The exact reason for the incorporation of pseudo-Kufic is unclear. It seems that Westerners mistakenly associated 13th-14th century Middle Eastern scripts with systems of writing used during the time of [[Jesus]], and thus found it natural to represent [[Early Christianity|early Christians]] in association with them.<ref>Mack, Rosamond E. Bazaar to Piazza: Islamic Trade and Italian Art, 1300\u20131600, University of California Press, 2001 {{ISBN|0-520-22131-1}}</ref>\n\n===Naskh===\n[[File:Folio from a Qur'an (Mamluk dynasty).jpg|thumb|right|[[Muhaqqaq]] script in a 14th-century Qur'an from the [[Mamluk Sultanate (Cairo)|Mamluk dynasty]].]]\n\nThe use of cursive scripts coexisted with Kufic, and historically cursive was commonly used for informal purposes.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Art of Arabic Calligraphy, a brief history |url=http://www.sakkal.com/ArtArabicCalligraphy.html |author=Mamoun Sakkal |year=1993}}</ref> With the rise of Islam, a new script was needed to fit the pace of conversions, and a well-defined cursive called [[naskh (script)|naskh]] first appeared in the 10th century. Naskh translates to \"copying,\" as it became the standard for transcribing books and manuscripts.<ref name=\":2\">Blair, Sheila S. (2006). ''Islamic Calligraphy''. Edinburgh University Press. pp. 158, 165. {{ISBN|0748612122}}.</ref> The script is the most ubiquitous among other styles, used in the Qur'an, official decrees, and private correspondence.<ref name=\"LOCFragments\">{{cite web|url=http://international.loc.gov/intldl/apochtml/apocfragments.html |title=Library of Congress, Selections of Arabic, Persian, and Ottoman Calligraphy: Qur'anic Fragments |publisher=International.loc.gov |accessdate=2013-12-04}}</ref> It became the basis of modern Arabic print.\n\nStandardization of the style was pioneered by [[Ibn Muqla]] (886&nbsp;&ndash;&#32;940 A.D.) and later expanded by [[Abu Hayan at-Tawhidi]] (died 1009 A.D.). Ibn Muqla is highly regarded in Muslim sources on calligraphy as the inventor of the naskh style, although this seems to be erroneous. Since Ibn Muqla wrote with a distinctly rounded hand, many scholars drew the conclusion that he founded this script. [[Ibn al-Bawwab]], the student of Ibn Muqla, is actually believed to have created this script.<ref name=\":2\" /> However, Ibn Muqla did establish systematic rules and proportions for shaping the letters, which use 'alif as the [[x-height]].<ref>Kampman, Frerik (2011). ''[http://www.islamicmanuscripts.info/reference/books/Kampman-2011-Typography-Bachelor-Thesis-Arabic-Frerik-Kampman-20120823-download.pdf Arabic Typography; its past and its future]''</ref>\n\nVariation of the naskh includes:\n#'''[[Thuluth]]''' was developed during the 10th century and later refined by Ahmad Tayyib Shah. Letters in this script have long vertical lines with broad spacing. The name, meaning \"third,\" is in reference to the x-height, which is one-third of the 'alif.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://calligraphyqalam.com/styles/thuluth-naskh.html|title=Thuluth and Naskh|last=Kvernen|first=Elisabeth|date=2009|website=CalligraphyQalam|access-date=26 November 2018}}</ref>\n#'''[[Reqa]]''' is a handwriting style derived from Naskh and thuluth, first appeared in the 10th century. The shape is simple with short strokes and small flourishes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://calligraphyqalam.com/styles/tawqi-riqa.html|title=Tawqi' and Riqa'|last=Kvernen|first=Elizabeth|date=2009|website=CalligraphyQalam|access-date=26 November 2018}}</ref>\n#'''[[Muhaqqaq]]''' is a majestic style used by accomplished calligraphers. It was considered one of the most beautiful scripts, as well as one of the most difficult to execute. Muhaqqaq was commonly used during the [[Mamluk Sultanate (Cairo)|Mamluk]] era, but its use became largely restricted to short phrases, such as the [[basmallah]], from the 18th century onward.<ref>Mansour, Nassar (2011). ''Sacred Script: Muhaqqaq in Islamic Calligraphy''. New York: I.B.Tauris & Co Ltd. {{ISBN|978-1-84885-439-0}}</ref>\n\n===Regional styles===\n[[File:Miremad-1.jpg|thumb|right|Nasta'liq calligraphy of a Persian poem by [[Mir Emad Hassani]], perhaps the most celebrated Persian calligrapher.]]\nWith the [[spread of Islam]], the [[Arabic script]] was established in a vast geographic area with many regions developing their own unique style. From the 14th century onward, other cursive styles began to develop in Turkey, Persia, and China.<ref name=\"LOCFragments\" />\n\n#[[Maghrebi script|'''Maghrebi''']] scripts developed from [[Kufic]] letters in the [[Maghreb]] (North Africa) and [[al-Andalus]] ([[Iberian Peninsula|Iberia]]), Maghrebi scripts are traditionally written with a pointed tip (\u0627\u0644\u0642\u0644\u0645 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0630\u0628\u0628), producing a line of even thickness. Within the Maghrebi family, there are different styles including the cursive ''mujawher'' and the ceremonial ''mabsut.''\n##[[Maghrebi script#West African Maghrebi scripts|'''Sudani''']] scripts developed in [[Sudan (region)|''Biled as-Sudan'']] (the [[West Africa|West African]] [[Sahel]]) and can be considered a subcategory of [[Maghrebi script|Maghrebi scripts]]\n#'''[[Diwani]]''' is a cursive style of Arabic calligraphy developed during the reign of the early [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman Turks]] in the 16th and early 17th centuries. It was invented by [[Housam Roumi]], and reached its height of popularity under [[S\u00fcleyman I the Magnificent]] (1520\u20131566).<ref>{{cite web|title=Diwani script|url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/166798/diwani-script|publisher=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica}}</ref> Spaces between letters are often narrow, and lines ascend upwards from right to left. Larger variations called ''djali'' are filled with dense decorations of dots and diacritical marks in the space between, giving it a compact appearance. Diwani is difficult to read and write due to its heavy stylization and became the ideal script for writing court documents as it ensured confidentiality and prevented forgery.<ref name=\"qalam\" />\n# '''[[Nasta'liq]]''' is a [[cursive]] style originally devised to write the [[Persian language]] for literary and non-Qur'anic works.<ref name=qalam>{{cite web| title= An Introduction of Arabic, Ottoman, and Persian Calligraphy: Style|author=Kvernen, Elizabeth |year=2009|publisher=Calligraphy Qalam |url=http://calligraphyqalam.com/styles/index.html}}</ref>  Nasta'liq is thought to be a later development of the naskh and the earlier ta'liq script used in Iran.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ta'liq Script |url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/581497/taliq-script|publisher=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica}}</ref> Quite rapidly gaining popularity as a script in South Asia. The name ''ta'liq'' means \"hanging,\" and refers to the slightly sloped quality of lines of text in this script. Letters have short vertical strokes with broad and sweeping horizontal strokes. The shapes are deep, hook-like, and have high contrast.<ref name=qalam/> A variant called ''[[Shikasta Nasta\u02bfl\u012bq|Shikasteh]]'' was developed in the 17th century for more formal contexts.\n# '''[[Sini (script)|Sini]]''' is a style developed in China. The shape is greatly influenced by [[Chinese calligraphy]], using a horsehair brush instead of the standard reed pen. A famous modern calligrapher in this tradition is [[Hajji]] [[Noor Deen Mi Guangjiang]].'''<ref>[http://www.hajinoordeen.com/gallery.html \"Gallery\"], ''Haji Noor Deen''.</ref><!--==Calligrams== [[File:Mogultughra.jpg|thumb|leftThe official imperial [[Tughra]] of the [[Mughal Empire]].]] [[File:The Bismillah India.jpg|thumb|Bismillah calligraphy from the [[Mughal Empire]].]]  [[Calligraphy]], the most Islamic of arts in the Muslim world, also has its figurative sides. By interweaving written words, made from an \"Allah\", a \"Muhammad\", a \"[[Basmala|Bismillah]]\", etc., or using [[micrography]],<ref name = \"bnf\">[http://expositions.bnf.fr/parole/grand/134.htm BNF - Torah, Bible, Coran]. In French.</ref> calligraphers produced anthropomorphic figures ([['Ali]], the Ideal Human of [[Sufi|mystics]], a praying man,<ref name=Praying>{{cite web|title=Praying Man|url=http://www.ethiopianmuslims.net/Images/calligraphy2.jpg|publisher=Ethiopian Muslims Network|accessdate=29 December 2012|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081217032258/http://www.ethiopianmuslims.net/Images/calligraphy2.jpg|archivedate=2008-12-17}}</ref> a face), zoomorphisms (symbolic creatures, most from the Shi'a iconography, like the lion (Ali \"the Lion of God\")<ref name = \"Cartage\">[http://www.cartage.org.lb/en/themes/GeogHist/histories/Oldcivilization/Egyptology/Calligraphy/art5.jpg Lion of 'Ali].</ref> horse ([['Ali]]'s [[Duldul (mule)|Duldul]]),<ref name = \"Levha\">[http://www.levha.net/calligraphy/calligraphy_index.html Horse of 'Ali].</ref> fish,<ref name = \"bnf\" /> stork or other bird (the qur'anic [[Hudhud]])<ref name = \"IslArch\">[https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20060625045753/http://www.islamicarchitecture.org/art/images/calligraphy/islamic.calligraphy.birdtext.101.gif HudHud].{{Dead link|date=June 2009}}</ref><ref name = \"UCSC\">[http://www.ucsc.edu/currents/01-02/art/islamic_bird.jpg Islamic Bird], ''UC Santa Cruz Currents Online''.</ref>) and inanimate representations (a sword ([[Zulfiqar|Dhu al-Fiqar]]), a mosque, a ship (made from the letter ''[[Waw (letter)|waw]]'', a symbol of mystical union, literally meaning \"and,\" in Arabic)). Calligrams are related to Muslim mysticism and popular with many leading calligraphers in [[Turkey]], [[Persian Empire|Persia]] and [[India]] from the 17th century onward.  Although striking in appearance, calligrams have never been regarded as appropriate or a decent expression of the art by the master calligraphers. Many calligrams therefore were produced by either folk calligraphers or for the interest of uncultivated people. These calligrams were not exhibited in mosques or Sufi convents in the Ottoman state, for example.  An element in this perspective is the rejection of the interpretation by the heretic Hurufiyyah Sufi order which sees letters as true manifestations of the fate, events and creation in themselves.  In the teachings of calligraphy, figurative imagery is used to help visualize the shape of letters to trace, for example, the letter ''ha' '' looks in ''nasta'liq'' similar to two eyes, as its Persian name implies: \"he' two eyes\" ''he' do cheshm''). In literature and poetry seeing in letters a reflection of the natural world goes back to the [[Abbasid]] times.  One of the contemporary masters of the calligram genre is [[Hassan Massoudy]] and [[Wissam Shawkat]].  Good commercial examples are the logos of [[Al Jazeera]], an international news station based at [[Qatar]], and the [[Edinburgh Middle East Report]], a Scottish academic journal on the [[Middle East]], and also the work of the calligrapher and designer Wissam Shawkat.-->'''\n\n===Modern ===\nIn the post-colonial era, artists working in North Africa and the Middle East transformed Arabic calligraphy into a modern art movement, known as the ''[[Hurufiyya movement]]''.<ref name=\":0\">Flood, Necipo\u011flu (2017). [https://www.worldcat.org/title/a-companion-to-islamic-art-and-architecture-2-from-the-mongols-to-modernism/oclc/1006377297&referer=brief_results A Companion to Islamic Art and Architecture]. Volume II. Hoboken: John Wiley & Sons. pp. 1294. {{ISBN|1119068665}}. OCLC 1006377297.</ref> Artists working in this style use calligraphy as a graphic element within contemporary artwork.<ref>Mavrakis, N., [https://mjmes.wordpress.com/2013/03/08/article-5/ \"The Hurufiyah Art Movement in Middle Eastern Art\"], ''McGill Journal of Middle Eastern Studies Blog''</ref><ref>A. and Masters, C., ''A-Z Great Modern Artists'', Hachette UK, 2015, p. 56</ref>\n\nThe term, ''hurufiyya'' is derived from the Arabic term, ''harf'' for letter. Traditionally, the term was charged with Sufi intellectual and esoteric meaning.<ref name=\":0\" /> It is an explicit reference to a medieval system of teaching involving [[political theology]] and lettrism. In this theology, letters were seen as primordial signifiers and manipulators of the cosmos.'''<ref>Mir-Kasimov, O., ''Words of Power: Hurufi Teachings Between Shi'ism and Sufism in Medieval Islam,'' I.B. Tauris and the Institute of Ismaili Studies, 2015</ref>'''\n\nHurufiyya artists blended Western art concepts with an artistic identity and sensibility drawn from their own culture and heritage. These artists integrated Islamic visual traditions, especially calligraphy, and elements of modern art into syncretic contemporary compositions.<ref>Lindgren, A. and Ross, S., ''The Modernist World,'' Routledge, 2015, p. 495; Mavrakis, N., \"The Hurufiyah Art Movement in Middle Eastern Art,\" ''McGill Journal of Middle Eastern Studies Blog,'' Online: https://mjmes.wordpress.com/2013/03/08/article-5/; Tuohy, A. and Masters, C., ''A-Z Great Modern Artists,'' Hachette UK, 2015, p. 56</ref> Although hurufiyyah artists struggled to find their own individual dialogue within the context of nationalism, they also worked towards an aesthetic that transcended national boundaries and represented a broader affiliation with an Islamic identity.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe hurufiyya artistic style as a movement most likely began in North Africa around 1955 with the work of [[Ibrahim el-Salahi]].<ref name=\":0\" /> However, the use of calligraphy in modern artworks appears to have emerged independently in various Islamic states. Artists working in this were often unaware of other hurufiyya artists's works, allowing for different manifestations of the style to emerge in different regions.<ref>Dadi. I., \"Ibrahim El Salahi and Calligraphic Modernism in a Comparative Perspective,\" ''South Atlantic Quarterly,'' 109 (3), 2010 pp 555-576, DOI:https://doi.org/10.1215/00382876-2010-006; Flood, F.B. and Necipoglu, G. (eds) ''A Companion to Islamic Art and Architecture,'' Wiley, 2017, p. 1294</ref> In Sudan, for instance, artworks include both Islamic calligraphy and West African motifs.<ref>Flood, Necipo\u011flu (2017). [https://www.worldcat.org/title/a-companion-to-islamic-art-and-architecture-2-from-the-mongols-to-modernism/oclc/1006377297&referer=brief_results A Companion to Islamic Art and Architecture]. Volume II. Hoboken: John Wiley & Sons. pp. 1298-1299. {{ISBN|1119068665}}. OCLC 1006377297.</ref>\n\n[[File:Roof of Frere Hall.JPG|thumb|The Roof of [[Frere Hall]], Karachi, Pakistan, c. 1986. Mural by artist, [[Sadequain|Sadequain Naqqash]] integrates calligraphy elements into a modern artwork]]\n\nThe hurufiyya art movement was not confined to painters and included artists working in a variety of media.<ref>Mavrakis, N., \"The Hurufiyah Art Movement in Middle Eastern Art,\" ''McGill Journal of Middle Eastern Studies Blog,'' Online: https://mjmes.wordpress.com/2013/03/08/article-5/;Tuohy {{cite web |url=https://mjmes.wordpress.com/2013/03/08/article-5/;Tuohy |title=Unknown |access-date=25 March 2020}}{{dead link|date=March 2020|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}, A. and Masters, C., ''A-Z Great Modern Artists,'' Hachette UK, 2015, p. 56; Dadi. I., \"Ibrahim El Salahi and Calligraphic Modernism in a Comparative Perspective,\" ''South Atlantic Quarterly,'' 109 (3), 2010 pp 555-576, DOI:https://doi.org/10.1215/00382876-2010-006</ref> One example is the Jordanian ceramicist, [[Mahmoud Taha]] who combined the traditional aesthetics of calligraphy with skilled craftsmanship.<ref>Asfour. M., \"A Window on Contemporary Arab Art,\" NABAD Art Gallery, Online: http://www.nabadartgallery.com/</ref> Although not affiliated with the hurufiyya movement, the contemporary artist [[Shirin Neshat]] integrates Arabic text into her black-and-white photography, creating contrast and duality. In Iraq, the movement was known as ''Al Bu'd al Wahad'' (or the [[One Dimension Group]])\",<ref>\"Shaker Hassan Al Said,\" Darat al Funum, Online: www.daratalfunun.org/main/activit/curentl/anniv/exhib3.html;  Flood, Necipo\u011flu (2017). [https://www.worldcat.org/title/a-companion-to-islamic-art-and-architecture-2-from-the-mongols-to-modernism/oclc/1006377297&referer=brief_results A Companion to Islamic Art and Architecture]. Volume II. Hoboken: John Wiley & Sons. pp. 1294. {{ISBN|1119068665}}. OCLC 1006377297.</ref> and in Iran, it was known as the [[Iranian modern and contemporary art#Saqqakhaneh movement|Saqqa-Khaneh movement]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nWestern art has influenced Arabic calligraphy in other ways, with forms such as [[calligraffiti]], which is the use of calligraphy in public art to make politico-social messages or to ornament public buildings and spaces.<ref>Grebenstein, M., ''Calligraphy Bible: A Complete Guide to More Than 100 Essential Projects and Techniques,'' 2012, p. 5</ref> Notable Islamic calligraffiti artists include: [[Yazan Halwani]] active in Lebanon'''<ref>Alabaster, Olivia. [http://www.dailystar.com.lb/Culture/Lifestyle/2013/Feb-09/205688-i-like-to-write-beirut-as-its-the-city-that-gave-us-everything.ashx#axzz3DCxf8Utr; \"I like to write Beirut as it\u2019s the city that gave us everything\"], ''[[The Daily Star (Lebanon)|The Daily Star]]'', Beirut, 09 February 2013</ref>''', [[EL Seed|el Seed]] working in France and Tunisia, and Caiand [[A1one]] in Tehran.<ref>{{cite news|last=Vandalog|title=A1one in Tehran IRAN|url=http://blog.vandalog.com/2011/05/from-a1one-in-tehran-iran/|accessdate=8 October 2012|newspaper=Vandalog|date=3 May 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n===Kufic===\n<gallery>\nImage:Qur'an folio 11th century kufic.jpg|Kufic script in an 11th-century Qur'an\nFile:Folio Blue Quran Met 2004.88.jpg|[[Maghrebi script|Maghrebi Kufic]] script in the 9th or 10th century [[Blue Qur'an|Blue Quran]]\nFile:Jame mosque yazd tilework.jpg|Square kufic tilework in Yazd, Iran\nFile:Cup votive inscriptions MET 40-170-15.jpg|Under-glaze terracotta bowl from the 11th century [[Nishapur]]\nFile:Hamdanid gold dinar, Nasir al-Dawla and Sayf al-Dawla.jpg|[[Gold dinar]] from 10th century Syria\nImage:An example of Kufic Calligraphy.jpg|A Kufic calligraphy in [[Chota Imambara]]\n</gallery>\n\n===Naskh===\n<gallery>\nImage:Qur'anic Manuscript - Mid to Late 15th Century, Turkey.jpg|Muhaqqaq script in a 15th-century Qur'an from Turkey.\nFile:Qur'an manuscript Surat al-Nisa'. (1).tif|Muhaqqaq script in a 13th-century Qur'an.\nFile:Muhammad ibn Pir Ahmad al-shahir bi-Ibn Arghun al-Shirazi - Text Page with Dedication to the Ottoman Sultan Selim I - Walters W5912A - Full Page.jpg|Naskh script in an early 16th-century Ottoman manuscript dedicated to [[Selim I]].\nFile:Ijazah3.jpg|Diploma of competency in calligraphy, written with thuluth and naskh script.\nFile:Mausol\u00e9e de Touman Aka (Shah-i-Zinda, Samarcande) (6009410911).jpg|Thuluth script tile in [[Samarkand]].\nImage:Kalligr\u00e1fia Hagia Sophia.jpg|Calligraphy of Ali decorating [[Hagia Sophia]].\n</gallery>\n\n===Regional varieties===\n<gallery>\nImage:Ta'liq Script.jpg|Ta'liq script in an Ottoman manuscript.\nImage:Brooklyn Museum - Sample of Calligraphy in Persian Nasta'liq Script.jpg|Nasta'liq Script.\nImage:Nastaliq-proportions.jpg|Proportions of the nasta'liq script.\nFile:Qur'anic Manuscript - Sini script.jpg|Sini script in an 11th-century Qur'an.\nFile:Chinese quran.jpg|Chinese Qur'an written in Sini with Chinese translation.\nImage:The Islamic calligraphy.jpg|The Word \"Allah\" written in the Form of [[Columbidae|Pigeon]] in [[Chota Imambara]]\n</gallery>\n\n===Modern examples===\n<gallery>\nFile:Bismillah.JPG|[[Bismallah]] calligraphy.\nFile:Muhammad calligraphy.svg|[[Muhammad]] calligraphy\nFile:Bismillah.svg|[[Bismallah]] calligraphy.\n\nFile:Caligrafia arabe pajaro.svg|An example of [[zoomorphic]] calligraphy.\nFile:Flag of Taliban.svg|flag of the [[Islamic Emirate of Afghanistan]] 2001.\nFile:Al jazeera Calligraphy Animation.gif|Animation showing the calligraphic composition of the [[Al Jazeera]] logo.\nFile:Emirates logo.svg|The Emirates logo is written in traditional Arabic calligraphy.\n\nFile:Learning Arabic calligraphy.jpg|The instruments and work of a student calligrapher.\nFile:Menulis khat.jpg|Islamic calligraphy performed by a Malay Muslim in Malaysia. Calligrapher is making a rough draft.\n</gallery>\n\n==List of calligraphers==\nSome classical calligraphers:\n;Medieval\n*[[Ibn Muqla]] (d. 939/940)\n*[[Ibn al-Bawwab]] (d. 1022)\n*[[Fakhr-un-Nisa]] (12th century)\n*[[Yaqut al-Musta'simi]] (d. 1298)\n*[[Mir Ali Tabrizi]] (d. 14th\u201315th century)\n;\n;Ottoman era {{anchor|Ottoman-era calligraphers}}\n\n*[[Sheikh Hamdullah|Shaykh Hamdullah]] (1436\u20131520)\n*[[Hamid Ayta\u00e7]] (1891-1982)\n*[[Seyyid Kasim Gubari]] (d. 1624)\n*[[H\u00e2fiz Osman]] (1642\u20131698)\n*[[Mustafa R\u00e2kim]] (1757\u20131826)\n*[[Mehmed Shevki Efendi]] (1829\u20131887)\n;{{See|List of Ottoman calligraphers}}\n;Contemporary\n\n* [[Ali Adjalli]] (b. 1939), Iran\n* [[Wijdan Ali]] (b. 1939),  Jordan\n* [[Hashem Muhammad al-Baghdadi]] in Iraq \n* [[Hamid Ayta\u00e7]]\n* [[Mohammad Hosni]] Syria\n* [[Shakir Hassan Al Said|Shakkir Hassan Al Sa'id]] (1925-2004) in Iraq\n* [[Madiha Omar]] Iraqi-American\n* [[Sadequain|Sadequain Naqqash]] (1930-1987), Pakistan\n* [[Ibrahim el-Salahi]] (b. 1930), Sudan\n* [[Mahmoud Taha]] (b. 1942), Jordan\n* [[Hossein Zenderoudi|Charles Hossein Zenderoudi]] (b. 1937), Iran\n* [[Abdulraouf Baydoun]] (b. 1956), Syria\n*[[Mohamed Zakariya]] (b. 1942), United States of America\n* [[Hassan Massoudy]] (b. 1944), Irak France\n*[https://www.facebook.com/amirkamalcalligraphy Amir Kamal] (b. 1972), Pakistan\n\n==See also==\n* [[Illuminated manuscript]]\n* [[Islamic architecture]]\n* [[Islamic Golden Age]]\n* [[Islamic graffiti]]\n* [[Islamic miniature]]\n* [[Islamic pottery]]\n* [[Museum of Turkish Calligraphy Art]]\n* [[Ottoman Turkish language]]\n* [[Persian calligraphy]]\n* [[Sini (script)]]\n* [[Uthman Taha]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Sister project links| wikt=no | commons=Category:Islamic calligraphy | b=no | n=no | q=Islamic calligraphy | s=no | v=no | voy=no | species=no | d=no}}\n\n* [http://www.themuslimculture.com/islamic-calligraphy-of-quran-verses-and-other-terms/ Islamic Calligraphy Pictures]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110228232705/http://www.mastersofistanbul.com/en/ustalar/2/calligraphy mastersofistanbul.com]\n* [https://baradariarts.com/ baradariarts.com]\n* [http://www.pbase.com/dosseman/calligraphy Gallery with lots of calligraphy in Turkish mosque]\n*[https://www.reed.edu/persian-calligraphy/en/index.html Anthology of Persian calligraphers from 10th to 20th centuries]\n{{Islamic calligraphy}}\n{{Islamic art}}\n{{Islamic architecture}}\n{{Islamic studies}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}}\n\n[[Category:Islamic calligraphy| ]]\n[[Category:Islamic art]]\n[[Category:Islamic culture]]\n[[Category:Islamic architectural elements]]\n[[Category:Ottoman culture]]\n[[Category:Islamic arts of the book]]\n[[Category:Islamic illuminated manuscripts]]\n[[Category:Persian calligraphy]]\n[[Category:Arabic calligraphy]]\n", "text_old": "\n\n{{short description|Artistic practice of calligraphy in Islamic contexts}}\n[[File:basmalah-1wm.svg|right|thumb|The [[Basmala]] in an 18th-century Islamic calligraphy from the [[Ottoman empire|Ottoman]] region, Thuluth script.]]\n{{Calligraphy}}\n\n'''Islamic calligraphy''' is the artistic practice of [[penmanship|handwriting]] and [[calligraphy]],<!-- and by extension, [[bookbinding|bookmaking]],--> based upon the [[Arabic alphabet|alphabet]] in the lands sharing a common Islamic cultural heritage. It includes [[Arabic calligraphy|Arabic Calligraphy]], [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]], and [[Persian calligraphy]].<ref name=\"Bloom\">{{cite book |last=Blair |first=Sheila S. |title=The art and architecture of Islam : 1250\u20131800 |year=1995 |publisher=Yale University Press |location=New Haven |isbn=0-300-06465-9 |edition=Reprinted with corrections |author2=Bloom, Jonathan M.}}</ref><!--{{rp|218}}--><ref name=\"ens\">Chapman, Caroline (2012). ''Encyclopedia of Islamic Art and Architecture'', {{ISBN|978-979-099-631-1}}</ref> It is known in [[Arabic language|Arabic]] as ''khatt Islami'' ({{rtl-lang|ar|\u062e\u0637 \u0625\u0633\u0644\u0627\u0645\u064a}}), meaning Islamic line, design, or construction.<ref name=\"typography\">{{cite web| title=Arabic calligraphy as a typographic exercise| url=http://ilovetypography.com/2008/07/10/arabic-calligraphy-as-a-typographic-exercise/ |author=Julia Kaestle |date=10 July 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe development of Islamic calligraphy is strongly tied to the [[Qur'an]]; chapters and excerpts from the Qur'an are a common and almost universal text upon which Islamic calligraphy is based. However, Islamic calligraphy is not limited to strictly religious subjects, objects, or spaces. Like all [[Islamic art]], it encompasses a diverse array of works created in a wide variety of contexts.<ref>Blair, Sheila S. (Spring 2003). \"The Mirage of Islamic Art: Reflections on the Study of an Unwieldy Field\". ''The Art Bulletin''. '''85''': 152\u2013184 \u2013 via JSTOR.</ref><!--{{rp|222}}--> The prevalence of calligraphy in Islamic art is not directly related to its non-figural tradition; rather, it reflects the centrality of the notion of writing and written text in Islam.<ref>Allen, Terry (1988). ''Five Essays on Islamic Art''. Sebastopol, CA: Solipsist Press. pp. 17\u201337. {{ISBN|0944940005}}.</ref> It is noteworthy, for instance, that the Prophet Muhammad is related to have said: \"The first thing God created was the pen.\"<ref name=\":1\">Roxburgh, David J. (2008). \"\"The Eye is Favored for Seeing the Writing's Form\": On the Sensual and the Sensuous in Islamic Calligraphy\". ''Muqarnas''. '''25''': 275\u2013298 \u2013 via JSTOR.</ref>\n\nIslamic calligraphy developed from two major styles: [[Kufic]] and [[Naskh (script)|Naskh]]. There are several variations of each, as well as regionally specific styles. Arabic or Persian calligraphy has also been incorporated into [[modern art]], beginning with the post-colonial period in the Middle East, as well as the more recent style of [[calligraffiti]].\n\n<!--[[Arabic language|Arabic]], [[Persian language|Persian]] and [[Ottoman Turkish language|Ottoman Turkish]] calligraphy is associated with abstract [[Arabesque (Islamic art)|arabesque]] motifs on the walls and ceilings of [[mosque]]s as well as on the page. Contemporary [[artists]] in the [[Islamic world]] draw on the heritage of calligraphy to use calligraphic inscriptions or abstractions in their work. They used it to represent God because they denied representing God with images.<ref name=\"Bernard Lewis\">Bernard Lewis and Butnzie Ellis Churchill, ''Islam : the Religion and the People'', {{ISBN|978-0-13-223085-8}}</rf>-->\n\n==Instruments and media==\nThe traditional instrument of the Islamic calligrapher is the [[qalam]], a [[pen]] normally made of dried [[Phragmites|reed]] or [[bamboo]]. The [[ink]] is often in [[Colour|color]] and chosen so that its intensity can vary greatly, creating dynamism and movement in the letter forms. Some styles are often written using a metallic-tip pen.\n[[File:Niebuhr Beschreibung von Arabien Tab XIII.png|thumbnail|Five principal Arabic calligraphic cursive styles:<br />\n{{ordered list|\n| Naskh\n| Nasta\u2018liq\n| Diwani\n| Thuluth\n| Reqa\n}}]]\nIslamic calligraphy can be applied to a wide range of decorative mediums other than paper, such as tiles, vessels, carpets, and stone.<ref name=ens/> Before the advent of paper, papyrus and parchment were used for writing. During the 9th century, an influx of paper from China revolutionized calligraphy. While monasteries in Europe treasured a few dozen volumes, libraries in the [[Muslim world]] regularly contained hundreds and even thousands of books.<ref name=Bloom>{{cite book |last=Blair |first=Sheila S. |title=The art and architecture of Islam : 1250\u20131800 |year=1995 |publisher=Yale University Press |location=New Haven |isbn=0-300-06465-9 |edition=Reprinted with corrections |author2=Bloom, Jonathan M.}}</ref>{{rp|218}}\n\nFor centuries, the art of writing has fulfilled a central iconographic function in Islamic art.<ref>Tabbaa, Yasser (1991). \"The Transformation of Arabic Writing: Part I, Qur'\u0101nic Calligraphy\". ''Ars Orientalis''. '''21''': 119\u2013148.</ref> Although the academic tradition of Islamic calligraphy began in Baghdad, the center of the Islamic empire during much of its early history, it eventually spread as far as India and Spain.\n\nCoins were another support for calligraphy. Beginning in 692, the Islamic caliphate reformed the coinage of the Near East by replacing Byzantine Christian imagery with Islamic phrases inscribed in Arabic. This was especially true for dinars, or gold coins of high value. Generally, the coins were inscribed with quotes from the Qur'an.\n\nBy the tenth century, the Persians, who had converted to Islam, began weaving inscriptions onto elaborately patterned silks. So precious were textiles featuring Arabic text that Crusaders brought them to Europe as prized possessions. A notable example is the [[Suaire de Saint-Josse]], used to wrap the bones of St. Josse in the Abbey of St. Josse-sur-Mer, near Caen in northwestern France.<ref name=Bloom />{{rp|223\u20135}}\n\nAs Islamic calligraphy is highly venerated, most works follow examples set by well-established calligraphers, with the exception of secular or contemporary works. In the Islamic tradition, calligraphers underwent extensive training in three stages, including the study of their teacher's models, in order to be granted certification.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Styles==\n===Kufic===\n[[File:A section of the Koran - Google Art Project.jpg|thumb|250px|left|9th century [[Qur'an]], an early kufic example from the [[Abbasid dynasty|Abbasid period]]]]\n[[File:Bowl with Kufic Calligraphy, 10th century.jpg|thumb|250px|left|''Bowl with [[Kufic]] [[Calligraphy]]'', 10th century. [[Brooklyn Museum]]]]\n\n[[Kufic]] is the oldest form of the Arabic script. The style emphasizes rigid and angular strokes, which appears as a modified form of the old [[Nabataean alphabet|Nabataean script]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=A Companion to Islamic Art and Architecture|last=Flood, Necipo\u011flu|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|year=2017|isbn=9781119068570|volume=Volume I|location=Hoboken|pages=109\u2013110|oclc=963439648}}</ref> The Archaic Kufi consisted of about 17 letters without diacritic dots or accents. Diacritical markings were added during the 7th century to help readers with pronunciation of the Qur'an and other important documents, increasing the number of Arabic letters to 28.<ref>Schimmel, Annemarie (1984). ''[http://universityoftexasbrownsville.worldcat.org/title/calligraphy-and-islamic-culture/oclc/20420019&referer=brief_results Calligraphy and Islamic Culture]''. New York: New York University Press. p. 4. {{ISBN|0814778305}}.</ref> Although some scholars dispute this, Kufic script was supposedly developed around the end of the 7th century in [[Kufa]], Iraq, from which it takes its name.<ref>Kvernen, Elizabeth (2009). \"An Introduction of Arabic, Ottoman, and Persian Calligraphy: Style\". [http://calligraphyqalam.com/index.html Calligraphy Qalam]., Schimmel, Annemarie (1984). ''Calligraphy and Islamic Culture''. New York: New York University Press. p. 3. {{ISBN|0814778305}}.</ref> The style later developed into several varieties, including floral, foliated, plaited or interlaced, bordered, and square kufic. Due to its straight and orderly style of lettering, Kufic was frequently used in ornamental stone carving as well as on coins.<ref>Ul Wahab, Zain; Yasmin Khan, Romana (June 30, 2016). \"The Element of Mural Art and Mediums in Potohar Region\". ''Journal of the Research Society of Pakistan''. Vol. 53; No. 1 \u2013 via Nexis Uni.</ref> It was the main script used to copy the Qur'an from the 8th to 10th century and went out of general use in the 12th century when the flowing naskh style become more practical. However, it continued to be used as a decorative element to contrast superseding styles.<ref>{{cite web|title=K\u016bfic script|url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/324418/Kufic-script|publisher=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica}}</ref>\n\nThere was no set rules of using the Kufic script; the only common feature is the angular, linear shapes of the characters. Due to the lack of standardization of early Kufic, the script differs widely between regions, ranging from very square and rigid forms to flowery and decorative ones.<ref name=qalam/>\n\nCommon varieties include<ref name=qalam/> square Kufic, a technique known as ''[[banna'i]]''.<ref name=\"BloomBlair2009\">{{cite book |author1=Jonathan M. Bloom |author2=Sheila Blair |title=The Grove encyclopedia of Islamic art and architecture |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=un4WcfEASZwC&pg=PA212 |accessdate=4 January 2012 |year=2009 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-530991-1 |pages=101, 131, 246}}</ref> Contemporary calligraphy using this style is also popular in modern decorations.\n\nDecorative Kufic inscriptions are often imitated into [[pseudo-kufic]]s in [[Middle Ages|Middle age]] and [[Renaissance]] Europe. Pseudo-kufics is especially common in [[Renaissance]] depictions of people from the [[Holy Land]]. The exact reason for the incorporation of pseudo-Kufic is unclear. It seems that Westerners mistakenly associated 13th-14th century Middle Eastern scripts with systems of writing used during the time of [[Jesus]], and thus found it natural to represent [[Early Christianity|early Christians]] in association with them.<ref>Mack, Rosamond E. Bazaar to Piazza: Islamic Trade and Italian Art, 1300\u20131600, University of California Press, 2001 {{ISBN|0-520-22131-1}}</ref>\n\n===Naskh===\n[[File:Folio from a Qur'an (Mamluk dynasty).jpg|thumb|right|[[Muhaqqaq]] script in a 14th-century Qur'an from the [[Mamluk Sultanate (Cairo)|Mamluk dynasty]].]]\n\nThe use of cursive scripts coexisted with Kufic, and historically cursive was commonly used for informal purposes.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Art of Arabic Calligraphy, a brief history |url=http://www.sakkal.com/ArtArabicCalligraphy.html |author=Mamoun Sakkal |year=1993}}</ref> With the rise of Islam, a new script was needed to fit the pace of conversions, and a well-defined cursive called [[naskh (script)|naskh]] first appeared in the 10th century. Naskh translates to \"copying,\" as it became the standard for transcribing books and manuscripts.<ref name=\":2\">Blair, Sheila S. (2006). ''Islamic Calligraphy''. Edinburgh University Press. pp. 158, 165. {{ISBN|0748612122}}.</ref> The script is the most ubiquitous among other styles, used in the Qur'an, official decrees, and private correspondence.<ref name=\"LOCFragments\">{{cite web|url=http://international.loc.gov/intldl/apochtml/apocfragments.html |title=Library of Congress, Selections of Arabic, Persian, and Ottoman Calligraphy: Qur'anic Fragments |publisher=International.loc.gov |accessdate=2013-12-04}}</ref> It became the basis of modern Arabic print.\n\nStandardization of the style was pioneered by [[Ibn Muqla]] (886&nbsp;&ndash;&#32;940 A.D.) and later expanded by [[Abu Hayan at-Tawhidi]] (died 1009 A.D.). Ibn Muqla is highly regarded in Muslim sources on calligraphy as the inventor of the naskh style, although this seems to be erroneous. Since Ibn Muqla wrote with a distinctly rounded hand, many scholars drew the conclusion that he founded this script. [[Ibn al-Bawwab]], the student of Ibn Muqla, is actually believed to have created this script.<ref name=\":2\" /> However, Ibn Muqla did establish systematic rules and proportions for shaping the letters, which use 'alif as the [[x-height]].<ref>Kampman, Frerik (2011). ''[http://www.islamicmanuscripts.info/reference/books/Kampman-2011-Typography-Bachelor-Thesis-Arabic-Frerik-Kampman-20120823-download.pdf Arabic Typography; its past and its future]''</ref>\n\nVariation of the naskh includes:\n#'''[[Thuluth]]''' was developed during the 10th century and later refined by Ahmad Tayyib Shah. Letters in this script have long vertical lines with broad spacing. The name, meaning \"third,\" is in reference to the x-height, which is one-third of the 'alif.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://calligraphyqalam.com/styles/thuluth-naskh.html|title=Thuluth and Naskh|last=Kvernen|first=Elisabeth|date=2009|website=CalligraphyQalam|access-date=26 November 2018}}</ref>\n#'''[[Reqa]]''' is a handwriting style derived from Naskh and thuluth, first appeared in the 10th century. The shape is simple with short strokes and small flourishes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://calligraphyqalam.com/styles/tawqi-riqa.html|title=Tawqi' and Riqa'|last=Kvernen|first=Elizabeth|date=2009|website=CalligraphyQalam|access-date=26 November 2018}}</ref>\n#'''[[Muhaqqaq]]''' is a majestic style used by accomplished calligraphers. It was considered one of the most beautiful scripts, as well as one of the most difficult to execute. Muhaqqaq was commonly used during the [[Mamluk Sultanate (Cairo)|Mamluk]] era, but its use became largely restricted to short phrases, such as the [[basmallah]], from the 18th century onward.<ref>Mansour, Nassar (2011). ''Sacred Script: Muhaqqaq in Islamic Calligraphy''. New York: I.B.Tauris & Co Ltd. {{ISBN|978-1-84885-439-0}}</ref>\n\n===Regional styles===\n[[File:Miremad-1.jpg|thumb|right|Nasta'liq calligraphy of a Persian poem by [[Mir Emad Hassani]], perhaps the most celebrated Persian calligrapher.]]\nWith the [[spread of Islam]], the [[Arabic script]] was established in a vast geographic area with many regions developing their own unique style. From the 14th century onward, other cursive styles began to develop in Turkey, Persia, and China.<ref name=\"LOCFragments\" />\n\n#[[Maghrebi script|'''Maghrebi''']] scripts developed from [[Kufic]] letters in the [[Maghreb]] (North Africa) and [[al-Andalus]] ([[Iberian Peninsula|Iberia]]), Maghrebi scripts are traditionally written with a pointed tip (\u0627\u0644\u0642\u0644\u0645 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0630\u0628\u0628), producing a line of even thickness. Within the Maghrebi family, there are different styles including the cursive ''mujawher'' and the ceremonial ''mabsut.''\n##[[Maghrebi script#West African Maghrebi scripts|'''Sudani''']] scripts developed in [[Sudan (region)|''Biled as-Sudan'']] (the [[West Africa|West African]] [[Sahel]]) and can be considered a subcategory of [[Maghrebi script|Maghrebi scripts]]\n#'''[[Diwani]]''' is a cursive style of Arabic calligraphy developed during the reign of the early [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman Turks]] in the 16th and early 17th centuries. It was invented by [[Housam Roumi]], and reached its height of popularity under [[S\u00fcleyman I the Magnificent]] (1520\u20131566).<ref>{{cite web|title=Diwani script|url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/166798/diwani-script|publisher=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica}}</ref> Spaces between letters are often narrow, and lines ascend upwards from right to left. Larger variations called ''djali'' are filled with dense decorations of dots and diacritical marks in the space between, giving it a compact appearance. Diwani is difficult to read and write due to its heavy stylization and became the ideal script for writing court documents as it ensured confidentiality and prevented forgery.<ref name=\"qalam\" />\n# '''[[Nasta'liq]]''' is a [[cursive]] style originally devised to write the [[Persian language]] for literary and non-Qur'anic works.<ref name=qalam>{{cite web| title= An Introduction of Arabic, Ottoman, and Persian Calligraphy: Style|author=Kvernen, Elizabeth |year=2009|publisher=Calligraphy Qalam |url=http://calligraphyqalam.com/styles/index.html}}</ref>  Nasta'liq is thought to be a later development of the naskh and the earlier ta'liq script used in Iran.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ta'liq Script |url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/581497/taliq-script|publisher=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica}}</ref> Quite rapidly gaining popularity as a script in South Asia. The name ''ta'liq'' means \"hanging,\" and refers to the slightly sloped quality of lines of text in this script. Letters have short vertical strokes with broad and sweeping horizontal strokes. The shapes are deep, hook-like, and have high contrast.<ref name=qalam/> A variant called ''[[Shikasta Nasta\u02bfl\u012bq|Shikasteh]]'' was developed in the 17th century for more formal contexts.\n# '''[[Sini (script)|Sini]]''' is a style developed in China. The shape is greatly influenced by [[Chinese calligraphy]], using a horsehair brush instead of the standard reed pen. A famous modern calligrapher in this tradition is [[Hajji]] [[Noor Deen Mi Guangjiang]].'''<ref>[http://www.hajinoordeen.com/gallery.html \"Gallery\"], ''Haji Noor Deen''.</ref><!--==Calligrams== [[File:Mogultughra.jpg|thumb|leftThe official imperial [[Tughra]] of the [[Mughal Empire]].]] [[File:The Bismillah India.jpg|thumb|Bismillah calligraphy from the [[Mughal Empire]].]]  [[Calligraphy]], the most Islamic of arts in the Muslim world, also has its figurative sides. By interweaving written words, made from an \"Allah\", a \"Muhammad\", a \"[[Basmala|Bismillah]]\", etc., or using [[micrography]],<ref name = \"bnf\">[http://expositions.bnf.fr/parole/grand/134.htm BNF - Torah, Bible, Coran]. In French.</ref> calligraphers produced anthropomorphic figures ([['Ali]], the Ideal Human of [[Sufi|mystics]], a praying man,<ref name=Praying>{{cite web|title=Praying Man|url=http://www.ethiopianmuslims.net/Images/calligraphy2.jpg|publisher=Ethiopian Muslims Network|accessdate=29 December 2012|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081217032258/http://www.ethiopianmuslims.net/Images/calligraphy2.jpg|archivedate=2008-12-17}}</ref> a face), zoomorphisms (symbolic creatures, most from the Shi'a iconography, like the lion (Ali \"the Lion of God\")<ref name = \"Cartage\">[http://www.cartage.org.lb/en/themes/GeogHist/histories/Oldcivilization/Egyptology/Calligraphy/art5.jpg Lion of 'Ali].</ref> horse ([['Ali]]'s [[Duldul (mule)|Duldul]]),<ref name = \"Levha\">[http://www.levha.net/calligraphy/calligraphy_index.html Horse of 'Ali].</ref> fish,<ref name = \"bnf\" /> stork or other bird (the qur'anic [[Hudhud]])<ref name = \"IslArch\">[https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20060625045753/http://www.islamicarchitecture.org/art/images/calligraphy/islamic.calligraphy.birdtext.101.gif HudHud].{{Dead link|date=June 2009}}</ref><ref name = \"UCSC\">[http://www.ucsc.edu/currents/01-02/art/islamic_bird.jpg Islamic Bird], ''UC Santa Cruz Currents Online''.</ref>) and inanimate representations (a sword ([[Zulfiqar|Dhu al-Fiqar]]), a mosque, a ship (made from the letter ''[[Waw (letter)|waw]]'', a symbol of mystical union, literally meaning \"and,\" in Arabic)). Calligrams are related to Muslim mysticism and popular with many leading calligraphers in [[Turkey]], [[Persian Empire|Persia]] and [[India]] from the 17th century onward.  Although striking in appearance, calligrams have never been regarded as appropriate or a decent expression of the art by the master calligraphers. Many calligrams therefore were produced by either folk calligraphers or for the interest of uncultivated people. These calligrams were not exhibited in mosques or Sufi convents in the Ottoman state, for example.  An element in this perspective is the rejection of the interpretation by the heretic Hurufiyyah Sufi order which sees letters as true manifestations of the fate, events and creation in themselves.  In the teachings of calligraphy, figurative imagery is used to help visualize the shape of letters to trace, for example, the letter ''ha' '' looks in ''nasta'liq'' similar to two eyes, as its Persian name implies: \"he' two eyes\" ''he' do cheshm''). In literature and poetry seeing in letters a reflection of the natural world goes back to the [[Abbasid]] times.  One of the contemporary masters of the calligram genre is [[Hassan Massoudy]] and [[Wissam Shawkat]].  Good commercial examples are the logos of [[Al Jazeera]], an international news station based at [[Qatar]], and the [[Edinburgh Middle East Report]], a Scottish academic journal on the [[Middle East]], and also the work of the calligrapher and designer Wissam Shawkat.-->'''\n\n===Modern ===\nIn the post-colonial era, artists working in North Africa and the Middle East transformed Arabic calligraphy into a modern art movement, known as the ''[[Hurufiyya movement]]''.<ref name=\":0\">Flood, Necipo\u011flu (2017). [https://www.worldcat.org/title/a-companion-to-islamic-art-and-architecture-2-from-the-mongols-to-modernism/oclc/1006377297&referer=brief_results A Companion to Islamic Art and Architecture]. Volume II. Hoboken: John Wiley & Sons. pp. 1294. {{ISBN|1119068665}}. OCLC 1006377297.</ref> Artists working in this style use calligraphy as a graphic element within contemporary artwork.<ref>Mavrakis, N., [https://mjmes.wordpress.com/2013/03/08/article-5/ \"The Hurufiyah Art Movement in Middle Eastern Art\"], ''McGill Journal of Middle Eastern Studies Blog''</ref><ref>A. and Masters, C., ''A-Z Great Modern Artists'', Hachette UK, 2015, p. 56</ref>\n\nThe term, ''hurufiyya'' is derived from the Arabic term, ''harf'' for letter. Traditionally, the term was charged with Sufi intellectual and esoteric meaning.<ref name=\":0\" /> It is an explicit reference to a medieval system of teaching involving [[political theology]] and lettrism. In this theology, letters were seen as primordial signifiers and manipulators of the cosmos.'''<ref>Mir-Kasimov, O., ''Words of Power: Hurufi Teachings Between Shi'ism and Sufism in Medieval Islam,'' I.B. Tauris and the Institute of Ismaili Studies, 2015</ref>'''\n\nHurufiyya artists blended Western art concepts with an artistic identity and sensibility drawn from their own culture and heritage. These artists integrated Islamic visual traditions, especially calligraphy, and elements of modern art into syncretic contemporary compositions.<ref>Lindgren, A. and Ross, S., ''The Modernist World,'' Routledge, 2015, p. 495; Mavrakis, N., \"The Hurufiyah Art Movement in Middle Eastern Art,\" ''McGill Journal of Middle Eastern Studies Blog,'' Online: https://mjmes.wordpress.com/2013/03/08/article-5/; Tuohy, A. and Masters, C., ''A-Z Great Modern Artists,'' Hachette UK, 2015, p. 56</ref> Although hurufiyyah artists struggled to find their own individual dialogue within the context of nationalism, they also worked towards an aesthetic that transcended national boundaries and represented a broader affiliation with an Islamic identity.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe hurufiyya artistic style as a movement most likely began in North Africa around 1955 with the work of [[Ibrahim el-Salahi]].<ref name=\":0\" /> However, the use of calligraphy in modern artworks appears to have emerged independently in various Islamic states. Artists working in this were often unaware of other hurufiyya artists's works, allowing for different manifestations of the style to emerge in different regions.<ref>Dadi. I., \"Ibrahim El Salahi and Calligraphic Modernism in a Comparative Perspective,\" ''South Atlantic Quarterly,'' 109 (3), 2010 pp 555-576, DOI:https://doi.org/10.1215/00382876-2010-006; Flood, F.B. and Necipoglu, G. (eds) ''A Companion to Islamic Art and Architecture,'' Wiley, 2017, p. 1294</ref> In Sudan, for instance, artworks include both Islamic calligraphy and West African motifs.<ref>Flood, Necipo\u011flu (2017). [https://www.worldcat.org/title/a-companion-to-islamic-art-and-architecture-2-from-the-mongols-to-modernism/oclc/1006377297&referer=brief_results A Companion to Islamic Art and Architecture]. Volume II. Hoboken: John Wiley & Sons. pp. 1298-1299. {{ISBN|1119068665}}. OCLC 1006377297.</ref>\n\n[[File:Roof of Frere Hall.JPG|thumb|The Roof of [[Frere Hall]], Karachi, Pakistan, c. 1986. Mural by artist, [[Sadequain|Sadequain Naqqash]] integrates calligraphy elements into a modern artwork]]\n\nThe hurufiyya art movement was not confined to painters and included artists working in a variety of media.<ref>Mavrakis, N., \"The Hurufiyah Art Movement in Middle Eastern Art,\" ''McGill Journal of Middle Eastern Studies Blog,'' Online: https://mjmes.wordpress.com/2013/03/08/article-5/;Tuohy {{cite web |url=https://mjmes.wordpress.com/2013/03/08/article-5/;Tuohy |title=Unknown |access-date=25 March 2020}}{{dead link|date=March 2020|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}, A. and Masters, C., ''A-Z Great Modern Artists,'' Hachette UK, 2015, p. 56; Dadi. I., \"Ibrahim El Salahi and Calligraphic Modernism in a Comparative Perspective,\" ''South Atlantic Quarterly,'' 109 (3), 2010 pp 555-576, DOI:https://doi.org/10.1215/00382876-2010-006</ref> One example is the Jordanian ceramicist, [[Mahmoud Taha]] who combined the traditional aesthetics of calligraphy with skilled craftsmanship.<ref>Asfour. M., \"A Window on Contemporary Arab Art,\" NABAD Art Gallery, Online: http://www.nabadartgallery.com/</ref> Although not affiliated with the hurufiyya movement, the contemporary artist [[Shirin Neshat]] integrates Arabic text into her black-and-white photography, creating contrast and duality. In Iraq, the movement was known as ''Al Bu'd al Wahad'' (or the [[One Dimension Group]])\",<ref>\"Shaker Hassan Al Said,\" Darat al Funum, Online: www.daratalfunun.org/main/activit/curentl/anniv/exhib3.html;  Flood, Necipo\u011flu (2017). [https://www.worldcat.org/title/a-companion-to-islamic-art-and-architecture-2-from-the-mongols-to-modernism/oclc/1006377297&referer=brief_results A Companion to Islamic Art and Architecture]. Volume II. Hoboken: John Wiley & Sons. pp. 1294. {{ISBN|1119068665}}. OCLC 1006377297.</ref> and in Iran, it was known as the [[Iranian modern and contemporary art#Saqqakhaneh movement|Saqqa-Khaneh movement]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nWestern art has influenced Arabic calligraphy in other ways, with forms such as [[calligraffiti]], which is the use of calligraphy in public art to make politico-social messages or to ornament public buildings and spaces.<ref>Grebenstein, M., ''Calligraphy Bible: A Complete Guide to More Than 100 Essential Projects and Techniques,'' 2012, p. 5</ref> Notable Islamic calligraffiti artists include: [[Yazan Halwani]] active in Lebanon'''<ref>Alabaster, Olivia. [http://www.dailystar.com.lb/Culture/Lifestyle/2013/Feb-09/205688-i-like-to-write-beirut-as-its-the-city-that-gave-us-everything.ashx#axzz3DCxf8Utr; \"I like to write Beirut as it\u2019s the city that gave us everything\"], ''[[The Daily Star (Lebanon)|The Daily Star]]'', Beirut, 09 February 2013</ref>''', [[EL Seed|el Seed]] working in France and Tunisia, and Caiand [[A1one]] in Tehran.<ref>{{cite news|last=Vandalog|title=A1one in Tehran IRAN|url=http://blog.vandalog.com/2011/05/from-a1one-in-tehran-iran/|accessdate=8 October 2012|newspaper=Vandalog|date=3 May 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n===Kufic===\n<gallery>\nImage:Qur'an folio 11th century kufic.jpg|Kufic script in an 11th-century Qur'an\nFile:Folio Blue Quran Met 2004.88.jpg|[[Maghrebi script|Maghrebi Kufic]] script in the 9th or 10th century [[Blue Qur'an|Blue Quran]]\nFile:Jame mosque yazd tilework.jpg|Square kufic tilework in Yazd, Iran\nFile:Cup votive inscriptions MET 40-170-15.jpg|Under-glaze terracotta bowl from the 11th century [[Nishapur]]\nFile:Hamdanid gold dinar, Nasir al-Dawla and Sayf al-Dawla.jpg|[[Gold dinar]] from 10th century Syria\nImage:An example of Kufic Calligraphy.jpg|A Kufic calligraphy in [[Chota Imambara]]\n</gallery>\n\n===Naskh===\n<gallery>\nImage:Qur'anic Manuscript - Mid to Late 15th Century, Turkey.jpg|Muhaqqaq script in a 15th-century Qur'an from Turkey.\nFile:Qur'an manuscript Surat al-Nisa'. (1).tif|Muhaqqaq script in a 13th-century Qur'an.\nFile:Muhammad ibn Pir Ahmad al-shahir bi-Ibn Arghun al-Shirazi - Text Page with Dedication to the Ottoman Sultan Selim I - Walters W5912A - Full Page.jpg|Naskh script in an early 16th-century Ottoman manuscript dedicated to [[Selim I]].\nFile:Ijazah3.jpg|Diploma of competency in calligraphy, written with thuluth and naskh script.\nFile:Mausol\u00e9e de Touman Aka (Shah-i-Zinda, Samarcande) (6009410911).jpg|Thuluth script tile in [[Samarkand]].\nImage:Kalligr\u00e1fia Hagia Sophia.jpg|Calligraphy of Ali decorating [[Hagia Sophia]].\n</gallery>\n\n===Regional varieties===\n<gallery>\nImage:Ta'liq Script.jpg|Ta'liq script in an Ottoman manuscript.\nImage:Brooklyn Museum - Sample of Calligraphy in Persian Nasta'liq Script.jpg|Nasta'liq Script.\nImage:Nastaliq-proportions.jpg|Proportions of the nasta'liq script.\nFile:Qur'anic Manuscript - Sini script.jpg|Sini script in an 11th-century Qur'an.\nFile:Chinese quran.jpg|Chinese Qur'an written in Sini with Chinese translation.\nImage:The Islamic calligraphy.jpg|The Word \"Allah\" written in the Form of [[Columbidae|Pigeon]] in [[Chota Imambara]]\n</gallery>\n\n===Modern examples===\n<gallery>\nFile:Bismillah.JPG|[[Bismallah]] calligraphy.\nFile:Muhammad calligraphy.svg|[[Muhammad]] calligraphy\nFile:Bismillah.svg|[[Bismallah]] calligraphy.\n\nFile:Caligrafia arabe pajaro.svg|An example of [[zoomorphic]] calligraphy.\nFile:Flag of Taliban.svg|flag of the [[Islamic Emirate of Afghanistan]] 2001.\nFile:Al jazeera Calligraphy Animation.gif|Animation showing the calligraphic composition of the [[Al Jazeera]] logo.\nFile:Emirates logo.svg|The Emirates logo is written in traditional Arabic calligraphy.\n\nFile:Learning Arabic calligraphy.jpg|The instruments and work of a student calligrapher.\nFile:Menulis khat.jpg|Islamic calligraphy performed by a Malay Muslim in Malaysia. Calligrapher is making a rough draft.\n</gallery>\n\n==List of calligraphers==\nSome classical calligraphers:\n;Medieval\n*[[Ibn Muqla]] (d. 939/940)\n*[[Ibn al-Bawwab]] (d. 1022)\n*[[Fakhr-un-Nisa]] (12th century)\n*[[Yaqut al-Musta'simi]] (d. 1298)\n*[[Mir Ali Tabrizi]] (d. 14th\u201315th century)\n;\n;Ottoman era {{anchor|Ottoman-era calligraphers}}\n\n*[[Sheikh Hamdullah|Shaykh Hamdullah]] (1436\u20131520)\n*[[Hamid Ayta\u00e7]] (1891-1982)\n*[[Seyyid Kasim Gubari]] (d. 1624)\n*[[H\u00e2fiz Osman]] (1642\u20131698)\n*[[Mustafa R\u00e2kim]] (1757\u20131826)\n*[[Mehmed Shevki Efendi]] (1829\u20131887)\n;{{See|List of Ottoman calligraphers}}\n;Contemporary\n\n* [[Ali Adjalli]] (b. 1939), Iran\n* [[Wijdan Ali]] (b. 1939),  Jordan\n* [[Hashem Muhammad al-Baghdadi]] in Iraq \n* [[Hamid Ayta\u00e7]]\n* [[Mohammad Hosni]] Syria\n* [[Shakir Hassan Al Said|Shakkir Hassan Al Sa'id]] (1925-2004) in Iraq\n* [[Madiha Omar]] Iraqi-American\n* [[Sadequain|Sadequain Naqqash]] (1930-1987), Pakistan\n* [[Ibrahim el-Salahi]] (b. 1930), Sudan\n* [[Mahmoud Taha]] (b. 1942), Jordan\n* [[Hossein Zenderoudi|Charles Hossein Zenderoudi]] (b. 1937), Iran\n* [[Abdulraouf Baydoun]] (b. 1956), Syria\n*[[Mohamed Zakariya]] (b. 1942), United States of America\n* [[Hassan Massoudy]] (b. 1944), Irak France\n*[https://www.facebook.com/amirkamalcalligraphy Amir Kamal] (b. 1972), Pakistan\n\n==See also==\n* [[Illuminated manuscript]]\n* [[Islamic architecture]]\n* [[Islamic Golden Age]]\n* [[Islamic graffiti]]\n* [[Islamic miniature]]\n* [[Islamic pottery]]\n* [[Museum of Turkish Calligraphy Art]]\n* [[Ottoman Turkish language]]\n* [[Persian calligraphy]]\n* [[Sini (script)]]\n* [[Uthman Taha]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Sister project links| wikt=no | commons=Category:Islamic calligraphy | b=no | n=no | q=Islamic calligraphy | s=no | v=no | voy=no | species=no | d=no}}\n\n* [http://www.themuslimculture.com/islamic-calligraphy-of-quran-verses-and-other-terms/ Islamic Calligraphy Pictures]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110228232705/http://www.mastersofistanbul.com/en/ustalar/2/calligraphy mastersofistanbul.com]\n* [https://baradariarts.com/ baradariarts.com]\n* [http://www.pbase.com/dosseman/calligraphy Gallery with lots of calligraphy in Turkish mosque]\n*[https://www.reed.edu/persian-calligraphy/en/index.html Anthology of Persian calligraphers from 10th to 20th centuries]\n{{Islamic calligraphy}}\n{{Islamic art}}\n{{Islamic architecture}}\n{{Islamic studies}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}}\n\n[[Category:Islamic calligraphy| ]]\n[[Category:Islamic art]]\n[[Category:Islamic culture]]\n[[Category:Islamic architectural elements]]\n[[Category:Ottoman culture]]\n[[Category:Islamic arts of the book]]\n[[Category:Islamic illuminated manuscripts]]\n", "name_user": "Munfarid1", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Islamic_calligraphy"}
{"title_page": "The Veldt (short story)", "text_new": "{{Infobox short story | <!-- See [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Novels]] or [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Books]] -->\n| name          = The Veldt\n| title_orig    = \n| translator    = \n| author        = [[Ray Bradbury]]\n| country       = [[United States]]\n| language      = [[English language|English]]\n| series        = \n| genre         = [[Science fiction]] \n| published_in  = ''[[The Saturday Evening Post]]''\n| publication_type = [[Periodical]]\n| publisher     = \n| media_type    = Print ([[magazine]])\n| pub_date      = September 23, 1950\n| english_pub_date = \n| preceded_by   = \n| followed_by   = \n}}\n\n{{external media | width = 210px | align = right | headerimage= | audio1 = [https://www.sciencehistory.org/distillations/podcast/sci-fi-radio-drama \u201cSci-Fi Radio Drama\u201d (performance of ''The Veldt'')], ''Distillations'' Podcast, [[Science History Institute]]}}\n\n\"'''The Veldt'''\" is a [[science fiction]] [[short story]]  by American author [[Ray Bradbury]]. Originally appearing as \"'''The World the Children Made'''\" in the September 23, 1950 issue of ''[[The Saturday Evening Post]]'', it was republished under its current name in the 1951 anthology ''[[The Illustrated Man]]''.\n\nIn the story, a mother and father struggle with their technologically advanced home taking over their role as parents, and their children becoming uncooperative as a result of their lack of discipline.\n\n==Plot summary==\n{{Original research|section|date=September 2018}}\nThe Hadley family lives in an automated house called \"The Happylife Home\", filled with machines that aid them in completing everyday tasks, such as tying their shoes, bathing themselves, or even cooking their food. The two children, Peter and Wendy,{{efn|Their names pay homage to [[Peter Pan]] and [[Wendy Darling]].<ref>{{Cite book|title = Ray Bradbury|url = https://books.google.com/books?id=htV4XatIrAUC|publisher = Infobase Publishing|date = 2010-01-01|isbn = 9781438131092|language = en|quote = The correspondence between the names of James Barrie's memorable characters in Peter Pan and those of Bradbury's children cannot be coincidental. In both works of fiction, Wendy and Peter are devotees of never-never land, a dimension that is beyond the constraints and conventions imposed on demanding, if not persecuting, adults, and which is outside the limitations and changes decreed by time. In \"The Veldt\", Wendy and Peter go beyond the point of no return. The vengeance they wreak on their parents leaves them unaffected and undisturbed. Afterward, when David McClean, a psychologist and family friend, finds them nonchalantly and cheerfully picnicking in the savage setting they have stimulated, they show no signs of remorse or guilt. They are unholy terrors for whom expediency and self-preservation are the sole dictates of behavior. Like the baby in the next story, they are amoral and conscience-free.|editor-last = Bloom|editor-first = Harold|last = Diskin|first = Lahna}}</ref>}} become fascinated with the \"nursery\", a [[virtual reality]] room able to reproduce any place they imagine.\n\nThe parents, George and Lydia, begin to wonder if there is something wrong with their way of life. Lydia tells George, \"That's just it. I feel like I don\u2019t belong here. The house is wife and mother now, and nursemaid. Can I compete with an African [[veld]]t? Can I give a bath and scrub the children as efficiently or quickly as the automatic scrub bath can? I cannot.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Boyd|first=Jason|title=The World the Veldt Made|url=http://nerdclave.com/home/world-veldt-made/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304200734/http://nerdclave.com/home/world-veldt-made/|url-status=dead|archive-date=2016-03-04|work=The Nerdclave|accessdate=2014-05-17}}</ref> They are also perplexed and confused that the nursery is stuck on an [[Africa]]n setting, with lions in the distance, eating a dead figure. There they also find recreations of their personal belongings and hear strangely familiar screams. Wondering why their children are so concerned with this scene of death, they decide to call a [[psychologist]].\n\nThe psychologist, David McClean, suggests they turn off the house, move to the country, and learn to be more self-sufficient. The children, reliant on the nursery, beg their parents to let them have one last visit, who give in and allow Peter and Wendy more time in the nursery. When the parents come to fetch them, the children lock George and Lydia into the nursery with the pride of lions. Shortly after, David comes by to look for George and Lydia. He finds the children enjoying lunch in the nursery and sees the lions eating figures in the distance, which are implied to be George and Lydia.\n\n==Adaptations==\n{{Refimprove section|date=December 2017}}\nThe story was adapted by [[Ernest Kinoy]] as an episode of the radio program ''[[Dimension X (radio program)|Dimension X]]'' in 1951.  The same script was used in a 1955 episode of ''[[X Minus One]]'', with the addition of a frame story in which it was explained that George and Lydia were not really slain and that the entire family was now undergoing psychiatric treatment.\n\nAn adaptation by [[Jack Pulman]] was broadcast on the [[BBC Light Programme]] on March 5, 1959, with [[John Cazabon]] and [[Diana Olsson]]. <ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/m000fh8j</ref>\n\n\"The Veldt\" was adapted for the cinema as part of ''[[The Illustrated Man (film)|The Illustrated Man]]'' (1969).\n\n\"The Veldt\" was adapted into a stage production by Bradbury and can be found in a volume titled ''The Wonderful Ice Cream Suit & Other Plays'' in 1972.\n\nA short film adaptation of \"The Veldt\" was produced by BFA Educational Media in 1974.\n\nIn 1983, Swedish Television premiered a TV movie based on \"The Veldt,\" under the title ''Savannen'' (\"The Savannah\"), with [[Bibi Andersson]] in the role of Lydia, and [[Erland Josephson]] playing David.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0169210/|title=Savannen (1983)|publisher=IMDb.com|accessdate=2013-10-05}}</ref>\n\nIn 1984, Michael McDonough of Brigham Young University produced \"The Veldt\" as an episode of ''Bradbury 13'', a series of thirteen audio adaptations of famous Ray Bradbury stories, in conjunction with National Public Radio.\n\nIn 1987, a film titled ''[[The Veldt (film)|The Veldt]]'' was made in the USSR (directed by Nazim Tulyakhojaev), where several of Bradbury's stories were intertwined.  It was billed as the \"First Soviet Horror Movie.\"\n\nThe Canadian-produced anthology television series ''[[The Ray Bradbury Theater]]'' included the story, scripted by Bradbury, as Episode #29 (Season 3, Episode 11).  It was the first broadcast on November 10, 1989, and starred [[Linda Kelsey]], Malcolm Stewart, Shana Alexander, and Thomas Peacocke.\n\nThe BBC produced another radio play version of \"The Veldt\", adapted from the stage play by [[Mike Walker (radio dramatist)|Mike Walker]], in 2007, which was broadcast on [[BBC Radio 4]].<ref>https://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/1c3bec2da4114e28b128e8d5daaf300b</ref>\n\nIn 2010, [[Stephen Colbert]] read \"The Veldt\" for the [[NPR]] radio program ''[[Selected Shorts]]'' before a live audience at [[Symphony Space]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KSoigRHHNLM |title=Stephen Colbert reading 'The Veldt' by Ray Bradbury (Part 1 of 3) |publisher=YouTube |accessdate=2013-10-05 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131011093633/http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KSoigRHHNLM |archivedate=2013-10-11 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, shortly before author Ray Bradbury's death, Canadian musician [[deadmau5]] produced a song titled \"[[The Veldt (song)|The Veldt]]\", including lyrics by Chris James based upon the story.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uiUAq4aVTjY |title=deadmau5 feat. Chris James - The Veldt |publisher=YouTube |date=2012-04-20 |accessdate=2013-10-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=l8M0TK5Vo1w&feature=g-u-u |title=deadmau5 ft. Chris James - The Veldt (Radio Edit) |publisher=YouTube |date= |accessdate=2013-10-05}}</ref> The music video, released after Bradbury's death, is dedicated to him and shows a young boy and girl wandering through an African veldt and witnessing several plot points from the story, including vultures, and a lion eating an unseen carcass. It is illustrated in a similar fashion to that of the video game ''[[Limbo (game)|Limbo]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_esYONwdKuw&hd=1 |title=deadmau5 feat. Chris James - The Veldt (Music Video) |publisher=YouTube |date=2012-06-25 |accessdate=2013-10-05}}</ref>{{original research inline|date=December 2017}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Children's literature}}\n*[[Holodeck]], from the ''[[Star Trek]]'' universe\n*[[Simulated reality]]\n*[[Simulated reality in fiction]]\n*''[[Smart House (film)|Smart House]]'', a film loosely based on ''The Veldt''\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{isfdb title|64827|The Veldt}}\n* [http://www.raybradbury.com/ Ray Bradbury\u2019s official website]\n* [http://bestsciencefictionstories.com/2008/02/21/the-veldt-by-ray-bradbury/ A short review of the story with resources for finding it]\n\n{{Ray Bradbury|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Veldt, The}}\n[[Category:1950 short stories]]\n[[Category:Science fiction short stories]]\n[[Category:Short stories by Ray Bradbury]]\n[[Category:Works originally published in The Saturday Evening Post]]\n[[Category:Short stories adapted into films]]\n[[Category:Virtual reality in fiction]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox short story | <!-- See [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Novels]] or [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Books]] -->\n| name          = The Veldt\n| title_orig    = \n| translator    = \n| author        = [[Ray Bradbury]]\n| country       = [[United States]]\n| language      = [[English language|English]]\n| series        = \n| genre         = [[Science fiction]] \n| published_in  = ''[[The Saturday Evening Post]]''\n| publication_type = [[Periodical]]\n| publisher     = \n| media_type    = Print ([[magazine]])\n| pub_date      = September 23, 1950\n| english_pub_date = \n| preceded_by   = \n| followed_by   = \n}}\n\n{{external media | width = 210px | align = right | headerimage= | audio1 = [https://www.sciencehistory.org/distillations/podcast/sci-fi-radio-drama \u201cSci-Fi Radio Drama\u201d (performance of ''The Veldt'')], ''Distillations'' Podcast, [[Science History Institute]]}}\n\n\"'''The Veldt'''\" is a [[science fiction]] [[short story]]  by American author [[Ray Bradbury]]. Originally appearing as \"'''The World the Children Made'''\" in the September 23, 1950 issue of ''[[The Saturday Evening Post]]'', it was republished under its current name in the 1951 anthology ''[[The Illustrated Man]]''.\n\nIn the story, a mother and father struggle with their technologically advanced home taking over their role as parents, and their children becoming uncooperative as a result of their lack of discipline.\n\n==Plot summary==\n{{Original research|section|date=September 2018}}\nThe Hadley family lives in an automated house called \"The Happylife Home\", filled with machines that aid them in completing everyday tasks, such as tying their shoes, bathing themselves, or even cooking their food. The two children, Peter and Wendy,{{efn|Their names pay homage to [[Peter Pan]] and [[Wendy Darling]].<ref>{{Cite book|title = Ray Bradbury|url = https://books.google.com/books?id=htV4XatIrAUC|publisher = Infobase Publishing|date = 2010-01-01|isbn = 9781438131092|language = en|quote = The correspondence between the names of James Barrie's memorable characters in Peter Pan and those of Bradbury's children cannot be coincidental. In both works of fiction, Wendy and Peter are devotees of never-never land, a dimension that is beyond the constraints and conventions imposed on demanding, if not persecuting, adults, and which is outside the limitations and changes decreed by time. In \"The Veldt\", Wendy and Peter go beyond the point of no return. The vengeance they wreak on their parents leaves them unaffected and undisturbed. Afterward, when David McClean, a psychologist and family friend, finds them nonchalantly and cheerfully picnicking in the savage setting they have stimulated, they show no signs of remorse or guilt. They are unholy terrors for whom expediency and self-preservation are the sole dictates of behavior. Like the baby in the next story, they are amoral and conscience-free.|editor-last = Bloom|editor-first = Harold|last = Diskin|first = Lahna}}</ref>}} become fascinated with the \"nursery\", a [[virtual reality]] room able to reproduce any place they imagine.\n\nThe parents, George and Lydia, begin to wonder if there is something wrong with their way of life. Lydia tells George, \"That's just it. I feel like I don\u2019t belong here. The house is wife and mother now, and nursemaid. Can I compete with an African [[veld]]t? Can I give a bath and scrub the children as efficiently or quickly as the automatic scrub bath can? I cannot.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Boyd|first=Jason|title=The World the Veldt Made|url=http://nerdclave.com/home/world-veldt-made/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304200734/http://nerdclave.com/home/world-veldt-made/|url-status=dead|archive-date=2016-03-04|work=The Nerdclave|accessdate=2014-05-17}}</ref> They are also perplexed and confused that the nursery is stuck on an [[Africa]]n setting, with lions in the distance, eating a dead figure. There they also find recreations of their personal belongings and hear strangely familiar screams. Wondering why their children are so concerned with this scene of death, they decide to call a [[psychologist]].\n\nThe psychologist, David McClean, suggests they turn off the house, move to the country, and learn to be more self-sufficient. The children, reliant on the nursery, beg their parents to let them have one last visit, who give in and allow Peter and Wendy more time in the nursery. When the parents come to fetch them, the children lock George and Lydia into the nursery with the pride of lions. Shortly after, David comes by to look for George and Lydia. He finds the children enjoying lunch in the nursery and sees the lions eating figures in the distance, which are implied to be George and Lydia.\n\n==Adaptations==\n{{Refimprove section|date=December 2017}}\nThe story was adapted by [[Ernest Kinoy]] as an episode  of the radio program ''[[Dimension X (radio program)|Dimension X]]'' in 1951.  The same script was used in a 1955 episode of ''[[X Minus One]]'', with the addition of a frame story in which it was explained that George and Lydia were not really slain, and that the entire family was now undergoing psychiatric treatment.\n\nAn adaptation by [[Jack Pulman]] was broadcast on the [[BBC Light Programme]] on March 5, 1959, with [[John Cazabon]] and [[Diana Olsson]].<ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/m000fh8j</ref>\n\n\"The Veldt\" was adapted for the cinema as part of ''[[The Illustrated Man (film)|The Illustrated Man]]'' (1969).\n\n\"The Veldt\" was adapted into a stage production by Bradbury and can be found in a volume titled ''The Wonderful Ice Cream Suit & Other Plays'' in 1972.\n\nA short film adaptation of \"The Veldt\" was produced by BFA Educational Media in 1974.\n\nIn 1983, Swedish Television premiered a TV movie based on \"The Veldt,\" under the title ''Savannen'' (\"The Savannah\"), with [[Bibi Andersson]] in the role of Lydia, and [[Erland Josephson]] playing David.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0169210/|title=Savannen (1983)|publisher=IMDb.com|accessdate=2013-10-05}}</ref>\n\nIn 1984, Michael McDonough of Brigham Young University produced \"The Veldt\" as an episode of ''Bradbury 13'', a series of thirteen audio adaptations of famous Ray Bradbury stories, in conjunction with National Public Radio.\n\nIn 1987, a film titled ''[[The Veldt (film)|The Veldt]]'' was made in the USSR (directed by Nazim Tulyakhojaev), where several of Bradbury's stories were intertwined.  It was billed as the \"First Soviet Horror Movie.\"\n\nThe Canadian-produced anthology television series ''[[The Ray Bradbury Theater]]'' included the story, scripted by Bradbury, as Episode #29 (Season 3, Episode 11).  It was first broadcast November 10, 1989, and starred [[Linda Kelsey]], Malcolm Stewart, Shana Alexander, and Thomas Peacocke.\n\nThe BBC produced another radio play version of \"The Veldt\", adapted from the stage play by [[Mike Walker (radio dramatist)|Mike Walker]], in 2007, which was broadcast on [[BBC Radio 4]].<ref>https://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/1c3bec2da4114e28b128e8d5daaf300b</ref>\n\nIn 2010, [[Stephen Colbert]] read \"The Veldt\" for the [[NPR]] radio program ''[[Selected Shorts]]'' before a live audience at [[Symphony Space]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KSoigRHHNLM |title=Stephen Colbert reading 'The Veldt' by Ray Bradbury (Part 1 of 3) |publisher=YouTube |accessdate=2013-10-05 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131011093633/http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KSoigRHHNLM |archivedate=2013-10-11 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, shortly before author Ray Bradbury's death, Canadian musician [[deadmau5]] produced a song titled \"[[The Veldt (song)|The Veldt]]\", including lyrics by Chris James based upon the story.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uiUAq4aVTjY |title=deadmau5 feat. Chris James - The Veldt |publisher=YouTube |date=2012-04-20 |accessdate=2013-10-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=l8M0TK5Vo1w&feature=g-u-u |title=deadmau5 ft. Chris James - The Veldt (Radio Edit) |publisher=YouTube |date= |accessdate=2013-10-05}}</ref> The music video, released after Bradbury's death, is dedicated to him and shows a young boy and girl wandering through an African veldt and witnessing several plot points from the story, including vultures, and a lion eating an unseen carcass. It is illustrated in a similar fashion to that of the video game ''[[Limbo (game)|Limbo]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_esYONwdKuw&hd=1 |title=deadmau5 feat. Chris James - The Veldt (Music Video) |publisher=YouTube |date=2012-06-25 |accessdate=2013-10-05}}</ref>{{original research inline|date=December 2017}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Children's literature}}\n*[[Holodeck]], from the ''[[Star Trek]]'' universe\n*[[Simulated reality]]\n*[[Simulated reality in fiction]]\n*''[[Smart House (film)|Smart House]]'', a film loosely based on ''The Veldt''\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{isfdb title|64827|The Veldt}}\n* [http://www.raybradbury.com/ Ray Bradbury\u2019s official website]\n* [http://bestsciencefictionstories.com/2008/02/21/the-veldt-by-ray-bradbury/ A short review of the story with resources for finding it]\n\n{{Ray Bradbury|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Veldt, The}}\n[[Category:1950 short stories]]\n[[Category:Science fiction short stories]]\n[[Category:Short stories by Ray Bradbury]]\n[[Category:Works originally published in The Saturday Evening Post]]\n[[Category:Short stories adapted into films]]\n[[Category:Virtual reality in fiction]]\n", "name_user": "24.188.52.255", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eAdaptations)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Veldt_(short_story)"}
{"title_page": "LP (singer)", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2015}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = LP\n| background       = solo_singer\n| image            = LP WTMD LHCollins sms 06062014.jpg\n| caption          = LP performing at [[WTMD]]'s [[WTMD#First Thursday Concerts in the Park|First Thursday series]] in [[Canton, Baltimore]], [[Maryland]], in June 2014\n| birth_name       = Laura Pergolizzi\n| alias            = LP\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1981|3|18|df=y}}\n| birth_place      = [[Long Island]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S.\n| origin           = Long Island, New York, U.S.\n| genre            = {{flat list|\n*[[Indie rock]]\n*[[Rock music|pop rock]]\n*[[indie pop]]\n*[[alternative rock]] \n}}\n| occupation       = Singer-songwriter\n| instrument       = {{flat list|\n*[[Vocals]]\n*[[guitar]]\n*[[ukulele]]\n*[[harmonica]]\n}}\n| years_active     = 1998\u2013present\n| label            = [[Warner Bros. Records]]\n| associated_acts  = \n| website          = {{URL|iamlp.com}}\n| current_members  = \n| past_members     = \n}}\n\n'''Laura Pergolizzi''' (born March 18, 1981), known professionally as '''LP''', is an American singer and songwriter, best known for her single \"[[Lost on You]]\". She has released five albums and three [[extended plays|EPs]]. She has written songs for other artists including [[Cher]], [[Rihanna]], the [[Backstreet Boys]], [[Leona Lewis]], [[Myl\u00e8ne Farmer]], [[C\u00e9line Dion]] and [[Christina Aguilera]].<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop-shop/6106473/lp-forever-for-now-laura-pergolizzi |title=LP focuses on LP with First Album in a Decade |date=June 3, 2014 |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |last=Graff |first=Gary}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n===Early life and career===\nLaura Pergolizzi was born in 1981 on [[Long Island]],<ref name=\"iamlp bio\">{{cite web|url=https://iamlp.blog/bio/ |title=Bio |work=LP Blog Official|access-date=July 13, 2019}}</ref> to an [[Italians|Italian]] father and an [[Irish people|Irish]] mother, her paternal grandfather coming from [[Naples]] and grandmother from [[Palermo]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lastampa.it/2016/12/06/spettacoli/musica/nata-dai-locali-di-new-york-mi-nutro-di-pop-senza-confini-0kZU2XyphCkTAHxGs4w4lK/pagina.html |title=\"Nata dai locali di New York mi nutro di pop senza confini\" - La Stampa |website=Lastampa.it |date= |access-date=June 14, 2017}}</ref> Pergolizzi adopted the stage name \"LP\" after moving to [[New York City]].<ref name=\"thefreelibrary\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Not+a+tomboy+in+a+dress%3A+after+walking+away+from+a+contract+at+Island...-a0189051454 | title=Not a tomboy in a dress: after walking away from a contract at Island Records, lesbian rocker LP returns to her androgynous roots with her anticipated third album. |access-date=July 14, 2013 |publisher=thefreelibrary.com}}</ref> [[David Lowery (musician)|David Lowery]] of the band [[Cracker (band)|Cracker]] saw LP performing and featured her on \"Cinderella\", a hidden track on the band's 1998 album, ''[[Gentleman's Blues]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=News |url=http://www.lprock.com/news.html |publisher=lprock.com |access-date=November 15, 2013}}</ref> Lowery followed up by producing LP's debut album, ''[[Heart-Shaped Scar]]'', released in 2001 through [[Koch Records]].\n\nLP's second album, ''Suburban Sprawl & Alcohol'', was released in June 2004 through Lightswitch Records. On the record, she collaborated with songwriter and music producer [[Linda Perry]].<ref name=\"thefreelibrary\" /> However, in spite of extensive touring to promote the release and positive reviews from music critics, the album failed to gain widespread recognition.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.afterellen.com/archive/ellen/Music/102004/suburbansprawl.html |title=AfterEllen.com - Review of LP's Suburban Sprawl & Alcohol |last=Marti |first=Kris Scott |date=October 27, 2004 |website=afterellen.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070404014424/http://www.afterellen.com/archive/ellen/Music/102004/suburbansprawl.html |archive-date=April 4, 2007 |access-date=April 5, 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===2006\u20132010===\nIn 2006, LP appeared at the music conference [[South by Southwest]] and reportedly sparked a bidding war amongst major music labels, eventually being signed by [[L.A. Reid]] to his [[Island Def Jam Music Group]] record label, part of the [[Universal Music Group]]. However, due to artistic differences LP left the contract. She signed with [[SoBe Entertainment]] in 2007, an independent record label, with the album tracks she had written at the major label.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bio: Who is LP?|url=http://www.lprock.com/bio.html |publisher=lprock.com}}</ref> \"Love Will Keep You Up All Night\", one of the tracks she had written at Island Def Jam Music Group with Billy Mann, was released in late 2007 on the [[Backstreet Boys]] album, ''[[Unbreakable (Backstreet Boys album)|Unbreakable]]''. LP wrote and performed \"Wasted\", from her album ''Suburban Sprawl & Alcohol'', which was the theme song for a television show, ''[[South of Nowhere]]'', on [[The N]], currently known as TeenNick. [[MTV]]'s ''[[The Hills (TV series)|The Hills]]'' also featured LP's song \"Damage Is Done\" in mid-2010, and it was released on [[iTunes]].\n\nDuring 2009, LP started writing songs for other artists, including several songs which ended up on [[Heidi Montag]]'s album, ''[[Superficial (album)|Superficial]]'' (Warner Music).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metroguiltypleasures.com/metro/laura-pergolizzi-on-sexuality-and-the-highs-and-lows-of-the-music-biz/ |title=Laura Pergolizzi Q&A on sexuality and the music biz |last=Harmsworth |first=Andrei |date=April 23, 2017 |website=www.metroguiltypleasures.com |publisher=Guilty Pleasures |access-date=May 4, 2017 |quote=You've also written for an eclectic mix of artists, from Rihanna to Heidi Montag. How did that come about?<br>No offence to Heidi, she's lovely, but I didn't write with her. A few of the songs I had, she just cut.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.idolator.com/7351112/heidi-montag-superficial-defense |title=In Defense Of Heidi Montag's 'Superficial'  |last=Lansky |first=Sam |date=September 28, 2012 |website=www.idolator.com |publisher=[[Idolator (website)|Idolator]] |access-date=May 4, 2017 |quote=Contributors to the album include The Runners (Rihanna, Cher Lloyd), Kool Kojak (Ke$ha, One Direction), Steve Morales (Enrique Iglesias, Celine Dion), Stacy Barthe (Katy Perry, Brandy), Chris Rojas (Pink, Sophie Ellis-Bextor) and Laura Pergolizzi (Christina Aguilera, Rita Ora).}}</ref> LP co-wrote the single, \"[[More Is More]]\", as well as the album tracks, \"Twisted\", \"Hey Boy\" and \"Love It or Leave It\". She also co-wrote other tracks for and with Montag, such as the [[Cathy Dennis]] co-written, \"Look How I'm Doin'\", \"I Do This\" and \"Who's That Girl\". A song LP wrote with [[Alexander Kronlund]], \"Standing Where You Left Me\", was released on [[Erik Hassle]]'s debut UK album, ''[[Pieces (Erik Hassle album)|Pieces]]'' (Roxy/EMI/Universal). LP moved to [[Los Angeles]] in 2010.<ref name=\"cnn\">{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2012/04/24/showbiz/lp-into-the-wild-music/index.html |title=Songwriter LP goes into the wild -- as a singer |last=Gumbrecht |first=Jamie |work=[[CNN]] |date=April 24, 2012 |accessdate=July 14, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===2011\u20132012===\nIn August 2010, it was announced that LP had signed with [[RedOne]]'s record label, [[2101 Records]]. LP landed her first major breakthrough as a songwriter, co-writing [[Rihanna|Rihanna's]] song, \"[[Cheers (Drink to That)]]\", featured on Rihanna's fifth studio album ''[[Loud (Rihanna album)|Loud]]'', released on November 12, 2010, on Def Jam Recordings. \"[[Cheers (Drink to That)|Cheers]]\" features a vocal hook performed by LP (taken from [[Avril Lavigne]]'s \"[[I'm with You (Avril Lavigne song)|I'm with You]]\"). In a 2010 interview with [[MTV News]], Rihanna said: \"I love that song (\"Cheers\"). That is one of my favorite songs on the album. It makes you feel like celebrating. It gives you a great feeling inside like you want to go out and have a drink. ... People can't wait for the weekend.\"<ref name=\"mtv news\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1652434/rihanna-glad-avril-lavigne-appears-on-louds-cheers.jhtml |title=Rihanna Glad Avril Lavigne Appears On Loud's 'Cheers' |last=Vena |first=Jocelyn |publisher=MTV |date=November 17, 2010 |accessdate=July 14, 2013}}</ref> LP's major label songwriting breakthroughs continued, as she co-wrote \"Beautiful People\", performed by [[Christina Aguilera]]. The song is featured on the ''[[Burlesque (soundtrack)|Burlesque: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack]]'' album, which was released on November 22, 2010 through [[RCA Records]].\n\nIn June 2011, LP co-wrote \"[[Afraid to Sleep]]\", which was performed by NBC's ''[[The Voice (TV series)|The Voice]]'' finalist [[Vicci Martinez]] and reached #10 on the iTunes Top Singles Chart. In September 2011, LP signed a deal with [[Warner Bros. Records]]. Shortly after, \"[[Into the Wild (song)|Into the Wild]]\", written and performed by LP, was prominently used in a [[Citibank]] national television advertisement campaign. In April 2012, LP released her first major label album, ''[[Into the Wild: Live at EastWest Studios]]'', a five-song live [[extended play]], and started touring extensively including festivals such as [[SXSW]], [[Bonnaroo]], [[Lollapalooza]], [[Bumbershoot]], [[Tropfest]] as well as [[Tokyo]]'s Sonic Boom and [[London]]'s Hyde Park. In 2012, she became the first female [[Martin Guitar]] ambassador.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iamlp.com/blog/martin-guitar-ambassador |title=Martin Guitar Ambassador |publisher=iamlp.com |date=May 10, 2012 |accessdate=July 14, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130906123851/http://www.iamlp.com/blog/martin-guitar-ambassador |archivedate=September 6, 2013 }}</ref>\n\n===2013\u2013present===\n[[File:LP (singer songwriter) (ZMF 2018) jm76932.jpg|thumb|LP at the [[Zelt-Musik-Festival]] 2018 in [[Freiburg]], [[Germany]]]]\nIn May 2012, LP was featured as the Artist of the Week in ''[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]'' magazine. Over the following two years, she completed the recording of her album that included collaborations with [[Billy Steinberg]], [[Isabella Summers|Isabella \"Machine\" Summers]] (from [[Florence and the Machine]]), [[Josh Alexander]], Claude Kelly, Justyn Pilbrow, Carl Ryden and Rob Kleiner.<ref>[http://www.discogs.com/LP-Forever-For-Now/release/5765341 Listing] of the ''Forever for Now'' album on Discogs.com, (accessed March 7, 2015).</ref> The album was produced by [[Rob Cavallo]], Warner Bros. Records' chairman and producer. On April 1, 2014, it was announced that LP's third full-length studio album would be titled ''[[Forever for Now (LP album)|Forever for Now]]'' and was scheduled to be released on June 3, 2014. The album was promoted by the lead single \"Night Like This\".<ref name=\":0\" /> Following the album, a second single, \"Someday\", was released in June 2014 in Canada.<ref name=\"Someday\"/> On September 16, 2014, a music video for \"Tokyo Sunrise\" officially premiered on ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine's website.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://time.com/3387757/lp-tokyo-sunrise-video-premiere/ |title=Catch a 'Tokyo Sunrise' With LP and Her New Video: Premiere |work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |first=Nolan |last=Feeney |accessdate=September 16, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2015, the song \"Muddy Waters\" was released as the first single from LP's fourth studio album [[Lost on You (album)|''Lost on You'']].<ref name=\"Muddy Waters\"/><ref name=\"Lost on You CoS\"/> In November 2015 one of LP's best known songs, [[Lost on You]] was released to great success.\n\nIn June 2016, the song featured in the violent and emotionally charged closing scene of the season four finale of [[Netflix]]'s original series ''[[Orange Is The New Black]]''. It was also featured in the trailer for the [[NBC]] show ''[[Shades of Blue (TV series)|Shades of Blue]]. \"Muddy Waters\"'' clarifies the ending of season 5 episode 4 of [[Starz]] [[Power (TV series)|Power]], as the layers of uncertainty and drama are revisited. In November, the album's [[Lost on You|eponymous second single]] was released, while LP held a residency at the No Vacancy club.<ref>{{cite web|title = LP's New Tune \"Muddy Waters\" Is a Sultry Prowl of a Song|url = http://noisey.vice.com/blog/premiere-lp-muddy-waters|website = NOISEY|accessdate = December 13, 2015}}</ref> Both songs originate from a collaboration with [[Mike Del Rio]]. An EP<ref name=\"Lost on You CoS\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.interviewmagazine.com/music/lp/#_|title=LP After the Storm|last=Rosenzweig|first=Mathias|date=March 2, 2016|website=Interview Magazine|access-date=April 5, 2016}}</ref> titled ''Death Valley'' was released on June 17, 2016.\n\nThe song \"Hi Ho Nobody Home\" by [[David Baerwald]] featuring LP was used in an episode of [[Mr. Mercedes (TV series)|Mr. Mercedes]].\nIn 2017 she performed the song \"Back Where I Belong\" ([[Otto Knows]] featuring [[Avicii]]) for the episode 5 (second season) of the [[Netflix]]'s  original series ''[[Sense8]]''.\n\nLP duets with [[Myl\u00e8ne Farmer]] on the single ''N'oublie pas'', released on June 22. The single immediately hit number 1 on the French [[iTunes]] chart upon release.<ref>https://instagram.com/p/BkU4lvol8BJ/</ref> The track is the second single from Farmer's upcoming studio album ''D\u00e9sob\u00e9issance''.\n\nOn June 15, 2018, LP announced on her Facebook page that she had been working on a new album.<ref name=\"Facebook 'Girls Go Wild'\">{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/iamLP/videos/490100428128322/|title='Girls Gone Wild' Facebook Post|date=15 August 2018|publisher=[[Facebook]]|access-date=August 18, 2018}}</ref>  A day later, the first track from the record, \"Girls Go Wild\" was released.<ref name=\"Billboard\">{{cite web |last=Bote |first=Joshua |title=LP Announces New Album, Shares New Single 'Girls Go Wild': Watch |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/pride/8470816/lp-new-album-single-girls-go-wild |website=Billboard |access-date=August 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2018 she recorded two songs for the singer [[Morrissey]] for his new album of cover songs.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.morrissey-solo.com/threads/lp-laura-pergolizzi-and-morrissey-photos-9-total-lp-sings-on-two-tracks-morrissey-central.142896/|title=LP (Laura Pergolizzi) and Morrissey photos (9 total); LP sings on two tracks - Morrissey Central|work=Morrissey-solo|access-date=2018-10-22|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nOn June 6, 2019, Grey Daze, the old band of late [[Linkin Park]]'s singer [[Chester Bennington]], announced on their Instagram page that she had recorded some vocals for a song from their upcoming album which also features vocals from Chester.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/ByXDgm5ARk0/|title=Grey Daze on Instagram: \"We had an amazing time recording today and had a very special guest @iamlpofficial wow, she blew us away and we think everyone is going to\u2026\"|author=|date=|website=Instagram|access-date=June 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2019, the song \"Strange\" was featured on the commercial for the [[Samsung]] Galaxy phone. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://tvadvertsongs.com/samsung-its-your-galaxy/|title=TV Commercial Songs|author=|date=|website=|access-date=October 21, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Studio albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|+ List of studio albums, with selected chart positions\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:10em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:18em;\"| Album details\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"10\"| Peak chart positions\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2