er)|Luciana]]\n| Violent Lips\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Happening\"\n| rowspan=\"5\"| 2012\n| [[Chiddy Bang]]\n| EMI Records\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Hi-Roller Baby\"\n| [[Joe Walsh]]\n| ''[[Analog Man (album)|Analog Man]]''\n| Concord Music\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"[[Shine Ya Light]]\"\n| [[Rita Ora]]\n| ''[[Ora (Rita Ora album)|Ora]]''\n| Roc Nation\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"[[Lolita (The Veronicas song)|Lolita]]\" \n| [[The Veronicas]]\n| {{N/A|Non-album single}}\n| Sire Records\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Fingerprint\"\n| [[Leona Lewis]]\n| ''[[Glassheart]]''\n| Sony Music\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Red\"\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2013\n| rowspan=\"2\"| [[Cher]]\n| rowspan=\"2\"| ''[[Closer to the Truth (Cher album)|Closer to the Truth]]''\n| rowspan=\"2\"| Warner Bros.\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Pride\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Tidal Wave\" \n| rowspan=\"3\"| 2014\n| [[Karmin]]\n| ''[[Pulses (album)|Pulses]]''\n| rowspan=\"2\"| Epic\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Human\"\n| [[Cher Lloyd]]\n| ''[[Sorry I'm Late (Cher Lloyd album)|Sorry I'm Late]]''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Line of Fire\"\n| The Veronicas\n| ''[[The Veronicas (album)|The Veronicas]]''\n| Sony Music\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Mirror Man\"\n| 2015\n| [[Ella Henderson]]\n| ''[[Chapter One (Ella Henderson album)|Chapter One]]''\n| Syco\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Solo para ti\"\n| 2016\n| [[Cazzette]]\n| ''Desserts EP''\n| ICONS Music\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"I Better Love You\"\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2017\n| [[Will Heard]]\n| ''Trust EP''\n| Black Butter\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Miracle\"\n| [[Marina Kaye]]\n| ''Explicit''\n| Capitol Records\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Change My Mind\"\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2019\n| [[Celine Dion]]\n| ''Courage''\n| Columbia Records\n|}\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{notelist-ua}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.iamlp.com}}\n* [http://www.discogs.com/artist/L.P.+(3) LP] discography at [[Discogs]]\n\n{{LP}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:LP}}\n[[Category:American female rock singers]]\n[[Category:American female singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:American singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:American people of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American rock songwriters]]\n[[Category:American female guitarists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American guitarists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women singers]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Guitarists from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Singers from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:People from Long Island]]\n[[Category:Lesbian musicians]]\n[[Category:LGBT singers]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:1981 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2015}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = LP\n| background       = solo_singer\n| image            = LP WTMD LHCollins sms 06062014.jpg\n| caption          = LP performing at [[WTMD]]'s [[WTMD#First Thursday Concerts in the Park|First Thursday series]] in [[Canton, Baltimore]], [[Maryland]], in June 2014\n| birth_name       = Laura Pergolizzi\n| alias            = LP\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1981|3|18|df=y}}\n| birth_place      = [[Long Island]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S.\n| origin           = Long Island, New York, U.S.\n| genre            = {{flat list|\n*[[Indie rock]]\n*[[Rock music|pop rock]]\n*[[indie pop]]\n*[[alternative rock]] \n}}\n| occupation       = Singer-songwriter\n| instrument       = {{flat list|\n*[[Vocals]]\n*[[guitar]]\n*[[ukulele]]\n*[[harmonica]]\n}}\n| years_active     = 1998\u2013present\n| label            = [[Warner Bros. Records]]\n| associated_acts  = \n| website          = {{URL|iamlp.com}}\n| current_members  = \n| past_members     = \n}}\n\n'''Laura Pergolizzi''' (born March 18, 1981), known professionally as '''LP''', is an American singer and songwriter, best known for her single \"[[Lost on You]]\". She has released five albums and three [[extended plays|EPs]]. She has written songs for other artists including [[Cher]], [[Rihanna]], the [[Backstreet Boys]], [[Leona Lewis]], [[Myl\u00e8ne Farmer]], [[C\u00e9line Dion]] and [[Christina Aguilera]].<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop-shop/6106473/lp-forever-for-now-laura-pergolizzi |title=LP focuses on LP with First Album in a Decade |date=June 3, 2014 |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |last=Graff |first=Gary}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n===Early life and career===\nLaura Pergolizzi was born in 1981 on [[Long Island]],<ref name=\"iamlp bio\">{{cite web|url=https://iamlp.blog/bio/ |title=Bio |work=LP Blog Official|access-date=July 13, 2019}}</ref> to an [[Italians|Italian]] father and an [[Irish people|Irish]] mother, her paternal grandfather coming from [[Naples]] and grandmother from [[Palermo]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lastampa.it/2016/12/06/spettacoli/musica/nata-dai-locali-di-new-york-mi-nutro-di-pop-senza-confini-0kZU2XyphCkTAHxGs4w4lK/pagina.html |title=\"Nata dai locali di New York mi nutro di pop senza confini\" - La Stampa |website=Lastampa.it |date= |access-date=June 14, 2017}}</ref> Pergolizzi adopted the stage name \"LP\" after moving to [[New York City]].<ref name=\"thefreelibrary\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Not+a+tomboy+in+a+dress%3A+after+walking+away+from+a+contract+at+Island...-a0189051454 | title=Not a tomboy in a dress: after walking away from a contract at Island Records, lesbian rocker LP returns to her androgynous roots with her anticipated third album. |access-date=July 14, 2013 |publisher=thefreelibrary.com}}</ref> [[David Lowery (musician)|David Lowery]] of the band [[Cracker (band)|Cracker]] saw LP performing and featured her on \"Cinderella\", a hidden track on the band's 1998 album, ''[[Gentleman's Blues]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=News |url=http://www.lprock.com/news.html |publisher=lprock.com |access-date=November 15, 2013}}</ref> Lowery followed up by producing LP's debut album, ''[[Heart-Shaped Scar]]'', released in 2001 through [[Koch Records]].\n\nLP's second album, ''Suburban Sprawl & Alcohol'', was released in June 2004 through Lightswitch Records. On the record, she collaborated with songwriter and music producer [[Linda Perry]].<ref name=\"thefreelibrary\" /> However, in spite of extensive touring to promote the release and positive reviews from music critics, the album failed to gain widespread recognition.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.afterellen.com/archive/ellen/Music/102004/suburbansprawl.html |title=AfterEllen.com - Review of LP's Suburban Sprawl & Alcohol |last=Marti |first=Kris Scott |date=October 27, 2004 |website=afterellen.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070404014424/http://www.afterellen.com/archive/ellen/Music/102004/suburbansprawl.html |archive-date=April 4, 2007 |access-date=April 5, 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===2006\u20132010===\nIn 2006, LP appeared at the music conference [[South by Southwest]] and reportedly sparked a bidding war amongst major music labels, eventually being signed by [[L.A. Reid]] to his [[Island Def Jam Music Group]] record label, part of the [[Universal Music Group]]. However, due to artistic differences LP left the contract. She signed with [[SoBe Entertainment]] in 2007, an independent record label, with the album tracks she had written at the major label.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bio: Who is LP?|url=http://www.lprock.com/bio.html |publisher=lprock.com}}</ref> \"Love Will Keep You Up All Night\", one of the tracks she had written at Island Def Jam Music Group with Billy Mann, was released in late 2007 on the [[Backstreet Boys]] album, ''[[Unbreakable (Backstreet Boys album)|Unbreakable]]''. LP wrote and performed \"Wasted\", from her album ''Suburban Sprawl & Alcohol'', which was the theme song for a television show, ''[[South of Nowhere]]'', on [[The N]], currently known as TeenNick. [[MTV]]'s ''[[The Hills (TV series)|The Hills]]'' also featured LP's song \"Damage Is Done\" in mid-2010, and it was released on [[iTunes]].\n\nDuring 2009, LP started writing songs for other artists, including several songs which ended up on [[Heidi Montag]]'s album, ''[[Superficial (album)|Superficial]]'' (Warner Music).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metroguiltypleasures.com/metro/laura-pergolizzi-on-sexuality-and-the-highs-and-lows-of-the-music-biz/ |title=Laura Pergolizzi Q&A on sexuality and the music biz |last=Harmsworth |first=Andrei |date=April 23, 2017 |website=www.metroguiltypleasures.com |publisher=Guilty Pleasures |access-date=May 4, 2017 |quote=You've also written for an eclectic mix of artists, from Rihanna to Heidi Montag. How did that come about?<br>No offence to Heidi, she's lovely, but I didn't write with her. A few of the songs I had, she just cut.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.idolator.com/7351112/heidi-montag-superficial-defense |title=In Defense Of Heidi Montag's 'Superficial'  |last=Lansky |first=Sam |date=September 28, 2012 |website=www.idolator.com |publisher=[[Idolator (website)|Idolator]] |access-date=May 4, 2017 |quote=Contributors to the album include The Runners (Rihanna, Cher Lloyd), Kool Kojak (Ke$ha, One Direction), Steve Morales (Enrique Iglesias, Celine Dion), Stacy Barthe (Katy Perry, Brandy), Chris Rojas (Pink, Sophie Ellis-Bextor) and Laura Pergolizzi (Christina Aguilera, Rita Ora).}}</ref> LP co-wrote the single, \"[[More Is More]]\", as well as the album tracks, \"Twisted\", \"Hey Boy\" and \"Love It or Leave It\". She also co-wrote other tracks for and with Montag, such as the [[Cathy Dennis]] co-written, \"Look How I'm Doin'\", \"I Do This\" and \"Who's That Girl\". A song LP wrote with [[Alexander Kronlund]], \"Standing Where You Left Me\", was released on [[Erik Hassle]]'s debut UK album, ''[[Pieces (Erik Hassle album)|Pieces]]'' (Roxy/EMI/Universal). LP moved to [[Los Angeles]] in 2010.<ref name=\"cnn\">{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2012/04/24/showbiz/lp-into-the-wild-music/index.html |title=Songwriter LP goes into the wild -- as a singer |last=Gumbrecht |first=Jamie |work=[[CNN]] |date=April 24, 2012 |accessdate=July 14, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===2011\u20132012===\nIn August 2010, it was announced that LP had signed with [[RedOne]]'s record label, [[2101 Records]]. LP landed her first major breakthrough as a songwriter, co-writing [[Rihanna|Rihanna's]] song, \"[[Cheers (Drink to That)]]\", featured on Rihanna's fifth studio album ''[[Loud (Rihanna album)|Loud]]'', released on November 12, 2010, on Def Jam Recordings. \"[[Cheers (Drink to That)|Cheers]]\" features a vocal hook performed by LP (taken from [[Avril Lavigne]]'s \"[[I'm with You (Avril Lavigne song)|I'm with You]]\"). In a 2010 interview with [[MTV News]], Rihanna said: \"I love that song (\"Cheers\"). That is one of my favorite songs on the album. It makes you feel like celebrating. It gives you a great feeling inside like you want to go out and have a drink. ... People can't wait for the weekend.\"<ref name=\"mtv news\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1652434/rihanna-glad-avril-lavigne-appears-on-louds-cheers.jhtml |title=Rihanna Glad Avril Lavigne Appears On Loud's 'Cheers' |last=Vena |first=Jocelyn |publisher=MTV |date=November 17, 2010 |accessdate=July 14, 2013}}</ref> LP's major label songwriting breakthroughs continued, as she co-wrote \"Beautiful People\", performed by [[Christina Aguilera]]. The song is featured on the ''[[Burlesque (soundtrack)|Burlesque: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack]]'' album, which was released on November 22, 2010 through [[RCA Records]].\n\nIn June 2011, LP co-wrote \"[[Afraid to Sleep]]\", which was performed by NBC's ''[[The Voice (TV series)|The Voice]]'' finalist [[Vicci Martinez]] and reached #10 on the iTunes Top Singles Chart. In September 2011, LP signed a deal with [[Warner Bros. Records]]. Shortly after, \"[[Into the Wild (song)|Into the Wild]]\", written and performed by LP, was prominently used in a [[Citibank]] national television advertisement campaign. In April 2012, LP released her first major label album, ''[[Into the Wild: Live at EastWest Studios]]'', a five-song live [[extended play]], and started touring extensively including festivals such as [[SXSW]], [[Bonnaroo]], [[Lollapalooza]], [[Bumbershoot]], [[Tropfest]] as well as [[Tokyo]]'s Sonic Boom and [[London]]'s Hyde Park. In 2012, she became the first female [[Martin Guitar]] ambassador.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iamlp.com/blog/martin-guitar-ambassador |title=Martin Guitar Ambassador |publisher=iamlp.com |date=May 10, 2012 |accessdate=July 14, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130906123851/http://www.iamlp.com/blog/martin-guitar-ambassador |archivedate=September 6, 2013 }}</ref>\n\n===2013\u2013present===\n[[File:LP (singer songwriter) (ZMF 2018) jm76932.jpg|thumb|LP at the [[Zelt-Musik-Festival]] 2018 in [[Freiburg]], [[Germany]]]]\nIn May 2012, LP was featured as the Artist of the Week in ''[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]'' magazine. Over the following two years, she completed the recording of her album that included collaborations with [[Billy Steinberg]], [[Isabella Summers|Isabella \"Machine\" Summers]] (from [[Florence and the Machine]]), [[Josh Alexander]], Claude Kelly, Justyn Pilbrow, Carl Ryden and Rob Kleiner.<ref>[http://www.discogs.com/LP-Forever-For-Now/release/5765341 Listing] of the ''Forever for Now'' album on Discogs.com, (accessed March 7, 2015).</ref> The album was produced by [[Rob Cavallo]], Warner Bros. Records' chairman and producer. On April 1, 2014, it was announced that LP's third full-length studio album would be titled ''[[Forever for Now (LP album)|Forever for Now]]'' and was scheduled to be released on June 3, 2014. The album was promoted by the lead single \"Night Like This\".<ref name=\":0\" /> Following the album, a second single, \"Someday\", was released in June 2014 in Canada.<ref name=\"Someday\"/> On September 16, 2014, a music video for \"Tokyo Sunrise\" officially premiered on ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine's website.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://time.com/3387757/lp-tokyo-sunrise-video-premiere/ |title=Catch a 'Tokyo Sunrise' With LP and Her New Video: Premiere |work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |first=Nolan |last=Feeney |accessdate=September 16, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2015, the song \"Muddy Waters\" was released as the first single from LP's fourth studio album [[Lost on You (album)|''Lost on You'']].<ref name=\"Muddy Waters\"/><ref name=\"Lost on You CoS\"/> In November 2015 one of LP's best known songs, [[Lost on You]] was released to great success.\n\nIn June 2016, the song featured in the violent and emotionally charged closing scene of the season four finale of [[Netflix]]'s original series ''[[Orange Is The New Black]]''. It was also featured in the trailer for the [[NBC]] show ''[[Shades of Blue (TV series)|Shades of Blue]]. \"Muddy Waters\"'' clarifies the ending of season 5 episode 4 of [[Starz]] [[Power (TV series)|Power]], as the layers of uncertainty and drama are revisited. In November, the album's [[Lost on You|eponymous second single]] was released, while LP held a residency at the No Vacancy club.<ref>{{cite web|title = LP's New Tune \"Muddy Waters\" Is a Sultry Prowl of a Song|url = http://noisey.vice.com/blog/premiere-lp-muddy-waters|website = NOISEY|accessdate = December 13, 2015}}</ref> Both songs originate from a collaboration with [[Mike Del Rio]]. An EP<ref name=\"Lost on You CoS\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.interviewmagazine.com/music/lp/#_|title=LP After the Storm|last=Rosenzweig|first=Mathias|date=March 2, 2016|website=Interview Magazine|access-date=April 5, 2016}}</ref> titled ''Death Valley'' was released on June 17, 2016.\n\nThe song \"Hi Ho Nobody Home\" by [[David Baerwald]] featuring LP was used in an episode of [[Mr. Mercedes (TV series)|Mr. Mercedes]].\nIn 2017 she performed the song \"Back Where I Belong\" ([[Otto Knows]] featuring [[Avicii]]) for the episode 5 (second season) of the [[Netflix]]'s  original series ''[[Sense8]]''.\n\nLP duets with [[Myl\u00e8ne Farmer]] on the single ''N'oublie pas'', released on June 22. The single immediately hit number 1 on the French [[iTunes]] chart upon release.<ref>https://instagram.com/p/BkU4lvol8BJ/</ref> The track is the second single from Farmer's upcoming studio album ''D\u00e9sob\u00e9issance''.\n\nOn June 15, 2018, LP announced on her Facebook page that she had been working on a new album.<ref name=\"Facebook 'Girls Go Wild'\">{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/iamLP/videos/490100428128322/|title='Girls Gone Wild' Facebook Post|date=15 August 2018|publisher=[[Facebook]]|access-date=August 18, 2018}}</ref>  A day later, the first track from the record, \"Girls Go Wild\" was released.<ref name=\"Billboard\">{{cite web |last=Bote |first=Joshua |title=LP Announces New Album, Shares New Single 'Girls Go Wild': Watch |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/pride/8470816/lp-new-album-single-girls-go-wild |website=Billboard |access-date=August 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2018 she recorded two songs for the singer [[Morrissey]] for his new album of cover songs.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.morrissey-solo.com/threads/lp-laura-pergolizzi-and-morrissey-photos-9-total-lp-sings-on-two-tracks-morrissey-central.142896/|title=LP (Laura Pergolizzi) and Morrissey photos (9 total); LP sings on two tracks - Morrissey Central|work=Morrissey-solo|access-date=2018-10-22|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nOn June 6, 2019, Grey Daze, the old band of late [[Linkin Park]]'s singer [[Chester Bennington]], announced on their Instagram page that she had recorded some vocals for a song from their upcoming album which also features vocals from Chester.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/ByXDgm5ARk0/|title=Grey Daze on Instagram: \"We had an amazing time recording today and had a very special guest @iamlpofficial wow, she blew us away and we think everyone is going to\u2026\"|author=|date=|website=Instagram|access-date=June 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2019, the song \"Strange\" was featured on the commercial for the [[Samsung]] Galaxy phone. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://tvadvertsongs.com/samsung-its-your-galaxy/|title=TV Commercial Songs|author=|date=|website=|access-date=October 21, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Studio albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|+ List of studio albums, with selected chart positions\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:10em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:18em;\"| Album details\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"10\"| Peak chart positions\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:10em;\"| Sales\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:13em;\"| Certifications\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\"| [[Billboard 200|US]]<br><ref name=\"BillboardLP\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/LP/chart-history/billboard-200|title=LP Chart History: Billboard 200|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=December 19, 2018}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\"| [[Top Heatseekers|US<br>Heat]]<br><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/LP/chart-history/heatseekers-albums|title=LP Chart History: Heatseekers Albums|work=Billboard|accessdate=December 19, 2018}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\"| [[\u00d63 Austria Top 40|AUT]]<br><ref>{{cite web|url=http://oe3.orf.at/charts/stories/2602614/ |title=\u00d63 Austria Top40: Longplay-Charts - \u00d63 Charts |website=Oe3.orf.at |date= |accessdate=2017-06-14}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\"| [[Ultratop|BEL<br>(Wa)]]<br><ref name=\"WA\"/>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\"| [[Syndicat National de l'\u00c9dition Phonographique|FRA]]<br><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.snepmusique.com/tops-semaine/top-albums-fusionnes/?ye=2016&we=50|title=Le Top de la semaine : Top Albums Fusionnes - SNEP (Week 50, 2016)|publisher=[[Syndicat National de l'\u00c9dition Phonographique]]|language=French|accessdate=December 20, 2016}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\"| [[Federazione Industria Musicale Italiana|ITA]]<br><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fimi.it/classifiche#/category:album/id:2388|title=Album \u2013 Classifica settimanale WK 50 (dal 2016-12-09 al 2016-12-15)|publisher=[[Federazione Industria Musicale Italiana]]|language=Italian|accessdate=December 20, 2016}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\"| [[OLiS|POL]]<br><ref name=\"POL\">Peak chart positions for studio albums in Poland:\n* ''Death Valley'': {{cite web|url=http://olis.onyx.pl/listy/index.asp?idlisty=1044&lang=en|title=OLiS \u2013 sales for the period 16.09.2016 \u2013 22.09.2016|publisher=[[OLiS]]|accessdate=September 29, 2016}}\n* ''Lost on You'': {{cite web|url=http://olis.onyx.pl/listy/index.asp?idlisty=1066&lang=en|title=OLiS \u2013 sales for the period 27.01.2017 \u2013 02.02.2017|work=[[OLiS]]|publisher=[[Polish Society of the Phonographic Industry|ZPAV]]|accessdate=February 9, 2017}}\n* ''Heart to Mouth'': {{cite web|url=http://olis.onyx.pl/listy/index.asp?idlisty=1178&lang=en|title=OLiS \u2013 sales for the period 07.12.2018 \u2013 13.12.2018|work=[[OLiS]]|publisher=[[Polish Society of the Phonographic Industry|ZPAV]]|accessdate=December 20, 2018}}</ref>\n!scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\"| [[Productores de M\u00fasica de Espa\u00f1a|SPA]]<br><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.promusicae.es/listas/semana/3303-%C3%81lbumes-semana-50-2016|title=TOP 100 ALBUMES \u2014 SEMANA 50: del 09.12.2016 al 15.12.2016|publisher=[[Productores de M\u00fasica de Espa\u00f1a]]|language=Spanish|accessdate=December 21, 2016}}</ref>\n!scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\"| [[Swiss Hitparade|SWI]]<br><ref name=\"SWI\">{{cite web|url=http://hitparade.ch/showinterpret.asp?interpret=LP|title=Discographie LP \u2013 hitparade.ch|publisher=Hung Medien|accessdate=August 29, 2016}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\"| [[UK Independent Singles and Albums Charts|UK<br>Indie]]<br><ref>Peak positions for UK Independent Albums Chart:\n* For \"Lost on You\": {{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/charts/independent-albums-chart/20170512/131/|title=Official Independent Singles Chart Top 50 \u2013 12 May 2017 \u2014 18 May 2017|publisher=Official Charts Company|accessdate=September 20, 2019}}\n* For \"Heart to Mouth\": {{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/charts/independent-albums-chart/20181214/131/|title=Official Independent Singles Chart Top 50 \u2013 14 December 2018 \u2014 20 December 2018|publisher=Official Charts Company|accessdate=September 20, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Heart-Shaped Scar]]''\n|\n* Released: 2001\n* Formats: [[Compact disc|CD]], [[music download|digital download]]\n* Label: [[Koch Records|Koch]]<ref name=\"thefreelibrary\" />\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''Suburban Sprawl & Alcohol''\n|\n* Released: June 29, 2004\n* Label: Lightswitch\n* Formats: CD, digital download\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"|''[[Forever for Now (LP album)|Forever for Now]]''\n|\n* Released: June 2, 2014\n* Label: [[Warner Bros. Records|Warner Bros.]]\n* Format: CD, [[LP record|LP]], digital download\n| 132 || 2 || \u2014 || 73 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|\n* US: 16,000{{efn|group=upper-alpha|United States sales figures for ''Forever for Now'' as of September 2016.<ref name=\"Sales\">{{cite web | url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7518840/lp-lost-on-you-finds-greece-success-europe-shazam |title=LP's 'Lost on You' Finds Unexpected Success in