lla Henderson]]\n| ''[[Chapter One (Ella Henderson album)|Chapter One]]''\n| Syco\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Solo para ti\"\n| 2016\n| [[Cazzette]]\n| ''Desserts EP''\n| ICONS Music\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"I Better Love You\"\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2017\n| [[Will Heard]]\n| ''Trust EP''\n| Black Butter\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Miracle\"\n| [[Marina Kaye]]\n| ''Explicit''\n| Capitol Records\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Change My Mind\"\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2019\n| [[Celine Dion]]\n| ''Courage''\n| Columbia Records\n|}\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{notelist-ua}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.iamlp.com}}\n* [http://www.discogs.com/artist/L.P.+(3) LP] discography at [[Discogs]]\n\n{{LP}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:LP}}\n[[Category:American female rock singers]]\n[[Category:American female singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:American singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:American people of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American rock songwriters]]\n[[Category:American female guitarists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American guitarists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Guitarists from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Singers from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:People from Long Island]]\n[[Category:Lesbian musicians]]\n[[Category:LGBT singers]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women singers]]\n[[Category:1981 births]]\n", "name_user": "Freddiem", "label": "safe", "comment": "grouped with other \"21st-century\" categories", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/LP_(singer)"}
{"title_page": "1091", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2011}}\n{{Year dab|1091}}\n{{Year nav|1091}}\n{{C11 year in topic}} \n[[File:Roger I of Sicily (Troina).jpg|thumb|right|[[Roger I of Sicily]] (r. 1071\u20131101)]]\nYear '''1091''' ('''[[Roman numerals|MXCI]]''') was a [[common year starting on Wednesday]] (link will display the full calendar) of the [[Julian calendar]].\n\n== Events ==\n<onlyinclude>\n\n=== By place ===\n\n==== Byzantine Empire ====\n* Spring &ndash; [[Tzachas]], a Seljuk Turkish military commander, establishes an independent maritime state centred in the [[Ionia]]n coastal city of [[Smyrna]] (modern-day [[\u0130zmir]]). He proclaims himself emperor (''[[basileus]]''), and concludes an alliance with the [[Pechenegs]] in [[Thrace (theme)|Thrace]]. Tzachas uses his fleet to blockade [[Constantinople]] by sea, while the Pechenegs besiege the capital by land.<ref>Brian Todd Carey (2012). ''Road to Manzikert: Byzantine and Islamic Warfare (527\u20131071)'', p. 160. {{ISBN|978-1-84884-215-1}}.</ref>\n* [[April 29]] &ndash; [[Battle of Levounion]]: Emperor [[Alexios I Komnenos|Alexios I]] supported by his allies defeats the Pechenegs' 80,000 men (including women and children) at the [[Maritsa|Evros River]] near [[Enez|Enos]] (modern [[Turkey]]). The [[Cumans]] and Byzantine forces fall upon the enemy camp, slaughtering all in their path. The Pechenegs are butchered so savagely, that they are almost wiped out.\n\n==== Europe ====\n* Spring &ndash; King [[Stephen II of Croatia|Stephen II]], the last member of the [[Trpimirovi\u0107 dynasty|Trpimirovi\u0107 Dynasty]], dies without leaving an heir after a 2-year reign. War and unrest breaks out in [[Kingdom of Croatia (925\u20131102)|Croatia]] afterwards. King [[Ladislaus I of Hungary|Ladislaus I]] of [[Kingdom of Hungary|Hungary]], on instigation of his sister, Queen [[Helena of Hungary, Queen of Croatia|Helena]], intervenes in the conflict and occupies Croatia. He proclaims himself king, but is contested by the Croatian nobleman [[Petar Sna\u010di\u0107]].\n* February &ndash; [[Norman conquest of southern Italy|Norman conquest of Sicily]]: The [[Normans]] conquer [[Noto]] and complete the 30-year-long conquest of [[Sicily]] from the Moorish rulers. Duke [[Roger Borsa]] (a son of [[Robert Guiscard]]) surrenders his share in the castles of [[Calabria]], and receives his inheritance of [[Palermo]]. He grants charters to various towns and encourages [[urban planning]] in [[County of Apulia and Calabria|Apulia and Calabria]]. \n* Summer &ndash; The [[Norman invasion of Malta]]: A Norman fleet led by Count [[Roger I of Sicily|Roger I]] ('''Bosso''') arrives in [[Malta]]. Roger disembarks his army, and besieges the island's capital Medina (modern-day [[Mdina]]). The inhabitants negotiate peace terms (by promising paying an annual [[tribute]]) and swear an oath of loyalty to Roger. On the way back, the Normans sack the island [[Gozo]].\n* July &ndash; The [[Abbadid dynasty|Abbadid Dynasty]] ruling in [[Al-Andalus]] (modern [[Spain]]) falls, when the [[Almoravid dynasty|Almoravid]] forces storm [[Seville]]. Confronted with this threat, Emir [[Taifa of Badajoz#Emirs of Badajoz|Muhammad ibn Abu Bakr Muhammad al-Aftas]] of [[Badajoz]] obtains the support of King [[Alfonso VI of Le\u00f3n and Castile|Alfonso VI]] ('''the Brave''') of [[Kingdom of Castile|Castile]], in exchange for the Moorish positions on the [[Tagus|Tagus River]] ([[Sintra]], [[Santar\u00e9m, Portugal|Santar\u00e9m]] and [[Lisbon]]).<ref name=picard2000>{{cite book|last=Picard|first=Christophe|title=Le Portugal musulman (VIIIe-XIIIe si\u00e8cle. L'Occident d'al-Andalus sous domination islamique|year=2000|publisher=Maisonneuve & Larose|location=Paris|isbn=2-7068-1398-9|page=109}}</ref>\n\n==== England ====\n* Spring &ndash; King [[William II of England|William II]] invades [[Duchy of Normandy|Normandy]] with a large army. His brothers, [[Henry I of England|Henry]] and [[Robert Curthose]], mobilizes mercenary forces to resist William during the siege at [[Mont-Saint-Michel]]. Henry is forced to surrender his estates of the [[Cotentin Peninsula]] in Normandy and signs a peace treaty.\n* Summer &ndash; King [[Malcolm III of Scotland|Malcolm III]] of [[Kingdom of Scotland|Scotland]] invades the north of [[Kingdom of England|England]], and besieges [[Durham, England|Durham]]. The Normans led by William II marches north to oppose the Scots, but a conflict is averted. Malcolm is forced to accept the terms of the [[Treaty of Abernethy]] (see [[1072]]) and pays [[Homage (feudal)|homage]] to William.\n* [[Cardiff Castle]] is constructed by [[Robert Fitzhamon]], Norman lord of [[Feudal barony of Gloucester|Gloucester]] (approximate date).\n\n=== By topic ===\n\n==== Disasters ====\n* [[October 17]] &ndash; [[London tornado of 1091|London tornado]]: A [[TORRO scale|T8 tornado]] (roughly equal to an [[Fujita scale|T4 tornado]]) occurs in [[London]]. The wooden [[London Bridge]] is demolished and the church of [[St Mary-le-Bow|St. Mary-le-Bow]] is badly damaged.\n\n==== Religion ====\n* December &ndash; [[Athanasius VI bar Khamoro]] becomes (against his will) patriarch and head of the [[Syriac Orthodox Church]] in [[Antioch]] (until [[1129]]).\n</onlyinclude>\n\n== Births ==\n* [[September 18]] &ndash; [[Andronikos Komnenos (son of Alexios I)|Andronikos Komnenos]], Byzantine prince and general\n* [[December 22]] &ndash; [[Jutta von Sponheim]], German [[abbess]] (d. [[1136]])\n* [[Hongzhi Zhengjue]], Chinese [[Chan Buddhism|Chan]] [[Chinese Buddhism|Buddhist]] monk and writer (d. [[1157]])\n* [[Matilda, Countess of Rethel|Matilda of Rethel]], French [[Nobility|noblewoman]] and sovereign (d. [[1151]])\n* [[Wartislaw I, Duke of Pomerania|Wartislaw I]] (or '''Warcis\u0142aw'''), duke of  [[Duchy of Pomerania|Pomerania]] (approximate date)\n\n== Deaths ==\n* [[March 26]] &ndash; [[Wallada bint al-Mustakfi]], Andalusian female [[poet]] (b. [[994]])\n* [[June 17]] &ndash; [[Dirk V, Count of Holland|Dirk V]], count of [[County of Holland|Friesland]] (west of the [[Vlie]]) (b. [[1052]])\n* [[June 29]] &ndash; [[Frederick of Montb\u00e9liard]], margrave of [[March of Turin|Turin]]\n* [[July 5]] &ndash; [[William of Hirsau]], German [[abbot]] and music theorist \n* [[August 8]] &ndash; [[Altmann, Bishop of Passau|Altmann of Passau]], German bishop and saint \n* [[August 25]] &ndash; [[Sisnando Davides]], Mozarab military leader\n* [[December 19]] \n** [[Adelaide of Susa]], margravine of Turin\n** [[Fujiwara no Tadaie]], Japanese statesman (b. [[1033]])\n* [[Fu Yaoyu]], Chinese government official and politician (b. [[1024]])\n* [[Helena of Hungary, Queen of Croatia|Helena of Hungary]], queen of [[Kingdom of Croatia (925\u20131102)|Croatia]] (approximate date)\n* [[Jordan I of Capua|Jordan I]] (or '''Giordano'''), Italo-Norman prince of [[Principality of Capua|Capua]]\n* [[Mac meic Aedh Ua Flaithbheartaigh]], king of [[Iar Connacht]]\n* [[Robert D'Oyly]], Norman nobleman (approximate date)\n* [[Stephen II of Croatia|Stephen II]] (or '''Stjepan'''), king of Croatia (approximate date)\n* [[Wolfhelm of Brauweiler]], German [[Benedictines|Benedictine]] abbot\n* [[Artuk Bey|Zaheer-ul-Daulah Artuk Beg]], Seljuk general and governor\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1091}}\n[[Category:1091| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2011}}\n{{Year dab|1091}}\n{{Year nav|1091}}\n{{C11 year in topic}} \n[[File:Roger I of Sicily (Troina).jpg|{{Largethumb}}|right|[[Roger I of Sicily]] (r. 1071\u20131101)]]\nYear '''1091''' ('''[[Roman numerals|MXCI]]''') was a [[common year starting on Wednesday]] (link will display the full calendar) of the [[Julian calendar]].\n\n== Events ==\n<onlyinclude>\n\n=== By place ===\n\n==== Byzantine Empire ====\n* Spring &ndash; [[Tzachas]], a Seljuk Turkish military commander, establishes an independent maritime state centred in the [[Ionia]]n coastal city of [[Smyrna]] (modern-day [[\u0130zmir]]). He proclaims himself emperor (''[[basileus]]''), and concludes an alliance with the [[Pechenegs]] in [[Thrace (theme)|Thrace]]. Tzachas uses his fleet to blockade [[Constantinople]] by sea, while the Pechenegs besiege the capital by land.<ref>Brian Todd Carey (2012). ''Road to Manzikert: Byzantine and Islamic Warfare (527\u20131071)'', p. 160. {{ISBN|978-1-84884-215-1}}.</ref>\n* [[April 29]] &ndash; [[Battle of Levounion]]: Emperor [[Alexios I Komnenos|Alexios I]] supported by his allies defeats the Pechenegs' 80,000 men (including women and children) at the [[Maritsa|Evros River]] near [[Enez|Enos]] (modern [[Turkey]]). The [[Cumans]] and Byzantine forces fall upon the enemy camp, slaughtering all in their path. The Pechenegs are butchered so savagely, that they are almost wiped out.\n\n==== Europe ====\n* Spring &ndash; King [[Stephen II of Croatia|Stephen II]], the last member of the [[Trpimirovi\u0107 dynasty|Trpimirovi\u0107 Dynasty]], dies without leaving an heir after a 2-year reign. War and unrest breaks out in [[Kingdom of Croatia (925\u20131102)|Croatia]] afterwards. King [[Ladislaus I of Hungary|Ladislaus I]] of [[Kingdom of Hungary|Hungary]], on instigation of his sister, Queen [[Helena of Hungary, Queen of Croatia|Helena]], intervenes in the conflict and occupies Croatia. He proclaims himself king, but is contested by the Croatian nobleman [[Petar Sna\u010di\u0107]].\n* February &ndash; [[Norman conquest of southern Italy|Norman conquest of Sicily]]: The [[Normans]] conquer [[Noto]] and complete the 30-year-long conquest of [[Sicily]] from the Moorish rulers. Duke [[Roger Borsa]] (a son of [[Robert Guiscard]]) surrenders his share in the castles of [[Calabria]], and receives his inheritance of [[Palermo]]. He grants charters to various towns and encourages [[urban planning]] in [[County of Apulia and Calabria|Apulia and Calabria]]. \n* Summer &ndash; The [[Norman invasion of Malta]]: A Norman fleet led by Count [[Roger I of Sicily|Roger I]] ('''Bosso''') arrives in [[Malta]]. Roger disembarks his army, and besieges the island's capital Medina (modern-day [[Mdina]]). The inhabitants negotiate peace terms (by promising paying an annual [[tribute]]) and swear an oath of loyalty to Roger. On the way back, the Normans sack the island [[Gozo]].\n* July &ndash; The [[Abbadid dynasty|Abbadid Dynasty]] ruling in [[Al-Andalus]] (modern [[Spain]]) falls, when the [[Almoravid dynasty|Almoravid]] forces storm [[Seville]]. Confronted with this threat, Emir [[Taifa of Badajoz#Emirs of Badajoz|Muhammad ibn Abu Bakr Muhammad al-Aftas]] of [[Badajoz]] obtains the support of King [[Alfonso VI of Le\u00f3n and Castile|Alfonso VI]] ('''the Brave''') of [[Kingdom of Castile|Castile]], in exchange for the Moorish positions on the [[Tagus|Tagus River]] ([[Sintra]], [[Santar\u00e9m, Portugal|Santar\u00e9m]] and [[Lisbon]]).<ref name=picard2000>{{cite book|last=Picard|first=Christophe|title=Le Portugal musulman (VIIIe-XIIIe si\u00e8cle. L'Occident d'al-Andalus sous domination islamique|year=2000|publisher=Maisonneuve & Larose|location=Paris|isbn=2-7068-1398-9|page=109}}</ref>\n\n==== England ====\n* Spring &ndash; King [[William II of England|William II]] invades [[Duchy of Normandy|Normandy]] with a large army. His brothers, [[Henry I of England|Henry]] and [[Robert Curthose]], mobilizes mercenary forces to resist William during the siege at [[Mont-Saint-Michel]]. Henry is forced to surrender his estates of the [[Cotentin Peninsula]] in Normandy and signs a peace treaty.\n* Summer &ndash; King [[Malcolm III of Scotland|Malcolm III]] of [[Kingdom of Scotland|Scotland]] invades the north of [[Kingdom of England|England]], and besieges [[Durham, England|Durham]]. The Normans led by William II marches north to oppose the Scots, but a conflict is averted. Malcolm is forced to accept the terms of the [[Treaty of Abernethy]] (see [[1072]]) and pays [[Homage (feudal)|homage]] to William.\n* [[Cardiff Castle]] is constructed by [[Robert Fitzhamon]], Norman lord of [[Feudal barony of Gloucester|Gloucester]] (approximate date).\n\n=== By topic ===\n\n==== Disasters ====\n* [[October 17]] &ndash; [[London tornado of 1091|London tornado]]: A [[TORRO scale|T8 tornado]] (roughly equal to an [[Fujita scale|T4 tornado]]) occurs in [[London]]. The wooden [[London Bridge]] is demolished and the church of [[St Mary-le-Bow|St. Mary-le-Bow]] is badly damaged.\n\n==== Religion ====\n* December &ndash; [[Athanasius VI bar Khamoro]] becomes (against his will) patriarch and head of the [[Syriac Orthodox Church]] in [[Antioch]] (until [[1129]]).\n</onlyinclude>\n\n== Births ==\n* [[September 18]] &ndash; [[Andronikos Komnenos (son of Alexios I)|Andronikos Komnenos]], Byzantine prince and general\n* [[December 22]] &ndash; [[Jutta von Sponheim]], German [[abbess]] (d. [[1136]])\n* [[Hongzhi Zhengjue]], Chinese [[Chan Buddhism|Chan]] [[Chinese Buddhism|Buddhist]] monk and writer (d. [[1157]])\n* [[Matilda, Countess of Rethel|Matilda of Rethel]], French [[Nobility|noblewoman]] and sovereign (d. [[1151]])\n* [[Wartislaw I, Duke of Pomerania|Wartislaw I]] (or '''Warcis\u0142aw'''), duke of  [[Duchy of Pomerania|Pomerania]] (approximate date)\n\n== Deaths ==\n* [[March 26]] &ndash; [[Wallada bint al-Mustakfi]], Andalusian female [[poet]] (b. [[994]])\n* [[June 17]] &ndash; [[Dirk V, Count of Holland|Dirk V]], count of [[County of Holland|Friesland]] (west of the [[Vlie]]) (b. [[1052]])\n* [[June 29]] &ndash; [[Frederick of Montb\u00e9liard]], margrave of [[March of Turin|Turin]]\n* [[July 5]] &ndash; [[William of Hirsau]], German [[abbot]] and music theorist \n* [[August 8]] &ndash; [[Altmann, Bishop of Passau|Altmann of Passau]], German bishop and saint \n* [[August 25]] &ndash; [[Sisnando Davides]], Mozarab military leader\n* [[December 19]] \n** [[Adelaide of Susa]], margravine of Turin\n** [[Fujiwara no Tadaie]], Japanese statesman (b. [[1033]])\n* [[Fu Yaoyu]], Chinese government official and politician (b. [[1024]])\n* [[Helena of Hungary, Queen of Croatia|Helena of Hungary]], queen of [[Kingdom of Croatia (925\u20131102)|Croatia]] (approximate date)\n* [[Jordan I of Capua|Jordan I]] (or '''Giordano'''), Italo-Norman prince of [[Principality of Capua|Capua]]\n* [[Mac meic Aedh Ua Flaithbheartaigh]], king of [[Iar Connacht]]\n* [[Robert D'Oyly]], Norman nobleman (approximate date)\n* [[Stephen II of Croatia|Stephen II]] (or '''Stjepan'''), king of Croatia (approximate date)\n* [[Wolfhelm of Brauweiler]], German [[Benedictines|Benedictine]] abbot\n* [[Artuk Bey|Zaheer-ul-Daulah Artuk Beg]], Seljuk general and governor\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1091}}\n[[Category:1091| ]]\n", "name_user": "Xwejnusgozo", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1091"}
{"title_page": "Business consultant", "text_new": "A '''business consultant''' (from [[Latin]] ''consultare'', \"to discuss\") is a Abraham Frempong who provides professional or expert advice<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/consultant |title=Consultant &#124; Define Consultant at Dictionary.com |publisher=Dictionary.reference.com |date=2004-03-09 |accessdate=2014-07-20}}</ref> in a particular area such as security ([[information security|electronic]] or [[physical security|physical]]), [[management]], [[accountancy]], [[law]], [[human resources]], [[marketing]] (and [[public relations]]), [[finance]], [[engineering]], [[science]] or any of many other specialized fields.\n\nA consultant is usually an expert or a professional in a specific field and has a wide area of knowledge in a specific subject. Consultants can save their clients time, increase revenue, and maintain resources. <ref>Pieter P. Tordoir (1995). ''The professional knowledge economy: the management and integration services in business organizations.'' p.140.</ref> The role of a consultant outside the medical sphere (where the term is used specifically for a grade of doctor) can fall under one of two general categories:\n* Internal consultant \u2013 someone who operates within an organization but is available to be consulted on areas of specialism by other departments or individuals (acting as clients); or\n* External consultant \u2013 someone who is employed externally (either by a firm or some other agency) whose expertise is provided on a temporary basis, usually for a fee.  As such this type of consultant generally engages with multiple and changing clients.\n\nThe overall impact of a consultant is that clients have access to deeper levels of expertise than would be feasible for them to retain in-house, and may purchase only as much service from the outside consultant as desired.\n\n== References ==\n{{Wiktionary|consultant|consulting}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n{{Reflist}}[https://www.janblaghy.ir/%D9%85%D8%B4%D8%A7%D9%88%D8%B1%D9%87-%DA%A9%D8%A7%D8%B1-%D9%88-%DA%A9%D8%B3%D8%A8/ Business Consultants]\n\n<!--==External links==\nPlease do not add consultant agencies or blogs of individual consultants -->\n\n{{Consulting}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Consulting occupations]]\n[[Category:Business occupations]]\n[[Category:Management occupations]]\n", "text_old": "A '''business consultant''' (from [[Latin]] ''consultare'', \"to discuss\") is a [[professional]] who provides professional or expert advice<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/consultant |title=Consultant &#124; Define Consultant at Dictionary.com |publisher=Dictionary.reference.com |date=2004-03-09 |accessdate=2014-07-20}}</ref> in a particular area such as security ([[information security|electronic]] or [[physical security|physical]]), [[management]], [[accountancy]], [[law]], [[human resources]], [[marketing]] (and [[public relations]]), [[finance]], [[engineering]], [[science]] or any of many other specialized fields.\n\nA consultant is usually an expert or a professional in a specific field and has a wide area of knowledge in a specific subject. Consultants can save their clients time, increase revenue, and maintain resources. <ref>Pieter P. Tordoir (1995). ''The professional knowledge economy: the management and integration services in business organizations.'' p.140.</ref> The role of a consultant outside the medical sphere (where the term is used specifically for a grade of doctor) can fall under one of two general categories:\n* Internal consultant \u2013 someone who operates within an organization but is available to be consulted on areas of specialism by other departments or individuals (acting as clients); or\n* External consultant \u2013 someone who is employed externally (either by a firm or some other agency) whose expertise is provided on a temporary basis, usually for a fee.  As such this type of consultant generally engages with multiple and changing clients.\n\nThe overall impact of a consultant is that clients have access to deeper levels of expertise than would be feasible for them to retain in-house, and may purchase only as much service from the outside consultant as desired. \n\n== References ==\n{{Wiktionary|consultant|consulting}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n<!--==External links==\nPlease do not add consultant agencies or blogs of individual consultants -->\n\n{{Consulting}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Consulting occupations]]\n[[Category:Business occupations]]\n[[Category:Management occupations]]\n", "name_user": "Maharba10", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Business_consultant"}
